"use strict";(globalThis.webpackChunkmy_blog=globalThis.webpackChunkmy_blog||[]).push([[5418],{10930(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"/OrchestrationBench","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/OrchestrationBench","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2026-02-04-OrchestrationBench/2026-02-04-OrchestrationBench.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-02-04-OrchestrationBench/2026-02-04-OrchestrationBench.md","title":"[\ub17c\ubb38 \ub9ac\ubdf0] OrchestrationBench: LLM-Driven Agentic Planning and Tool Use in Multi-Domain Scenarios","description":"LLM-Driven Agentic Planning and Tool Use in Multi-Domain Scenarios \ub17c\ubb38 \ub9ac\ubdf0","date":"2026-02-04T14:57:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Paper Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/paper-review"},{"inline":true,"label":"LLM","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/llm"},{"inline":true,"label":"Agent","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/agent"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"[\ub17c\ubb38 \ub9ac\ubdf0] OrchestrationBench: LLM-Driven Agentic Planning and Tool Use in Multi-Domain Scenarios","date":"2026-02-04 14:57","authors":"teddygood","tags":["Paper Review","LLM","Agent"],"slug":"/OrchestrationBench","description":"LLM-Driven Agentic Planning and Tool Use in Multi-Domain Scenarios \ub17c\ubb38 \ub9ac\ubdf0","keywords":["orchestration","agent","llm","benchmark","planning"]},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Why Linked Lists Are Rarely Used in Python","permalink":"/en/blog/Linked-List"}},"content":"> ICLR 2026. [[Paper](https://openreview.net/forum?id=Oljnxmf4pc&noteId=NyL52JeO4j)] [[Github](https://github.com/kakao/OrchestrationBench)]  \\n\\n\\n## \ub4e4\uc5b4\uac00\uba70\\n\\n\ucd5c\uadfc moltbot(\ud604 openclaw), oh-my-opencode\uc640 \uac19\uc740 \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4\uac00 \ud56b\ud574\uc9c0\uba74\uc11c \uc77d\uc73c\uba74 \uc7ac\ubc0c\uc744 \uac83 \uac19\ub2e4\ub294 \uc0dd\uac01\uc5d0 \uc77d\uace0 \ub9ac\ubdf0\ub97c \ud574\ubcf8\ub2e4.\\n\\n## \uac04\ub2e8 \uc694\uc57d\\n\\n1. \uc2e4\uc81c multi-domain \ud658\uacbd\uc5d0\uc11c LLM \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158\uc744 \ud3c9\uac00\ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud55c \uc774\uc911 \uc5b8\uc5b4(\ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4, \uc601\uc5b4) \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\ub97c \uc18c\uac1c\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n2. workflow planning\uacfc tool execution\uc73c\ub85c \ubd84\ub9ac\ud558\uace0 Graph Edit Distance(GED)\uc640 \uac19\uc740 structured metric\uc744 \uc0ac\uc6a9\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n3. \uc774 \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\ub294 constraint validation\uacfc dynamic revision\uc744 \ud3ec\ud568\ud558\ub294 17\uac1c domain\uacfc \uac70\uc758 100\uac1c\uc758 tool\ub85c \uad6c\uc131\ub41c \uc218\ub3d9\uc73c\ub85c \ub9cc\ub4e0 \ub370\uc774\ud130\uc14b\uc744 \ud3ec\ud568\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n4. \uc2e4\ud5d8 \uacb0\uacfc \uc77c\uad00\ub41c tool execution\uc740 \ud655\uc778\ub418\uc5c8\uc9c0\ub9cc planning \ub2e8\uacc4\uc5d0\uc11c\ub294 \uc0c1\ub2f9\ud55c \ubcc0\ub3d9\uc131\uc774 \ub098\ud0c0\ub098 structured \ud3c9\uac00\uc758 \ud544\uc694\uc131\uc744 \uac15\uc870\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n5. \uc0c8\ub85c\uc6b4 domain, tool, deployment context\ub85c \ud655\uc7a5 \uac00\ub2a5\ud55c \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\ub85c \uc124\uacc4\ub410\ub2e4.\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Introduction\\n\\n\uae30\uc874 \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\ub294 \ub300\ubd80\ubd84 \ub2e8\uc21c\ud654\ub418\uc5b4 \uc788\uac70\ub098 domain\uc774 \uaca9\ub9ac\ub41c \ud658\uacbd\uc5d0\uc11c \uc791\ub3d9\ud558\uae30\uc5d0 \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4 \uc900\ube44\uac00 \ub41c LLM\uc5d0 \ud544\uc694\ud55c \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158 \ub2a5\ub825\uc744 \ud655\uc778\ud560 \uc218 \uc5c6\ub2e4. \uc774\ub7f0 gap\uc744 \ud574\uc18c\ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud574 \ud604\uc2e4\uc801\uc778 \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4 \ud658\uacbd\uc5d0\uc11c LLM\uc744 \ud3c9\uac00\ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud574 \uc774\uc911 \uc5b8\uc5b4 \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\uc778 OrchestrationBench\ub97c \uc18c\uac1c\ud55c\ub2e4. \uc774 \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\ub294 workflow planning\uacfc constraint-aware tool execution\uc744 \uac15\uc870\ud558\ub294 \ud3ec\uad04\uc801\uc778 \ud3c9\uac00 \ud504\ub85c\ud1a0\ucf5c\uc744 \uc815\uc758\ud55c\ub2e4. workflow planning \uacbd\uc6b0\uc5d0\ub294 \ud3c9\uac00\ub294 workflow cosntruction\uc5d0 \uacf5\uc2dd\ud654\ub41c\ub2e4. \uac01 workflow\ub294 Directed Acyclic Graph(DAG)\ub85c \ud45c\ud604\ub41c\ub2e4. constraint-aware tool execution\uc740 \ud3c9\uac00\ub294 tool calling\uc758 syntactic correctness\ub97c \ub118\uc5b4\uc120\ub2e4.\\n\\n![Architecture](../assets/paper/OrchestrationBench/01-architecture.png)\\n\\n\\n## Related Work\\n\\n\ub17c\ubb38\uc5d0\uc11c\ub294 \uad00\ub828 \uc5f0\uad6c\ub97c \ub124 \uac00\uc9c0 \uc601\uc5ed\uc73c\ub85c \ubd84\ub958\ud55c\ub2e4. \\n\\n**Tool Execution Benchmarks**  \\nBFCL, API-Bank, T-Eval, ToolBench \ub4f1\uc740 \uc5d0\uc774\uc804\ud2b8\uac00 task\ub97c \ubd84\ud574\ud558\uace0 \uc801\uc808\ud55c tool\uc774\ub098 API\ub97c invoke\ud558\ub294 \ub2a5\ub825\uc744 \ud3c9\uac00\ud55c\ub2e4. \\n\\n**Single-agent Task Performance Benchmarks**  \\nTaskBench, \u03c4-bench, GAIA, WebArena, OSWorld \ub4f1\uc740 single agent\uac00 \ud2b9\uc815 \ud658\uacbd\uc5d0\uc11c task\uc744 \uc644\ub8cc\ud558\ub294 \ub2a5\ub825\uc744 \ud3c9\uac00\ud55c\ub2e4. \uc774\ub7f0 \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\ub4e4\uc740 \uc5ec\ub7ec domain\uc5d0 \uac78\uccd0 LLM\uc758 agentic task execution \ub2a5\ub825\uc744 \uce21\uc815\ud55c\ub2e4\ub294 \uc810\uc5d0\uc11c \uac00\uce58\uac00 \uc788\ub2e4. \uadf8\ub7ec\ub098 OrchestrationBench\ub294 \uc774\ub7f0 \uc5f0\uad6c\ub4e4\uacfc \ub2e4\ub974\uac8c \uc8fc\ub85c \uac1c\ubcc4 \uc5d0\uc774\uc804\ud2b8 \uc131\ub2a5\ubcf4\ub2e4\ub294 LLM-to-LLM \ud611\uc5c5\uc5d0 \ucd08\uc810\uc744 \ub9de\ucd94\uba70, \ud2b9\ud788 \uba54\uc778 \ubaa8\ub378\uc774 \uc804\ubb38 LLM\uc744 \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158\ud558\uace0 \ud638\ucd9c\ud558\ub294 \uc2dc\uc2a4\ud15c\uc744 \uc124\uacc4\ud55c\ub2e4. \\n\\n**Tool Safety Benchmarks**  \\nToolEmu, R-Judge, SafeToolBench\ub294 \uc704\ud5d8\ud55c \uc694\uccad\uc744 \uac70\ubd80\ud558\ub294 \ub2a5\ub825\uc744 \ud3c9\uac00\ud55c\ub2e4. \ub354 \uc790\uc138\ud788 \uc124\uba85\ud558\uba74 ToolEmu\ub294 single agent, R-Judge, SafeToolBench\ub294 multi-turn agent\uc758 \uacbd\uc6b0\uc774\ub2e4. \uc5ec\uae30\uc11c ToolEmu\ub294 \ubcf5\uc7a1\ud55c \ub2e4\ub2e8\uacc4 \uacc4\ud68d \uc218\ud589 \ub2a5\ub825\ubcf4\ub2e4\ub294 emulate\ub41c \ud658\uacbd \ub0b4 \uac1c\ubcc4 tool call\uc758 safety alignment\uc5d0 \ucd08\uc810\uc744 \ub9de\ucd98\ub2e4\uace0 \ud55c\ub2e4. \uadf8\ub7ec\ub098 OrchestrationBench\ub294 main LLM\uc774 \uc0ac\uc6a9 \uac00\ub2a5\ud55c sub-LLM\uc758 functional descriptions\uacfc constraints\ub97c \uc62c\ubc14\ub974\uac8c \uc774\ud574\ud568\uc73c\ub85c\uc368 \uc2e4\ud589 \ubd88\uac00\ub2a5\ud55c \uc694\uccad\uc744 \uac70\ubd80\ud560 \uc218 \uc788\ub294\uc9c0 \ud14c\uc2a4\ud2b8\ud558\uace0, safety\uacfc\ub294 \ub2e4\ub978 \ucc28\uc6d0\uc758 functional feasibility\uc5d0 \ub300\ud55c \ud3c9\uac00\ub97c \ub2e4\ub8ec\ub2e4.\\n\\n**Agentic Planning Benchmarks**  \\n\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ucd94\uc0c1\ud654 \uc218\uc900\uc5d0\uc11c \uacc4\ud68d \ubc0f \uc870\uc815 \ub2a5\ub825\uc744 \ud3c9\uac00\ud558\ub294 \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\uc774\ub2e4. PlanBench, MultiAgentBench, REALM-Bench \ub4f1 \ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\uac00 \uc788\ub2e4. \uc774\ub7f0 \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\ub4e4\uc774 \uc5d0\uc774\uc804\ud2b8\uc758 plan\uc774\ub098 tool calling \ub2a5\ub825\uc744 \ud14c\uc2a4\ud2b8\ud558\uc9c0\ub9cc OrchestrationBench\ub294 main LLM\uc774 natural language capability description\uc5d0 \uae30\ubc18\ud558\uc5ec \uc804\ubb38\ud654\ub41c \uc11c\ube0c LLM\uc744 \ub3d9\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \uc870\uc815\ud558\ub294 \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\ud130 \uc5ed\ud560\uc744 \ud558\ub294 \uacc4\uce35\uc801\uc778 LLM-to-LLM \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158 \uacfc\uc81c\ub97c \uc81c\uc2dc\ud55c\ub2e4. workflow planning\uc744 constraint-aware execution\uacfc \ubd84\ub9ac\ud558\ub294 diagnostic evaluation\ub97c \uc81c\uacf5\ud558\uc5ec \uc0c1\uc6a9 \ucc57\ubd07 \ubc30\ud3ec\uc5d0 \ud544\uc694\ud55c \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158 \uae30\ub2a5\uc5d0 \ub300\ud55c \uc720\ub2c8\ud06c\ud55c \ud3c9\uac00\ub97c \uc81c\uacf5\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\n![alt text](../assets/paper/OrchestrationBench/02-related-work.png)\\n\\nOrchestrationBench\ub294 \uc774 \ubaa8\ub4e0 \ud3c9\uac00\ub97c \ub9cc\uc871\ud558\ub294 \uc720\uc77c\ud55c \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\ub77c\uace0 \ud55c\ub2e4.  \\n\\n## The OrchestrationBench Framework\\n\\n### 1. The Complexity of Evaluating LLMs in Real-World Environments\\n\\n\uc2e4\uc81c \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4 \ud658\uacbd\uc5d0\uc11c LLM \ud3c9\uac00\ub294 \ub2e8\uc21c\ud55c QA\ub97c \ub118\uc5b4\uc11c\ub294 \ubcf5\uc7a1\ud55c \ub3c4\uc804\uc774\ub2e4. \ub2e4\uc74c \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790 \uc694\uccad\uc744 \uc0dd\uac01\ud574\ubcf4\uc790.\\n\\n> \\"\uc11c\uc6b8\ud589 \ud56d\uacf5\ud3b8 \uc608\uc57d\ud558\uace0, COEX \uadfc\ucc98 \ud638\ud154 \ucc3e\uc544\uc11c, \uc77c\uc815\uc744 \ud300\uc5d0\uac8c \uacf5\uc720\ud574\uc918.\\"\\n\\n\uc774 \uc694\uccad\uc744 \ucc98\ub9ac\ud558\ub824\uba74 \uc544\ub798\uc640 \uac19\uc740 \\n\\n1. **multi-steep planning**: \uc77c\uc815 \uacf5\uc720\ub294 \uc608\uc57d \uc644\ub8cc \ud6c4\uc5d0\ub9cc \uac00\ub2a5\\n2. **dynamic adaptation**: \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790\uac00 \\"\uc544\uce68 \ube44\ud589\uae30\ub85c \ubc14\uafd4\uc918\\"\ub77c\uace0 \uc218\uc815 \uc694\uccad \uc2dc \ub300\uc751\\n3. **constraint validation**: \\"4\uc2dc 10\ubd84\uc5d0 \uce58\uacfc \uc608\uc57d\\"\uc5d0 \ub300\ud574 \uc2dc\uc2a4\ud15c \uc81c\uc57d(\uc815\uc2dc/30\ubd84 \ub2e8\uc704\ub9cc \uac00\ub2a5)\uc744 \uc778\uc9c0\ud558\uace0 \ub300\uc548 \uc81c\uc2dc\\n\\n\uc774\ub7f0 \uc2dc\ub098\ub9ac\uc624\ub294 \uae30\uc874\uc758 \uc815\uc801\uc778 \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\uac00 \uc7a1\uc9c0 \ubabb\ud558\ub294 planning, adaptation, constraint-aware execution\uc758 \ubcf5\uc7a1\ud558\uac8c \uc5bd\ud78c \uacfc\uc81c\ub97c \uac15\uc870\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\n### 2. OrchestrationBench Architecture\\n\\nOrchestrationBench\ub294 \uc601\uc5b4\uc640 \ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4 \uc989, \uc774\uc911 \uc5b8\uc5b4 \ub370\uc774\ud130\uc14b\uc744 \uac16\ucd98 \ud3ec\uad04\uc801\uc778 \ud3c9\uac00 \ud504\ub808\uc784\uc6cc\ud06c\ub97c \ub3c4\uc785\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\n#### 2.1 Advanced Planning and Coordination\\n\\n\uc544\ub798\ub97c \ubcf4\uba74 \uc54c \uc218 \uc788\ub4ef\uc774 \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158\uc744 \uac01 task\uc758 execution \uc0c1\ud0dc, \uc885\uc18d\uc131 \uad00\uacc4, step-level planning\uc744 \uc815\uc758\ud558\ub294 structured workflow schema\ub85c \ud615\uc2dd\ud654\ud55c\ub2e4. \uc774\ub7f0 \uad6c\uc870\ub294 sequential \ubc0f parallel execution\uc744 \uad00\ub9ac\ud558\uace0 workflow \uac04 \uc885\uc18d\uc131\uc744 \ucc98\ub9ac\ud558\uba70, execution \uc911 \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790 \uc0c1\ud638\uc791\uc6a9\uc5d0 \uc801\uc751\ud560 \uc218 \uc788\ub294\uc9c0 \ud3c9\uac00\ud560 \uc218 \uc788\uac8c \ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\n**Workflow Schema**\\n\\n![alt text](../assets/paper/OrchestrationBench/03-workflow-schema.png)\\n\\n**\uc608\uc2dc**: \\"\ub0b4\uc77c \uc11c\uc6b8 \ucd9c\uc7a5\uc774\ub2e4. \ud56d\uacf5\ud3b8 \uc608\uc57d\ud558\uace0, COEX \uadfc\ucc98 \ud638\ud154\ub3c4 \ucc3e\uace0, \uc77c\uc815\uc744 \ud300\uc5d0\uac8c \uacf5\uc720\ud574\uc918.\\"\\n\\n```yaml\\nworkflow_1:\\n  status: pending\\n  type: independent\\n  steps:\\n    - status: pending\\n      name: travel_agent\\n      refined_query: \\"\ub0b4\uc77c \uc11c\uc6b8\ud589 \ucd9c\uc7a5 \ud56d\uacf5\ud3b8 \uc608\uc57d\\"\\n\\nworkflow_2:\\n  status: pending\\n  type: independent\\n  steps:\\n    - status: pending\\n      name: travel_agent\\n      refined_query: \\"COEX \uadfc\ucc98 \ud638\ud154 \uc608\uc57d\\"\\n\\nworkflow_3:\\n  status: pending\\n  type: dependent\\n  depend_on: [\\"workflow_1\\", \\"workflow_2\\"]\\n  steps:\\n    - status: pending\\n      name: calendar_agent\\n      refined_query: \\"\uc644\ub8cc\ub41c \uc77c\uc815\uc744 \ud300\uc5d0\uac8c \uacf5\uc720\\"\\n```\\n\\n`depend_on`\uc740 \ud604\uc7ac workflow\uac00 \uc2dc\uc791\ub418\uae30 \uc804\uc5d0 \uc644\ub8cc\ub418\uc5b4\uc57c \ud558\ub294 workflow\ub97c \uc9c0\uc815\ud55c\ub2e4. `workflow_3`\uc740 `workflow_1`\uacfc `workflow_2`\uc5d0 \uc758\uc874\ud558\ubbc0\ub85c, \ub450 task\uc774 \uc644\ub8cc\ub41c \ud6c4\uc5d0\uc57c \uc2e4\ud589\ub41c\ub2e4.\\n\\n\uc2e4\uc81c \ud658\uacbd\uc5d0\uc11c \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790 \ucffc\ub9ac\ub294 \uc815\uc801\uc778 task plan\uc744 \ub530\ub974\uae30\ubcf4\ub2e4\ub294 \ub3d9\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \uc9c4\ud654\ud558\ub294 \uacbd\uc6b0\uac00 \ub9ce\ub2e4. OrchestrationBench\ub294 \ubaa8\ub378\uc774 \ucd94\uac00\uc801\uc778 tool\uc774 \ud544\uc694\ud560 \ub54c \uc0c8\ub85c\uc6b4 workflow\ub97c \uc0dd\uc131\ud558\uace0 explicit confirmation\uc774\ub098 sub-task\ub85c\uc758 \ubd84\uae30\uac00 \ud544\uc694\ud560 \ub54c workflow\ub97c \ubd84\ud560\ud568\uc73c\ub85c\uc368 \uc720\uc5f0\ud558\uac8c \uc870\uc815\ud560 \uc218 \uc788\ub294\uc9c0\ub97c \ud3c9\uac00\ud55c\ub2e4. \uc608\ub97c \ub4e4\uc5b4 \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790\uac00 \uc608\uc57d\ub41c \uc694\uccad\uc744 \uc218\uc815\ud558\uac70\ub098 \ub300\ud654 \uc911\uc5d0 \uc0c8\ub85c\uc6b4 \uc870\uac74\uc744 \ucd94\uac00\ud558\ub294 \uacbd\uc6b0 \ubaa8\ub378\uc740 \uc774\uc804 \ub2e8\uacc4\uc640\uc758 \uc77c\uad00\uc131\uc744 \uc720\uc9c0\ud558\uba74\uc11c workflow\ub97c \uc5c5\ub370\uc774\ud2b8\ud558\uac70\ub098 \ud655\uc7a5\ud574\uc57c \ud55c\ub2e4. \uba85\ud655\ud55c \uae30\uc900\uc740 workflow\ub97c \ubd84\ud560\ud558\uac70\ub098 \ud1b5\ud569\ud574\uc57c \ud558\ub294 \uc2dc\uc810\uc744 \uacb0\uc815\ud55c\ub2e4. \ub3c5\ub9bd\uc801\uc778 \uc694\uccad(e.g., \ud56d\uacf5\ud3b8 \uc77c\uc815\uacfc \ud638\ud154\ucd94\ucc9c \ubaa8\ub450 \uc694\uccad\ud558\ub294 \uacbd\uc6b0) \ub610\ub294 \uc911\uac04 \ud655\uc778\uc774 \ud544\uc694\ud55c task(e.g., \uc608\uc57d \uc804\uc5d0 \ucd94\ucc9c \uc2b9\uc778)\ub294 \ubcc4\ub3c4\uc758 \uc6cc\ucee4\ud50c\ub85c\ub85c \ucc98\ub9ac\ub41c\ub2e4. \ubc18\ub300\ub85c \uc77c\uad00\ub418\uace0 \ud558\ub098\uc758 \ubaa9\ud45c\uc5d0 \uae30\uc5ec\ud558\ub294 task\ub294 \ud558\ub098\uc758 workflow \ub0b4\uc5d0 \uc720\uc9c0\ub41c\ub2e4. \uc608\ub97c \ub4e4\uc5b4 \uc720\uba85\uc778\uc758 \ubcc4\uc790\ub9ac\ub97c \uacb0\uc815\ud558\uae30 \uc804\uc5d0 \uc0dd\uc77c\uc744 \ud655\uc778\ud558\ub294 \uacbd\uc6b0\uc774\ub2e4.\\n\\n\uc989, \uc774 \ud504\ub808\uc784\uc6cc\ud06c\ub294 \ubaa8\ub378\uc774 \uacc4\ud68d\ud560 \ubfd0\ub9cc \uc544\ub2c8\ub77c \uc2e4\uc81c \uc0c1\ud638\uc791\uc6a9\uc801\uc778 \uc2dc\ub098\ub9ac\uc624\uc5d0 \ub9de\ucdb0 workflow\ub97c \uc870\uc815\ud558\uace0 \uc911\ub2e8\ud558\uace0 \ub2e4\uc2dc \uc791\ub3d9\ud558\ub294 \ub2a5\ub825\uc744 \uc790\uc138\ud558\uac8c \ud3c9\uac00\ud560 \uc218 \uc788\ub3c4\ub85d \ud55c\ub2e4. \\n\\n#### 2.2. Comprehensive Tool Use\\n\\ntool execution \ud3c9\uac00\ub294 \ub2e8\uc21c\ud788 tool call \uc815\ud655\ub3c4\ub97c \uac80\uc99d\ud558\ub294 \uc218\uc900\uc744 \ub118\uc5b4, \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4 \uc218\uc900 \uc0c1\ud638\uc791\uc6a9 \uacfc\uc815 \uc804\uccb4\ub97c \ud3ec\uad04\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\uc774\ub294 \ubaa8\ub378\uc774 tool\uc744 \uc62c\ubc14\ub974\uac8c invoke\ud558\ub294\uc9c0 \ubfd0\ub9cc \uc544\ub2c8\ub77c, \uc5b8\uc81c tool use\uac00 \ud544\uc694\ud55c\uc9c0, \uc5b8\uc81c\ub294 \ucd94\uac00 tool \uc5c6\uc774 \uc9c1\uc811 \uc815\ubcf4\ub97c \uc81c\uacf5\ud560 \uc218 \uc788\ub294\uc9c0, \uadf8\ub9ac\uace0 \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790 \uc785\ub825\uc774 \ubd88\ucda9\ubd84\ud558\uac70\ub098 \ubaa8\ud638\ud55c \uacbd\uc6b0\ub97c \uc778\uc9c0\ud558\uc5ec \ub2a5\ub3d9\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \ucd94\uac00 \uc124\uba85\uc744 \uc694\uccad\ud560 \uc218 \uc788\ub294\uc9c0\ub97c \ud3c9\uac00\ud55c\ub2e4. \uc774\ub7ec\ud55c \ud589\ub3d9\uc740 `AWAIT_FOR_USER_INPUT` \uc2e0\ud638\ub85c \ud45c\ud604\ub41c\ub2e4.\\n\\nsyntatic correctness\ub97c \ub118\uc5b4\uc11c\uc11c \uc2e4\uc81c \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4\ub294 \ub3c4\uba54\uc778\ubcc4 \ube44\uc988\ub2c8\uc2a4 \uaddc\uce59\uc744 \uc5c4\uaca9\ud558\uac8c \uc900\uc218\ud574\uc57c \ud55c\ub2e4. tool\uc744 \uc2e4\uc81c\ub85c invoke\ud558\uae30 \uc804\uc5d0, \ubaa8\ub378\uc740 pre-execution \uac80\uc99d\uc744 \uc218\ud589\ud558\uba70, \ud544\uc694\ud55c \uc81c\uc57d \uc870\uac74\uc774 \ucda9\uc871\ub418\uc9c0 \uc54a\uc558\uc744 \uacbd\uc6b0 `TOOL_CONSTRAINT_VIOLATION`\uc744 \ubc1c\uc0dd\uc2dc\ud0a8\ub2e4.\\n\\n- \ub17c\ub9ac\uc801 \uc77c\uad00\uc131 \uc720\uc9c0\\n    - \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790\uc758 \uc694\uccad \ub0b4\uc6a9\uc774 \ud604\uc2e4\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \ub9d0\uc774 \ub418\uac70\ub098 \ub17c\ub9ac\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \ubaa8\uc21c\ub418\uc9c0 \uc54a\ub294\uc9c0 \ud655\uc778\ud558\ub294 \uacfc\uc815\\n    - e.g., \ud56d\uacf5\uad8c \uc608\uc57d \uc2dc \uadc0\uad6d\uc77c\uc774 \ucd9c\ubc1c\uc77c\ubcf4\ub2e4 \ube60\ub978 \uac83\\n- \uc790\uc6d0 \uc81c\ud55c \uac15\uc81c\\n    - \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4\ub098 \ub3c4\uad6c\uac00 \uc81c\uacf5\ud558\ub294 \ud2b9\uc815 \uc790\uc6d0\uc758 \uc81c\uc57d\uc744 \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790\uc758 \uc694\uccad\uc774 \uc900\uc218\ud558\ub294\uc9c0 \ud655\uc778\ud558\ub294 \uacfc\uc815\\n    - e.g., \ud2b9\uc815 \ubb3c\ud488\uc758 \uc7ac\uace0 \uc218\ub7c9\uc744 \ucd08\uacfc\ud558\ub294 \uc8fc\ubb38 \uc694\uccad, \ud5c8\uc6a9\ub41c \uc608\uc0b0\uc744 \ub118\uc5b4\uc11c\ub294 \uad6c\ub9e4 \uc694\uccad\\n\\nLLM\uc740 \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790\uc758 \uc694\uccad\uc774\ub098 \ucd94\ucd9c\ub41c \uc815\ubcf4\uc5d0 \ub300\ud574 \uc131\uacf5\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \uc720\ud6a8\uc131 \uac80\uc0ac\ub97c \ub9c8\uce5c \ud6c4\uc5d0\uc57c \ube44\ub85c\uc18c \uc62c\ubc14\ub978 \ud615\uc2dd\uc758 \ub9e4\uac1c\ubcc0\uc218\ub97c \uc0ac\uc6a9\ud558\uc5ec \ud574\ub2f9 \uc678\ubd80 \ub3c4\uad6c\ub97c \uc2e4\ud589\ud574\uc57c \ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\n\ubaa8\ub378 \uc131\ub2a5\uc740 call/reject \ubd84\ub958 \ub9e4\ud2b8\ub9ad\uc744 \ud1b5\ud574 \uce21\uc815\ub418\uace0 \uc5ec\uae30\uc11c `AWAIT_FOR_USER_INPUT`, `TOOL_CONSTRAINT_VIOLATION`\uc740 reject \uc0ac\ub840\ub97c \ub098\ud0c0\ub0b4\uace0 \uc131\uacf5\uc801\uc778 execution\uc740 funcion-calling \uc131\ub2a5 \uc9c0\ud45c\ub97c \uc0ac\uc6a9\ud558\uc5ec \ud3c9\uac00\ub41c\ub2e4.\\n\\n#### 2.3. Multi-Domain Tool Environments\\n\\n\uc774 \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\ub294 \ud2b9\uc815 \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4 \uc885\uc18d\uc131\uacfc\ub294 \ub3c5\ub9bd\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \uc720\uc9c0\ud558\uba74\uc11c \uc2e4\uc81c \uc560\ud50c\ub9ac\ucf00\uc774\uc158\uc73c\ub85c \ud655\uc7a5 \uac00\ub2a5\ud55c 17\uac1c\uc758 \ub300\ud45c\uc801\uc778 \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4 \ub3c4\uba54\uc778\uc744 \uc815\uc758\ud55c\ub2e4. \uac01 \ub3c4\uba54\uc778\uc740 \ubaa8\ub378\uc758 \uace0\uc720\ud55c \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158 \ubc0f \uba85\ub839\uc5b4 \uc218\ud589 \ub2a5\ub825\uc744 \ud3c9\uac00\ud560 \uc218 \uc788\ub3c4\ub85d \ud604\uc2e4\uc801\uc774\uba74\uc11c\ub3c4 \uc77c\ubc18\ud654\ub41c \uc2dc\ub098\ub9ac\uc624\ub97c \uc911\uc2ec\uc73c\ub85c \uad6c\ucd95\ub41c\ub2e4.\\n\\n![alt text](../assets/paper/OrchestrationBench/04-multi-domain-tools.png)\\n\\n\uc601\uc5b4 97\uac1c, \ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4 99\uac1c\uc758 tool\uc774 \uc788\ub2e4. \ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4\uc5d0\ub294 \uc8fc\uc18c \ub85c\ub9c8\uc790 \ubcc0\ud658, \uc0ac\uc8fc \uc815\ubcf4 \ub4f1\uacfc \uac19\uc740 \ud2b9\uc218 tool\uc774 \ucd94\uac00\ub418\uc5b4 \uc788\ub2e4. \ub2e8\uc21c\ud654\ub41c tool \ucd94\uc0c1\ud654\ub97c \uc0ac\uc6a9\ud55c \uc774\uc804 \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\ub4e4\uacfc\ub294 \ub2ec\ub9ac OrchestrationBench\ub294 \ub3c4\uba54\uc778\ubcc4 \uc81c\uc57d \uc870\uac74\uacfc \ud604\uc2e4\uc801\uc778 \ub3d9\uc791\uc744 \ud1b5\ud569\ud558\uc5ec \ub2e4\uc591\ud55c task\uc5d0 \ub300\ud55c \uc138\ubc00\ud55c \ucee4\ubc84\ub9ac\uc9c0\ub97c \uc81c\uacf5\ud558\uace0 \uc2e4\uc81c \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4 \ud658\uacbd\uc744 \ucda9\uc2e4\ud558\uac8c \uc2dc\ubbac\ub808\uc774\uc158\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\n\uc774\ub7f0 domain\ub4e4\uc740 \uc9d1\ud569\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \uc138 \uac00\uc9c0 \uc77c\ubc18\uc801\uc778 \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790 workflow \uc720\ud615\uc744 \ub098\ud0c0\ub0b8\ub2e4. \uc774\ub7f0 \ubd84\ub958\ub294 \uc774 \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\uac00 \uc8fc\ub85c \uc77c\uc0c1\uc801\uc778 \uc18c\ube44\uc790 \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4\ub97c \ubc18\uc601\ud558\ub294 \ub3d9\uc2dc\uc5d0 \uc720\ud2f8\ub9ac\ud2f0 \ubc0f \uc0dd\uc0b0\uc131 \ub9e5\ub77d\uc73c\ub85c \ud655\uc7a5 \uac00\ub2a5\ud568\uc744 \uac15\uc870\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\n1. \ubb38\uc758 \ubc0f \uc815\ubcf4 task(e.g., \ub0a0\uc528 \ud655\uc778, \uc7a5\uc18c \ucc3e\uae30, \ub274\uc2a4 \uc77d\uae30)\\n2. \ud589\ub3d9 \ubc0f \uac70\ub798 task(e.g., \ud56d\uacf5\uad8c \uc608\uc57d, \ubb3c\ud488 \uad6c\ub9e4)\\n3. \uacc4\ud68d \ubc0f \uc870\uc815 task(e.g., \ud68c\uc758 \uc77c\uc815 \uc7a1\uae30, \uba54\uc2dc\uc9c0 \ubcf4\ub0b4\uae30, \ubc30\uc1a1 \uc900\ube44)\\n\\n### 3. Dataset Construction\\n\\n\ud574\ub2f9 \ub370\uc774\ud130\uc14b\uc740 \uc2e4\uc81c \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4 \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158\uc758 \ubcf5\uc7a1\uc131\uacfc \ud604\uc2e4\uc131\uc744 \uc7a1\uc744 \uc218 \uc788\ub3c4\ub85d \uc124\uacc4\ub410\ub2e4. \uc9c4\uc815\uc131\uacfc \ud004\ub9ac\ud2f0\ub97c \ubcf4\uc7a5\ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud574 \ubaa8\ub4e0 \ub300\ud654 \uc138\uc158, workflow \ubc0f tool call\uc740 \uc778\uacf5\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \uc0dd\uc131\ud55c \uac83\uc774 \uc544\ub2cc \ud6c8\ub828\ub41c annotator\uac00 \uc0c1\uc138\ud55c \uad6c\ucd95 \uc9c0\uce68\uc5d0 \ub530\ub77c \uc9c1\uc811 \uc0dd\uc131\ud588\ub2e4. \uc989, \ub300\ud654 \ud750\ub984, tool \uc0ac\uc6a9 \ubc0f \uc81c\uc57d \uc870\uac74 \ucc98\ub9ac\uac00 \ud2b9\uc815 \ubaa8\ub378\uc758 \uc778\uacf5 \ub370\uc774\ud130\uac00 \uc544\ub2cc \ud604\uc2e4\uc801\uc778 \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790-\uc11c\ube44\uc2a4 \uc0c1\ud638\uc791\uc6a9\uc744 \ucda9\uc2e4\ud558\uac8c \ubc18\uc601\ud558\ub3c4\ub85d \ubcf4\uc7a5\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\n\uc544\ub798 \ud45c\ub294 domain \uc120\ud0dd, \uac00\uc0c1 tool \uc124\uacc4, \uc218\ub3d9 \uac80\ud1a0 \ubc0f \uac80\uc99d\uc744 \ud3ec\ud568\ud558\ub294 \uc804\ubc18\uc801\uc778 \uad6c\ucd95 \ud30c\uc774\ud504\ub77c\uc778\uc774\ub2e4. \ubaa8\ub4e0 \uc2dc\ub098\ub9ac\uc624\ub294 \uc77c\uad00\uc131\uacfc \uc815\ud655\uc131\uc744 \ubcf4\uc7a5\ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud574 \ucd5c\uc18c \uc138 \uba85\uc758 annotator\uc5d0 \uc758\ud574 \uad50\ucc28 \uac80\uc99d \ub410\ub2e4. \ud1b5\uc81c\ub418\uace0 \ud574\uc11d \uac00\ub2a5\ud55c \ud3c9\uac00\ub97c \uac00\ub2a5\ud558\uac8c \ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud574 \ubaa8\ud638\ud558\uac70\ub098 \ub2e4\uc911 \uc194\ub8e8\uc158 \uc0ac\ub840\ub97c \uc81c\uc678\ud558\uace0 \uba85\ud655\ud558\uace0 \uc798 \uc815\uc758\ub41c \uc885\uc18d\uc131\uc744 \uac00\uc9c4 task\uc138\uc5b4\ub9cc \ub370\uc774\ud130\ub97c \uad6c\ucd95\ud588\ub2e4. \uc989, \uc774 \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\ub294 \ub192\uc740 \uc2e0\ub8b0\uc131\uc744 \ub2ec\uc131\ud558\ub294 \ub3d9\uc2dc\uc5d0 \ub2e8\uc77c \ubaa8\ub378\uc774\ub098 \ub3c5\uc810 API\uc5d0 \ub3c5\ub9bd\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \uc720\uc9c0\ub41c\ub2e4.\\n\\n![alt text](../assets/paper/OrchestrationBench/05-dataset-construction.png)\\n\\n**\uc2dc\ub098\ub9ac\uc624 \uc720\ud615 \uc608\uc2dc**\\n\\n![alt text](../assets/paper/OrchestrationBench/06-scenario-types.png)\\n\\n### 4. Dataset Scale and Distribution\\n\\n![alt text](../assets/paper/OrchestrationBench/07-dataset-scale.png)\\n\\n![alt text](../assets/paper/OrchestrationBench/08-dataset-distribution.png)\\n\\n\uc774 \ub370\uc774\ud130\uc14b\uc740 \uc601\uc5b4\uc640 \ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4 \uc11c\ube0c\uc14b\uc744 \ubaa8\ub450 \ud3ec\ud568\ud558\uba70 \uaddc\ubaa8 \uba74\uc5d0\uc11c \uc720\uc0ac\ud558\ub2e4. \ub450 \ub370\uc774\ud130\uc14b \ubaa8\ub450 17\uac1c\uc758 \ub300\ud45c\uc801\uc778 \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4 \ub3c4\uba54\uc778\uc5d0 \uac78\uccd0 \uc788\uace0, \uc758\ub3c4\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \ube44\ub300\uce6d\uc801\uc778 tool \ubd84\ud3ec\ub97c \ubcf4\uc5ec\uc900\ub2e4. Places \ub610\ub294 Entertainment\uc640 \uac19\uc740 \ub113\uc740 domain\uc740 \ub9ce\uc740 tool\uc744 \ud3ec\ud568\ud558\uc9c0\ub9cc, Weather\ub098 News \uac19\uc740 \uc881\uc740 domain\uc740 \ud604\uc2e4\uc801\uc778 \uc0ac\uc6a9 \ube48\ub3c4\ub97c \ubc18\uc601\ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud574 \uac04\uacb0\ud558\uac8c \uad6c\uc131\ub418\uc5b4 \uc788\ub2e4.\\n\\nworkflow \uc218\uc900\uc5d0\uc11c \ub300\ubd80\ubd84\uc758 \uc138\uc158\uc740 2~3\uac1c\uc758 workflow\uc640 2~3\uac1c\uc758 domain\uc744 \ud3ec\ud568\ud558\uc9c0\ub9cc \uc77c\ubd80\ub294 \ucd5c\ub300 7 step\uae4c\uc9c0 \ud655\uc7a5\ub418\uac70\ub098 4\uac1c \uc774\uc0c1\uc758 domain\uc5d0 \uac78\uce5c\ub2e4. \uc774\ub294 single session\uc774 \uc77c\ubc18\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \uc5ec\ub7ec \ucc28\ub840\uc758 planning\uc744 \ud544\uc694\ub85c \ud558\uba70 \uc77c\ubd80\ub294 \ucd5c\ub300 7 planning step\uc744 \ud3ec\ud568\ud558\ub294 \uac78 \ubcf4\uc5ec\uc900\ub2e4. \ub610\ud55c, \ub450 \uac1c \uc774\uc0c1\uc758 domain\uc774 \uc790\uc8fc \ud3ec\ud568\ub418\ub294 \uac83\uc740 \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790\uac00 heterogeneous \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4 \uac04\uc5d0 \uc804\ud658\ud558\ub294 \ud604\uc2e4\uc801\uc778 \ub2e4\uc911 \ub3c4\uba54\uc778 \uc2dc\ub098\ub9ac\uc624\ub97c \ubc18\uc601\ud55c\ub2e4. tool invocation \uce21\uba74\uc5d0\uc11c \uc774 \ub370\uc774\ud130\uc14b\uc740 single isolated call\ubcf4\ub2e4\ub294 sequential and parallel call \uad6c\uc870\uac00 \uc9c0\ubc30\uc801\uc774\uc5b4\uc11c \uc2e4\uc81c task\uc744 \uc644\ub8cc\ud558\ub294 \ub370 \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158\uc774 \ubcf5\uc7a1\ud55c \uac78 \ud655\uc778\ud560 \uc218 \uc788\ub2e4.\\n\\n\uc774\ub7f0 \ubd84\ud3ec\ub4e4\uc740 \uc885\ud569\uc801\uc73c\ub85c OrchestrationBench\uac00 \uad11\ubc94\uc704\ud55c \uc2e4\uc81c \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158 \ud328\ud134\uc744 \ub2e4\ub8e8\uba70, \ubaa8\ub378 planning, tool invocation \uadf8\ub9ac\uace0 adaptive reasoning capabilities\uc5d0 \ub300\ud55c \uc138\ubc00\ud55c \ud3c9\uac00\ub97c \uac00\ub2a5\ud558\uac8c \ud568\uc744 \ubcf4\uc5ec\uc900\ub2e4. \uc774\ub294 \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\uac00 \uace0\ub9bd\ub41c \uc9c8\uc758\uc751\ub2f5 \ub610\ub294 \ub2e8\uc21c\ud55c tool calling\uc744 \ub118\uc5b4 \ud604\uc2e4\uc801\uc774\uace0 constaint-aware \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4 \ud658\uacbd\uc5d0\uc11c\uc758 \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158 \uc131\ub2a5 \ud3c9\uac00\ub97c \uac00\ub2a5\ud558\uac8c \ud568\uc744 \uac15\uc870\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\n## Evaluation\\n\\n\ud604\uc7ac\uc758 end-to-end \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\uc778 AgentBench, GAIA, SWE-bench, \u03c4-bench\ub294 \uc720\uc5f0\uc131\uc744 \uc81c\uacf5\ud558\uc9c0\ub9cc \ubcf5\uc7a1\ud55c multi-step task\uc5d0\uc11c \uc2e4\ud328 \uc9c0\uc810\uc744 \ubaa8\ud638\ud558\uac8c \ub9cc\ub4dc\ub294 \uacbd\uc6b0\uac00 \ub9ce\ub2e4. \uc774\ub7f0 \ud55c\uacc4\ub97c \ud574\uacb0\ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud574 \uac01 \uad6c\uc131 \uc694\uc18c\ub97c \ub3c5\ub9bd\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \ubd84\ub9ac\ud558\uace0 \ud14c\uc2a4\ud2b8\ud558\ub294 \uc2a4\ud0ed\ubcc4 \ud3c9\uac00\ub97c \uc0ac\uc6a9\ud55c\ub2e4. \ud3c9\uac00\ub294 Planning\uacfc Tool execution \ub450 \uac00\uc9c0 \uc8fc\uc694 \ub2e8\uacc4\ub97c \uad6c\ubd84\ud55c\ub2e4. \uc11c\ube0c LLM\uc758 \ubbf8\ubb18\ud55c \ub3d9\uc791\uc744 \uc7a1\uae30 \uc704\ud574 tool execution\uc744 \ub450 \uac00\uc9c0 \uc21c\ucc28\uc801\uc778 \ud3c9\uac00 \uae30\uc900\uc73c\ub85c \ub354 \ubd84\ud574\ud55c\ub2e4. call/reject \ubd84\ub958 \uc815\ud655\ub3c4\uc640 function calling \uc131\ub2a5\uc774\ub2e4.\\n\\n**\ubaa8\ub378**  \\n\ubaa8\ub4e0 reasoning \ubaa8\ub378\uc740 low reasoning \uc124\uc815\uc73c\ub85c \uad6c\uc131\ub410\ub2e4.\\n- OpenAI GPT Models (gpt-4.1, gpt-4o, gpt-5)\\n- Anthropic Claude Models (claude-sonnet-4)\\n- Google Gemini Models (gemini-2.5-pro-preview, gemini-2.5-flash-preview)\\n- Alibaba Qwen Models (Qwen3 series)\\n- Korean Open-Source Models (SKT A.X-4.0, Kakao kanana-1.5, LG AI Research EXAONE-4.0)\\n\\n**Evaluation Protocol**\\n- \uac01 \ud0c0\uac9f LLM\uc740 \ud3c9\uac00 \uc2dc\uc810\uae4c\uc9c0\uc758 \uc804\uccb4 \ub300\ud654 \uae30\ub85d\uc744 \uc785\ub825\uc73c\ub85c \uc81c\uacf5\ubc1b\ub294\ub2e4.\\n- \ubcd1\ub82c\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \uc2e4\ud589\ub418\ub294 LLM\ub4e4\uc740 \uc815\ubcf4 \ub204\ucd9c\uc744 \ubc29\uc9c0\ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud574 \uc11c\ub85c \ubd84\ub9ac\ub41c \uae30\ub85d\uc5d0\uc11c \uc791\ub3d9\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n- \uc21c\ucc28\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \uc2e4\ud589\ub418\ub294 LLM\ub4e4\uc740 \uc774\uc804 \ubaa8\ub378\uc758 \ucd9c\ub825\uc744 \ud3ec\ud568\ud55c \ub204\uc801\ub41c \ub300\ud654 \uae30\ub85d\uc5d0 \uc811\uadfc\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n- \uba54\uc778 LLM\uc758 workflow \uc0dd\uc131\uc740 \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790 \uc785\ub825\uc5d0 \uc758\ud574\uc11c\ub9cc \ud2b8\ub9ac\uac70\ub41c\ub2e4.\\n- \uc11c\ube0c LLM\uc740 \uba54\uc778 LLM\uc73c\ub85c\ubd80\ud130 \uc804\ub2ec\ub41c \uc815\uc81c\ub41c \uc9c8\uc758\uc640 \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc790\uac00 \uc81c\uacf5\ud55c \ucd94\uac00 \uc124\uba85\uc744 \ucc98\ub9ac\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\n### 1. Evaluation Metrics\\n\\n2\uac00\uc9c0\ub85c \ub098\ub25c\ub2e4. \uc774\ub807\uac8c \ubd84\ub9ac\ud55c \uc774\uc720\ub294 \uacc4\ud68d\uc744 \uc798 \uc138\uc6cc\ub3c4 \uc2e4\ud589\uc5d0\uc11c \ud2c0\ub9b4 \uc218 \uc788\uace0, \ubc18\ub300\ub85c \ub2e8\uc21c \ud638\ucd9c \uc815\ud655\ub3c4\ub294 \uc88b\uc544\ub3c4 \uc804\uccb4 workflow\ub294 \ub9dd\uac00\uc9c8 \uc218 \uc788\uae30 \ub54c\ubb38\uc774\ub2e4.\\n\\n**Planning Assessment**\\nworkflow \uc0dd\uc131 \ud488\uc9c8\uc744 \ud3c9\uac00\ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud574 Graph Edit Distance(GED)\ub97c \uc0ac\uc6a9\ud55c\ub2e4. GED\ub294 \ud558\ub098\uc758 \uadf8\ub798\ud504\ub97c \ub2e4\ub978 \uadf8\ub798\ud504\ub85c \ubcc0\ud658\ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud574 \ud544\uc694\ud55c \ucd5c\uc18c \ud3b8\uc9d1 \uc5f0\uc0b0(minimum edit operations)\uc758 \uc218\ub97c \uacc4\uc0b0\ud568\uc73c\ub85c\uc368 \uad6c\uc870\uc801 \ucc28\uc774(structural differences)\ub97c \uc815\ub7c9\ud654\ud558\uba70, Advancing Agentic Systems\uc758 \ubc29\ubc95\uc744 \ub530\ub978\ub2e4. \ubcf8 \uc5f0\uad6c\uc5d0\uc11c\ub294 \uac12\uc774 \ud074\uc218\ub85d \uc131\ub2a5\uc774 \uc6b0\uc218\ud568\uc744 \uc758\ubbf8\ud558\ub3c4\ub85d 1\u2212GED\ub97c \uc0ac\uc6a9\ud55c\ub2e4. \uc6b0\ub9ac\uc758 workflow representation\uc740 workflow structure, step assignment(sub-LLM selection), \uadf8\ub9ac\uace0 execution status\ub97c \ud3ec\ud568\ud55c\ub2e4. \uc6b0\ub9ac\ub294 \uacc4\uce35\uc801 workflow \uc810\uc218 \ud3c9\uac00\ub97c \uc218\ud589\ud558\uba70, \uc774 \uc911 structural score\ub294 workflow topology\uc758 \uc815\ud655\uc131\uc744 \uce21\uc815\ud558\uace0, component score\ub294 step-level assignments\uc744 \ud3c9\uac00\ud55c\ub2e4. \uc624\ub958 \uac00\uc911\uce58 \uc124\uc815\uc5d0\uc11c\ub294 status errors(0.2)\ubcf4\ub2e4 selection errors(0.8)\uc5d0 \ub354 \ub192\uc740 \uac00\uc911\uce58\ub97c \ubd80\uc5ec\ud55c\ub2e4. \uc774\ub294 \uc798\ubabb\ub41c tool\uc744 \uc120\ud0dd\ud558\ub294 \uac83\uc774 tool execution \uc0c1\ud0dc\ub97c \uc798\ubabb \ud310\ub2e8\ud558\ub294 \uac83\ubcf4\ub2e4 \uc77c\ubc18\uc801\uc73c\ub85c task \uc131\uacf5\uc5d0 \ub354 \uce58\uba85\uc801\uc774\ub77c\ub294 \uc9c1\uad00\uc744 \ubc18\uc601\ud55c \uac83\uc774\ub2e4. \ub2e4\ub9cc, \uc774\ub7ec\ud55c \uac00\uc911\uce58\ub294 \uacbd\ud5d8\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \ub3c4\ucd9c\ub41c \uac83\uc740 \uc544\ub2c8\ub2e4.\\n\\n**Tool Execution Assessment**\\ntool execution \ub2a5\ub825\uc744 \uc885\ud569\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \ud3c9\uac00\ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud574, \uc6b0\ub9ac\ub294 \ub450 \uac00\uc9c0 \ud575\uc2ec \uc694\uc18c\ub97c \ubd84\uc11d\ud55c\ub2e4. \uccab\uc9f8\ub294 \ubaa8\ub378\uc774 \uc801\uc808\ud55c calling \uacb0\uc815\uc744 \ub0b4\ub9b4 \uc218 \uc788\ub294 \ub2a5\ub825\uc774\uba70, \ub458\uc9f8\ub294 \uc2e4\uc81c function execution\uc758 \ud004\ub9ac\ud2f0\uc774\ub2e4. call/reject classification accuracy\ub294 \uc804\uccb4 \uc0ac\ub840 \uc911\uc5d0\uc11c \uc801\uc808\ud55c reject \uacb0\uc815\uacfc \uc131\uacf5\uc801\uc778 function call \uc2dc\ub3c4\ub97c \ubaa8\ub450 \ud3ec\ud568\ud55c \uc62c\ubc14\ub978 \uacb0\uc815\uc758 \ube44\uc728\uc744 \uce21\uc815\ud55c\ub2e4. function calling performance\ub294 function call \ub2e8\uacc4\ub85c \uc815\uc0c1\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \uc9c4\ud589\ub41c \uc0ac\ub840\ub4e4\uc5d0 \ud55c\ud574 \uc2e4\uc81c function call\uc758 \uc815\ud655\uc131\uc744 \ud3c9\uac00\ud558\uba70, \uc138 \uac00\uc9c0 \uc138\ubd80 \uc9c0\ud45c\ub97c \uc0ac\uc6a9\ud55c\ub2e4. tool \uc120\ud0dd F1, key F1, \uadf8\ub9ac\uace0 argument F1\uc774\ub2e4.\\n\\nfunction calling \ud30c\ub77c\ubbf8\ud130 \uac80\uc99d\uc740 3\ub2e8\uacc4 \uc811\uadfc\ubc95\uc744 \uc0ac\uc6a9\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n1. Exact match \ube44\uad50\\n2. tool descriptions\uc5d0 \uae30\ubc18\ud55c type/pattern \uac80\uc99d\\n3. \ub098\uba38\uc9c0 \uc0ac\ub840\uc5d0 \ub300\ud55c semantic \uac80\uc99d\\n\\n\ubaa8\ub378 bias\ub97c \uc904\uc774\uae30 \uc704\ud574, \uc6b0\ub9ac\ub294 \uc138 \uac1c\uc758 LLM judges \u2014 GPT-4.1, Claude Sonnet 4, Gemini 2.5 Flash \u2014 \ub85c \uad6c\uc131\ub41c \uc559\uc0c1\ube14(ensemble)\uc744 \uc0ac\uc6a9\ud558\uba70, temperature\ub294 0.3\uc73c\ub85c \uc124\uc815\ud558\uace0 arithmetic mean\uc744 \ud1b5\ud574 \uc810\uc218\ub97c \uc9d1\uacc4\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\nLLM judge\ub294 true/false positives and negatives\uc744 \ubd84\ub958\ud558\uba70, \uc774\ub7ec\ud55c \ud310\uc815 \uacb0\uacfc\ub294 F1 \uacc4\uc0b0\uc5d0 \ud1b5\ud569\ub41c\ub2e4. \ud3c9\uac00\uc758 \uc2e0\ub8b0\uc131\uc744 \ucd94\uac00\ub85c \ud655\ubcf4\ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud574, annotator\uc640 LLM judge \uac04\uc758 judge \uac04 \uc77c\uce58\ub3c4(inter-rater agreement)\ub97c \uce21\uc815\ud558\uc600\uace0, \uadf8 \uacb0\uacfc Cohen\u2019s Kappa \uc810\uc218 0.63\uc744 \uc5bb\uc5c8\uc73c\uba70, \uc774\ub294 \uc0c1\ub2f9\ud55c \uc218\uc900\uc758 \uc77c\uce58\ub97c \uc758\ubbf8\ud55c\ub2e4. function calling training\uacfc\uc758 \ud638\ud658\uc131, \uc989 JSON \ucd9c\ub825 \ud615\uc2dd\uc744 \uc720\uc9c0\ud558\uae30 \uc704\ud574 call rejection\uacfc information requests\ub97c XML \ucd9c\ub825 \ud615\uc2dd\uc73c\ub85c \uad6c\ud604\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\n### 2. Evaluation Results\\n\\n![alt text](../assets/paper/OrchestrationBench/09-evaluation-results.png)\\n\\n\ucd5c\uace0 \uc131\ub2a5\uc740 bold, \ucc28\uc21c\uc704 \uc131\ub2a5\uc740 \ubc11\uc904\ub85c \ud45c\uc2dc\ub410\ub2e4. Claude \ubaa8\ub378\uc740 `anthropic.claude-sonnet-4-20250514-v1:0`\uc744 \uc0ac\uc6a9\ud558\uc5ec AWS Bedrock\uc744 \ud1b5\ud574 \ud3c9\uac00\ub410\ub2e4. workflow \uc810\uc218\ub294 1-GED\ub85c \uacc4\uc0b0\ub418\uace0 \uac12\uc774 \ub192\uc744\uc218\ub85d \uc131\ub2a5\uc774 \uc88b\ub2e4.\\n\\n**\ud575\uc2ec \ubc1c\uacac**\\n\\n**Open-Source Model Viability**\\n\\nQwen3-235B-A22B \uac19\uc740 \uc624\ud508\uc18c\uc2a4 dense \ubaa8\ub378\uc774 \uc0c1\uc6a9 \ubaa8\ub378\uc5d0 \uadfc\uc811\ud55c \uc131\ub2a5\uc744 \ubcf4\uc600\ub2e4. Dense \uc544\ud0a4\ud14d\ucc98\uac00 Mixture-of-Experts(MoE)\ubcf4\ub2e4 Planning \ud0dc\uc2a4\ud06c\uc5d0\uc11c \uc77c\uad00\ub418\uac8c \uc6b0\uc218\ud588\ub2e4.\\n\\n**Model-Specific Specializations**\\n\\nGemini\ub294 Planning\uc5d0\uc11c \ucd5c\uace0(\uc601\uc5b4 0.850)\ub97c \ubcf4\uc5ec\uc92c\uc9c0\ub9cc function calling\uc740 \uc57d\ud558\ub2e4. Claude-sonnet-4\ub294 Function Calling\uc5d0\uc11c \ucd5c\uace0(\uc601\uc5b4 0.885)\ub97c \uae30\ub85d\ud588\ub2e4. GPT-4.1\uc740 \uade0\ud615 \uc7a1\ud78c \uc131\ub2a5\uc744 \ubcf4\uc5ec\uc900\ub2e4. \ud2b9\ud788 workflow \uc0dd\uc131\uc740 \uc704\uc758 \uadf8\ub798\ud504\ub97c \ubcf4\uba74 \uc54c \uc218 \uc788\ub4ef\uc774 \uc601\uc5b4 \ubc0f \ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4 \ub370\uc774\ud130\uc14b \ubaa8\ub450\uc5d0\uc11c \ucd5c\uc0c1\uc704 \ubaa8\ub378\uacfc \ud558\uc704 \ubaa8\ub378 \uac04\uc5d0 \uc0c1\ub300\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \ud070 \uc131\ub2a5 \ud3b8\ucc28\ub97c \ubcf4\uc774\uace0, \ud3c9\uac00\ub41c task\ub4e4 \uc911\uc5d0\uc11c planning \ub2a5\ub825\uc774 \ucc28\ubcc4\ud654\ub418\ub294 \uc5ed\ub7c9\uc774\ub2e4.\\n\\n**Planning-Execution Gap**\\n\\nPlanning\uacfc Call/Reject \uac04 \uc0c1\uad00\uacc4\uc218\uac00 \uc601\uc5b4 0.58, \ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4 0.45\ub85c \uc0c1\ub300\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \ub0ae\ub2e4. planning\uacfc decision \uac04\uc758 \uc5f0\uad00\uc131\uc774 \uc0c1\ub300\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \uc57d\ud558\ub2e4. \uc989, \ubaa8\ub378\uc774 \uc88b\uc740 workflow\ub97c \uc0dd\uc131\ud558\ub354\ub77c\ub3c4 execution decision-making\uc774 \ubd80\uc815\ud655\ud560 \uc218 \uc788\ub2e4.\\n\\n**Language-Dependent Performance**\\n\\nClaude\ub294 \uc601\uc5b4 Call/Reject decision\uc5d0\uc11c 0.868\uc774\uc9c0\ub9cc \ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4\uc5d0\uc11c\ub294 0.759\ub85c \ud558\ub77d\ud55c\ub2e4. \ubc18\uba74 Gemini\ub294 \ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4\uc5d0\uc11c \ub354 \uac15\ud55c \uc131\ub2a5\uc744 \ubcf4\uc5ec\uc900\ub2e4. \uc774\ub294 \uc5b8\uc5b4\ubcc4 \ud559\uc2b5 \ud6a8\uacfc\uc640 \uc774\uc911 \uc5b8\uc5b4 \ud3c9\uac00\uc758 \uc911\uc694\uc131\uc744 \ub098\ud0c0\ub0b8\ub2e4.\\n\\n\uc774\ub7ec\ud55c \uacb0\uacfc\ub294 \uac15\ub825\ud55c \uac1c\ubcc4 \uc5ed\ub7c9\uc5d0\ub3c4 \ubd88\uad6c\ud558\uace0, planning-execution \uac04\uc758 \ucc28\uc774\uac00 \uc2e4\uc81c \ud658\uacbd\uc5d0\uc11c\uc758 \uc5d0\uc774\uc804\ud2b8\ud615 \uc131\ub2a5\uc744 \uc81c\ud55c\ud560 \uc218 \uc788\uc74c\uc744 \ubcf4\uc5ec\uc8fc\uba70 task-specific and language-aware \ubaa8\ub378 \uc120\ud0dd\uc758 \ud544\uc694\uc131\uc744 \uac15\uc870\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\n![alt text](../assets/paper/OrchestrationBench/10-metric-correlation.png)\\n\\n## Conclusion and Future Works\\n\\nOrchestrationBench\ub294 \ud604\uc2e4\uc801\uc778 multi-domain \uc11c\ube44\uc2a4 \ud658\uacbd\uc5d0\uc11c LLM \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158 \ub2a5\ub825\uc744 \ud3c9\uac00\ud558\ub294 \ucd5c\ucd08\uc758 \uc774\uc911\uc5b8\uc5b4(\uc601\uc5b4/\ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4) \ubca4\uce58\ub9c8\ud06c\uc774\ub2e4. \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158\uc744 workflow planning\uacfc tool execution \uc694\uc18c\ub85c \ubd84\ub9ac\ud568\uc73c\ub85c\uc368 agentic reasoning\uc758 \ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \uce21\uba74\uc5d0 \uac78\uce5c \ubaa8\ub378 \uc131\ub2a5\uc5d0 \ub300\ud55c \uc778\uc0ac\uc774\ud2b8\ub97c \uc81c\uacf5\ud55c\ub2e4.\\n\\n\ud575\uc2ec \uacb0\ub860\uc740 \ub450 \uac00\uc9c0\uc774\ub2e4.\\n- workflow planning\uc740 function calling\ubcf4\ub2e4 \ubaa8\ub378 \uac04 \uc131\ub2a5 \uaca9\ucc28\uac00 \ud6e8\uc52c \ud06c\uba70 \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158 task\uc5d0\uc11c \uc2e0\uc911\ud55c \ubaa8\ub378 \uc120\ud0dd\uc774 \ud544\uc694\ud558\ub2e4.\\n- \ubaa8\ub378\ub4e4\uc774 \ud568\uc218 \ud638\ucd9c\uc740 \uc798 \uc218\ud589\ud558\uc9c0\ub9cc, \uc2e4\uc81c \ud658\uacbd\uc5d0\uc11c\uc758 tool constraints\ub97c \uace0\ub824\ud574 function call\uc774 \uc801\uc808\ud55c\uc9c0 \ud310\ub2e8\ud558\ub294 call/reject \ubd84\ub958\uc5d0\uc11c\ub294 \uc5b4\ub824\uc6c0\uc744 \ubcf4\uc778\ub2e4.\\n\\n\ud55c\uacc4\ub3c4 \ub2e4\uc74c\uacfc \uac19\ub2e4.\\n- 17\uac1c \ub3c4\uba54\uc778\uc774 \ubaa8\ub4e0 \uc624\ucf00\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\uc158 \uc2dc\ub098\ub9ac\uc624\ub97c \ud3ec\ucc29\ud558\uac70\ub098 \ub2e4\ub978 \uc5b8\uc5b4\ub85c \uc77c\ubc18\ud654\ud558\uae30\uc5d0\ub294 \ubb34\ub9ac\uac00 \uc788\ub2e4.\\n- \uac00\uc0c1 \ub3c4\uad6c \uc0ac\uc6a9\uc73c\ub85c \uc2e4\uc81c API \ud1b5\ud569\uc758 \ubcf5\uc7a1\uc131\uc774 \ubc18\uc601\ub418\uc9c0 \uc54a\ub294\ub2e4.\\n- turn-by-turn \ud3c9\uac00\ub294 \uac01 step\uc5d0\uc11c\uc758 execution\uc774 \uc131\uacf5\uc801\uc73c\ub85c \uc774\ub8e8\uc5b4\uc9c4\ub2e4\uace0 \uac00\uc815\ud558\uae30\uc5d0 \uc804\uccb4 \uc131\ub2a5 \ub9e4\ud2b8\ub9ad\uc744 \uacfc\ub300\ud3c9\uac00\ud560 \uac00\ub2a5\uc131\uc774 \uc788\ub2e4.\\n\\n\ud5a5\ud6c4 \ubc29\ud5a5\uc740 \uc544\ub798\uc640 \uac19\ub2e4.\\n- MCP \uac19\uc740 \ud504\ub808\uc784\uc6cc\ud06c\ub97c \ud1b5\ud55c \uc2e4\uc81c multi-domain tool \ud1b5\ud569\\n- planning-execution \uac2d\uc744 \ud574\uacb0\ud558\ub294 \ud559\uc2b5 \ubc29\ubc95 \uac1c\ubc1c\\n- \ub354 \uc815\uad50\ud55c multi-agent \ud611\uc5c5 \ud328\ud134 \uc9c0\uc6d0"},{"id":"/Linked-List","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Linked-List","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2025-11-14-Linked-List/2025-11-14-Linked-List.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2025-11-14-Linked-List/2025-11-14-Linked-List.md","title":"Why Linked Lists Are Rarely Used in Python","description":"Things I looked up while studying linked lists out of curiosity","date":"2025-11-14T16:11:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Dev","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/dev"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2025-11-14 16:11","description":"Things I looked up while studying linked lists out of curiosity","draft":false,"slug":"/Linked-List","tags":["Dev"],"title":"Why Linked Lists Are Rarely Used in Python"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"[\ub17c\ubb38 \ub9ac\ubdf0] OrchestrationBench: LLM-Driven Agentic Planning and Tool Use in Multi-Domain Scenarios","permalink":"/en/blog/OrchestrationBench"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6AI Engineering","permalink":"/en/blog/ai-engineering"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n## Introduction\\nWhen studying data structures and algorithms, one inevitably learns about linked lists. However, in my development experience or when solving practical problems, I rarely had to implement or use linked lists directly. After learning the basic concepts long ago, I had almost no practical use cases for them. Even while preparing for coding tests recently, I rarely encountered problems that required linked lists. When I did, I mostly solved them using Python\'s `deque`, and my understanding was limited to the superficial knowledge that \\"linked lists are inefficient in Python.\\"\\n\\nThis led me to revisit linked lists and ask a fundamental question: \\"Why are linked lists not used often?\\" Simply attributing it to \\"inefficiency in Python\\" felt insufficient, so I wanted to investigate and organize the actual reasons. This post summarizes my research and reflections on the topic.\\n\\n## Why Linked Lists Are Rarely Used in Python\\n\\n:::caution\\nThis is not a claim that linked lists are never used. The title was changed from \\"Reasons Not to Use Linked Lists\\" to \\"Reasons Why Linked Lists Seem Not to Be Used\\" to reflect this.\\n:::\\n\\n:::info\\nEnglish comments in the code are from the original source.\\n:::\\n\\n### Dynamic Arrays\\nIn Python, linked lists are rarely used because the built-in `list` is implemented as a dynamic array, providing many of the advantages of linked lists. According to the CPython FAQ, a list is a contiguous array of pointers to other objects, and the list header contains a pointer to this array and its length. This structure ensures that accessing an element by index `a[i]` is always O(1), regardless of the list size.\\n\\n**Array**  \\n- Index access: O(1)  \\n- Contiguous memory  \\n- Insertion/deletion in the middle: O(n)  \\n- Appending at the end: Amortized O(1)  \\n\\n**Linked List**  \\n- Index access: O(n)  \\n- Scattered memory  \\n- Insertion/deletion (given a node): O(1)  \\n- Finding the insertion position: O(n)  \\n\\nThis is structurally similar to C\'s arrays and C++\'s `std::vector`. Below is the `PyListObject` definition from `cpython/Include/cpython/listobject.h`. The key part is `PyObject **ob_item`, which stores pointers to Python objects in a contiguous array.\\n\\n```cpp\\ntypedef struct {\\n    PyObject_VAR_HEAD\\n    /* Vector of pointers to list elements.  list[0] is ob_item[0], etc. */\\n    PyObject **ob_item;\\n\\n    /* ob_item contains space for \'allocated\' elements.  The number\\n     * currently in use is ob_size.\\n     * Invariants:\\n     *     0 <= ob_size <= allocated\\n     *     len(list) == ob_size\\n     *     ob_item == NULL implies ob_size == allocated == 0\\n     * list.sort() temporarily sets allocated to -1 to detect mutations.\\n     *\\n     * Items must normally not be NULL, except during construction when\\n     * the list is not yet visible outside the function that builds it.\\n     */\\n    Py_ssize_t allocated;\\n} PyListObject;\\n```\\n\\nHere, `ob_item` is allocated using `malloc`. When `append()` is called and the array is full, reallocation occurs. CPython uses a strategy to pre-allocate extra space to make multiple append operations efficient.\\n\\n- `cpython/Objects/lisobject.c`\\n```cpp\\n...\\nitems = PyMem_New(PyObject*, size);\\n...\\n```\\n\\n- `cpython/include/pymem.h`\\n```cpp\\n#define PyMem_New(type, n) \\\\\\n  ( ((size_t)(n) > PY_SSIZE_T_MAX / sizeof(type)) ? NULL :      \\\\\\n        ( (type *) PyMem_Malloc((n) * sizeof(type)) ) )\\n```\\n\\n- `cpython/Objects/obmalloc.c`\\n```cpp\\nvoid *\\nPyMem_Malloc(size_t size)\\n{\\n    /* see PyMem_RawMalloc() */\\n    if (size > (size_t)PY_SSIZE_T_MAX)\\n        return NULL;\\n    OBJECT_STAT_INC_COND(allocations512, size < 512);\\n    OBJECT_STAT_INC_COND(allocations4k, size >= 512 && size < 4094);\\n    OBJECT_STAT_INC_COND(allocations_big, size >= 4094);\\n    OBJECT_STAT_INC(allocations);\\n    return _PyMem.malloc(_PyMem.ctx, size);\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### Cache Locality\\nCache locality is an important factor that makes dynamic arrays more efficient than linked lists, not just in Python but also in C++.\\n\\nTheoretically, linked list insertions and deletions are O(1), but actual performance is heavily influenced by memory access patterns. CPUs have caches (L1, L2, L3) that are much faster than main memory (RAM). Accessing L1 cache takes about 1\u20132 ns, while accessing main memory takes about 60\u2013100 ns. Modern CPUs prefetch adjacent memory when accessing a location, leading to cache hits for contiguous memory like arrays. Linked lists, with scattered memory, often result in cache misses.\\n\\n**Array Example**  \\nMemory addresses: 1000   1008   1016   1024  \\nPointers: [ptr0] [ptr1] [ptr2] [ptr3] (contiguous memory)  \\nSequential access has high cache hit rates.\\n\\n**Linked List Example**  \\nMemory addresses: 1000        5432        2048        7890  \\nNodes: Node(1) \u2192 Node(2) \u2192 Node(3) \u2192 Node(4)  \\nEach node access may cause a cache miss.\\n\\nThus, arrays have near O(1) access due to cache hits, while linked lists suffer from O(n) access due to cache misses. This is why `std::vector` is preferred over `std::list` in C++ and Python\'s `list` over linked lists.\\n\\n### PyObject and Memory Overhead\\nIn Python, all values are represented as `PyObject` structures. Below is the `PyObject` definition from `cpython/Include/object.h`:\\n\\n```c\\n// PyObject base structure\\nstruct _object {\\n    _Py_ANONYMOUS union {\\n#if SIZEOF_VOID_P > 4 // 64-bit system\\n        PY_INT64_T ob_refcnt_full; /* For efficient initialization with Clang on ARM */ // 8 bytes\\n        struct {\\n#  if PY_BIG_ENDIAN\\n            uint16_t ob_flags; // 2 bytes\\n            uint16_t ob_overflow; // 2 bytes\\n            uint32_t ob_refcnt; // 4 bytes (reference count)\\n#  else\\n            uint32_t ob_refcnt;      \\n            uint16_t ob_overflow;\\n            uint16_t ob_flags;\\n#  endif\\n        }; // Union size is 8 bytes\\n#else\\n        Py_ssize_t ob_refcnt;\\n#endif\\n        _Py_ALIGNED_DEF(_PyObject_MIN_ALIGNMENT, char) _aligner;\\n    };\\n    PyTypeObject *ob_type;           // 8 bytes (type pointer)\\n};\\n```\\n\\nEvery Python object includes:\\n- Reference count: 8 bytes (union size)\\n- Type pointer: 8 bytes (64-bit system)\\n- Total: 16 bytes\\n\\n**C++ Node vs Python Node Comparison**\\n```c\\n// C++ Node structure\\nstruct Node {\\n    int val;        // 4 bytes\\n    // Padding: 4 bytes (for 8-byte alignment on 64-bit systems)\\n    Node* next;     // 8 bytes (64-bit pointer)\\n    Node(int v) : val(v), next(nullptr) {} // Constructor stored in code segment\\n};\\n\\nNode node(1);       // Instance creation\\n// Total: 16 bytes\\n```\\n\\n```python\\n# Python\\nclass Node:\\n    def __init__(self, val): # Constructor stored in class\\n        self.val = val\\n        self.next = None\\n\\nnode = Node(1)\\n```\\n\\nIn Python, object attributes are stored in a `__dict__` dictionary. For example:\\n```python\\nprint(node.__dict__)  # {\'val\': 1, \'next\': None}\\n```\\n\\nThus, the total memory usage includes both the object itself and the `__dict__`:\\n```python\\nimport sys\\nprint(sys.getsizeof(node))          # Object itself: 48 bytes\\nprint(sys.getsizeof(node.__dict__)) # Attribute dictionary: 64 bytes\\n# Total: 112 bytes (may vary by version)\\n```\\n\\nFor cases requiring insertions/deletions at both ends, Python\'s `collections.deque` is more efficient. Deque is a hybrid structure of linked lists and arrays, allowing O(1) operations at both ends while maintaining cache efficiency. Below is the deque structure from `cpython/Modules/_collectionsmodule.c`:\\n\\n```c\\n#define BLOCKLEN 64  // Each block size\\n\\n// Block structure - doubly linked list node\\ntypedef struct BLOCK {\\n    struct BLOCK *leftlink;      // Previous block pointer\\n    PyObject *data[BLOCKLEN];    // Array of 64 PyObject pointers\\n    struct BLOCK *rightlink;     // Next block pointer\\n} block;\\n\\nstruct dequeobject {\\n    PyObject_VAR_HEAD\\n    block *leftblock;\\n    block *rightblock;\\n    Py_ssize_t leftindex;       /* 0 <= leftindex < BLOCKLEN */\\n    Py_ssize_t rightindex;      /* 0 <= rightindex < BLOCKLEN */\\n    size_t state;               /* Incremented when indices move */\\n    Py_ssize_t maxlen;          /* -1 for unbounded deques */\\n    Py_ssize_t numfreeblocks;\\n    block *freeblocks[MAXFREEBLOCKS];\\n    PyObject *weakreflist;\\n};\\n```\\n\\nEach block is a doubly linked list node containing a fixed-size array. This structure allows O(1) operations at both ends while maintaining cache efficiency. However, deque has slightly more memory overhead than `list`, and middle insertions/deletions are still O(n), with indexing being O(1) only at the ends.\\n\\n```python\\nfrom collections import deque\\n\\n# Deque creation\\ndq = deque([1, 2, 3])\\n\\n# O(1) operations at both ends\\ndq.append(4)        # Right append: [1, 2, 3, 4]\\ndq.appendleft(0)    # Left append: [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]\\ndq.pop()            # Right pop: [0, 1, 2, 3]\\ndq.popleft()        # Left pop: [1, 2, 3]\\n\\n# Indexing (O(1) at ends, O(n) in the middle)\\nprint(dq[0]) # 1 - Left end, O(1) \\nprint(dq[-1]) # 3 - Right end, O(1) \\nprint(dq[1]) # 2 - Middle, O(n)\\n```\\n\\nThus, `deque` is suitable for stack/queue-like operations at the ends, while `list` is better for random access or middle insertions/deletions.\\n\\n## Cases Where Linked Lists Are Used in Python\\nDespite the above, linked lists are still useful in specific scenarios. Below are examples from Python\'s standard library and other systems.\\n\\n### Python `functools.lru_cache` Double Linked List\\nPython\'s `functools.lru_cache` uses a circular doubly linked list to implement LRU caching. The dictionary alone cannot track usage order, and using an array would make middle insertions/deletions O(n). The linked list allows O(1) operations when combined with a dictionary for O(1) lookups.\\n\\n```python\\ndef _lru_cache_wrapper(user_function, maxsize, typed, _CacheInfo):\\n    # Constants shared by all lru cache instances:\\n    sentinel = object()          # Unique object for cache misses\\n    make_key = _make_key         # Build a key from function arguments\\n    PREV, NEXT, KEY, RESULT = 0, 1, 2, 3   # Names for link fields\\n\\n    cache = {}\\n    hits = misses = 0\\n    full = False\\n    cache_get = cache.get    # Bound method to lookup a key or return None\\n    cache_len = cache.__len__  # Get cache size without calling len()\\n    lock = RLock()           # Because linkedlist updates aren\'t threadsafe\\n    root = []                # Root of the circular doubly linked list -> Sentinel node\\n    root[:] = [root, root, None, None]     # Initialize by pointing to self\\n```\\n\\nThe sentinel node (`root`) points to itself when the list is empty, simplifying edge cases. The dictionary provides O(1) lookups, and the linked list manages usage order. When a new item is added, it is inserted right after the root. When an existing item is accessed, it is moved to the front. If the cache is full, the least recently used item (root\'s previous node) is removed in O(1) time.\\n\\n### Python `weakref` Module\\nPython\'s `weakref` module uses linked lists to manage weak references. When an object is deleted, all weak references to it must be invalidated. The linked list allows O(1) removal when combined with a dictionary for O(1) lookups.\\n\\n```c\\n/* PyWeakReference is the base struct for Python ReferenceType, ProxyType, and CallableProxyType. */\\nstruct _PyWeakReference {\\n    PyObject_HEAD\\n\\n    /* The object to which this is a weak reference, or Py_None if none.\\n     * Note that this is a stealth reference:  wr_object\'s refcount is\\n     * not incremented to reflect this pointer.\\n     */\\n    PyObject *wr_object;\\n\\n    /* A callable to invoke when wr_object dies, or NULL if none. */\\n    PyObject *wr_callback;\\n\\n    /* Cache for wr_object\'s hash code. -1 if not known yet. */\\n    Py_hash_t hash;\\n\\n    /* If wr_object is weakly referenced, it has a doubly-linked NULL-terminated\\n     * list of weak references. These are the list pointers.\\n     * If wr_object goes away, wr_object is set to Py_None, and these pointers\\n     * have no meaning then.\\n     */\\n    PyWeakReference *wr_prev;\\n    PyWeakReference *wr_next;\\n    vectorcallfunc vectorcall;\\n\\n#ifdef Py_GIL_DISABLED\\n    /* Pointer to the lock used when clearing in free-threaded builds.\\n     * Normally this can be derived from wr_object, but in some cases we need\\n     * to lock after wr_object has been set to Py_None.\\n     */\\n    PyMutex *weakrefs_lock;\\n#endif\\n};\\n```\\n\\nThe `wr_prev` and `wr_next` pointers form a doubly linked list of weak references. When an object is deleted, the list is traversed to invalidate all weak references and call their callbacks.\\n\\n### Python `asyncio` Event Loop\\nThe `asyncio` event loop uses `deque` for the `_ready` queue, which is a hybrid of linked lists and arrays. The `_ready` deque allows O(1) operations at both ends, while the `_scheduled` list uses a heap for time-based sorting.\\n\\n```python\\nclass BaseEventLoop(events.AbstractEventLoop):\\n    def __init__(self):\\n        self._ready = collections.deque()  # Ready callbacks\\n        self._scheduled = []  # Time-sorted heap\\n        # ...\\n\\n    def call_soon(self, callback, *args, context=None):\\n        \\"\\"\\"Arrange for a callback to be called as soon as possible.\\"\\"\\"\\n        self._check_closed()\\n        if self._debug:\\n            self._check_thread()\\n            self._check_callback(callback, \'call_soon\')\\n        handle = self._call_soon(callback, args, context)\\n        if handle._source_traceback:\\n            del handle._source_traceback[-1]\\n        return handle\\n\\n    def _call_soon(self, callback, args, context):\\n        handle = events.Handle(callback, args, self, context)\\n        if handle._source_traceback:\\n            del handle._source_traceback[-1]\\n        self._ready.append(handle)  # O(1) append to deque\\n        return handle\\n\\n    def _run_once(self):\\n        \\"\\"\\"Run one full iteration of the event loop.\\"\\"\\"\\n        # Move timed-out scheduled callbacks to ready\\n        ready = self._ready\\n        self._ready = collections.deque()\\n        end_time = self.time()\\n        while self._scheduled:\\n            handle = self._scheduled[0]\\n            if handle._when > end_time:\\n                break\\n            handle = heapq.heappop(self._scheduled)\\n            ready.append(handle)\\n\\n        # ready is deque for efficient O(1) operations at both ends\\n        ntodo = len(ready)\\n        for _ in range(ntodo):\\n            handle = ready.popleft()\\n            if not handle._cancelled:\\n                handle._run()\\n```\\n\\nThe `_ready` deque is a block-based linked list, while `_scheduled` is a heap implemented as a dynamic array. This design leverages the strengths of both structures.\\n\\n## Other Cases Where Linked Lists Are Used\\n### Python `OrderedDict` Double Linked List\\nBefore Python 3.7, dictionaries did not preserve insertion order, so `OrderedDict` was used. The C implementation in `cpython/Objects/odictobject.c` uses a doubly linked list to maintain order.\\n\\n```c\\n/* PyODictObject */\\nstruct _odictobject {\\n    PyDictObject od_dict;        /* Underlying dict */\\n    _ODictNode *od_first;        /* First node in the linked list, if any */\\n    _ODictNode *od_last;         /* Last node in the linked list, if any */\\n    /* od_fast_nodes, od_fast_nodes_size, and od_resize_sentinel are managed\\n     * by _odict_resize().\\n     * Note that we rely on implementation details of dict for both. */\\n    _ODictNode **od_fast_nodes;  /* Hash table mirroring the dict table */\\n    Py_ssize_t od_fast_nodes_size;\\n    void *od_resize_sentinel;    /* Changes if odict should be resized */\\n\\n    size_t od_state;             /* Incremented whenever the LL changes */\\n    PyObject *od_inst_dict;      /* OrderedDict().__dict__ */\\n    PyObject *od_weakreflist;    /* Holds weakrefs to the odict */\\n};\\n\\n...\\n\\nstruct _odictnode {\\n    PyObject *key;\\n    Py_hash_t hash;\\n    _ODictNode *next;\\n    _ODictNode *prev;\\n};\\n```\\n\\nThe `od_fast_nodes` array mirrors the dictionary\'s hash table, allowing O(1) lookups while maintaining insertion order via the linked list.\\n\\n### Redis Sorted Set with Skip List and Double Linked List\\nRedis uses a skip list with backward pointers (a doubly linked list at level 1) for sorted sets. This allows O(log N) range queries and O(1) reverse traversal.\\n\\n```cpp\\n/* ZSETs are ordered sets using two data structures to hold the same elements\\n * in order to get O(log(N)) INSERT and REMOVE operations into a sorted\\n * data structure.\\n *\\n * The elements are added to a hash table mapping Redis objects to scores.\\n * At the same time the elements are added to a skip list mapping scores\\n * to Redis objects (so objects are sorted by scores in this \\"view\\").\\n *\\n * This skiplist implementation is almost a C translation of the original\\n * algorithm described by William Pugh in \\"Skip Lists: A Probabilistic\\n * Alternative to Balanced Trees\\", modified in three ways:\\n * a) this implementation allows for repeated scores.\\n * b) the comparison is not just by key (our \'score\') but by satellite data.\\n * c) there is a back pointer, so it\'s a doubly linked list with the back\\n * pointers being only at level 1. This allows to traverse the list\\n * from tail to head, useful for ZREVRANGE. */\\n```\\n\\nThe backward pointer at level 1 enables reverse traversal for commands like `ZREVRANGE`.\\n\\n### glibc `malloc` Free List\\nThe `malloc`/`free` implementation in glibc uses a linked list to manage free memory blocks. The next pointer is stored in the first few bytes of the free block, eliminating the need for additional memory.\\n\\n```c\\n// Free memory block linked list\\nstruct malloc_chunk {\\n  INTERNAL_SIZE_T mchunk_prev_size;  /* Previous chunk size */\\n  INTERNAL_SIZE_T mchunk_size;       /* Current chunk size */\\n  struct malloc_chunk* fd;           /* Forward link - next free block */\\n  struct malloc_chunk* bk;           /* Backward link - previous free block */\\n  struct malloc_chunk* fd_nextsize;  /* Next size for large chunks */\\n  struct malloc_chunk* bk_nextsize;  /* Previous size for large chunks */\\n};\\n\\n// Remove a free chunk from the list - O(1) operation\\nstatic void\\nunlink_chunk (mstate av, mchunkptr p)\\n{\\n  mchunkptr fd = p->fd;  // Pointer re-linking\\n  mchunkptr bk = p->bk;  // O(1) removal\\n  fd->bk = bk;\\n  bk->fd = fd;\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis design avoids extra memory allocation by storing pointers within the free blocks themselves.\\n\\n### libstdc++ `unordered_map` Chaining\\nThe C++ standard library\'s `std::unordered_map` uses chaining with linked lists to resolve hash collisions. This allows O(1) insertions in the case of collisions.\\n\\n```cpp\\n// Single linked list for collision resolution\\nstruct _Hash_node_base {\\n  _Hash_node_base* _M_nxt;  // Next node pointer\\n\\n  _Hash_node_base() noexcept : _M_nxt() { }\\n  _Hash_node_base(_Hash_node_base* __next) noexcept : _M_nxt(__next) { }\\n};\\n\\n// Node storing the actual value\\ntemplate<typename _Value, bool _Cache_hash_code>\\nstruct _Hash_node : _Hash_node_base,\\n                    _Hash_node_value<_Value, _Cache_hash_code> {\\n  _Hash_node* _M_next() const noexcept {\\n    return static_cast<_Hash_node*>(this->_M_nxt);\\n  }\\n};\\n```\\n\\nEach bucket points to a linked list of colliding elements, allowing efficient insertions.\\n\\n### Linux Kernel Intrusive Doubly Linked List\\nThe Linux kernel provides an intrusive doubly linked list in `include/linux/list.h`. This design allows any structure with a `list_head` field to be part of a linked list.\\n\\n```c\\nstruct list_head {\\n    struct list_head *next, *prev;\\n};\\n\\n// Initialization - self-referential\\n#define LIST_HEAD_INIT(name) { &(name), &(name) }\\n\\nstatic inline void INIT_LIST_HEAD(struct list_head *list) {\\n    WRITE_ONCE(list->next, list);\\n    WRITE_ONCE(list->prev, list);\\n}\\n\\n// O(1) insertion\\nstatic inline void __list_add(struct list_head *new,\\n                struct list_head *prev,\\n                struct list_head *next) {\\n    next->prev = new;\\n    new->next = next;\\n    new->prev = prev;\\n    WRITE_ONCE(prev->next, new);\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis intrusive design allows the same list operations to be reused across different data structures, such as task scheduling and memory management.\\n\\n### Chromium `base::LinkedList` Intrusive List\\nChromium uses its own `base::LinkedList` implementation, which is intrusive and allows O(1) deletions without needing to search for the element.\\n\\n```cpp\\n// Chromium\'s intrusive linked list implementation\\ntemplate <typename T>\\nclass LinkedList {\\n public:\\n  // The \\"root\\" node is self-referential, forming the basis of a circular list.\\n  LinkedList() { root_.set(&root_, &root_); }\\n  LinkedList(const LinkedList&) = delete;\\n  LinkedList& operator=(const LinkedList&) = delete;\\n  \\n  // Move constructor (use with care if nodes are stack-allocated)\\n  LinkedList(LinkedList&& other) : root_(std::move(other.root_)) {\\n    other.root_.MakeSelfReferencing();\\n  }\\n\\n  // Appends |e| to the end of the linked list\\n  void Append(LinkNode<T>* e) { e->InsertBefore(&root_); }\\n\\n  LinkNode<T>* head() const { return root_.next(); }\\n\\n  LinkNode<T>* tail() const { return root_.previous(); }\\n\\n  const LinkNode<T>* end() const { return &root_; }\\n\\n  bool empty() const { return head() == end(); }\\n\\n private:\\n  LinkNode<T> root_;\\n};\\n```\\n\\nThis design avoids the overhead of reallocating and copying elements, making it suitable for scenarios where multiple iterators need to remain valid during modifications.\\n\\n## Summary\\nWhile linked lists are rarely used directly in Python for general-purpose programming, they are still essential in specific scenarios and system-level implementations. The built-in `list` and `deque` provide most of the functionality needed for everyday tasks, but linked lists shine in cases requiring efficient insertions/deletions at known positions or when memory constraints demand intrusive designs.\\n\\nThe main takeaway is that unless a problem explicitly requires implementing a linked list, it\'s unlikely you\'ll need to use one in coding tests or general development. However, understanding their strengths and weaknesses is crucial for designing efficient systems.\\n\\nBelow is a comparison of time complexity and implementation examples in Python and C++.\\n\\n| Operation     | `list`           | `deque` | Custom Linked List |\\n| ----------- | ---------------- | ------- | ------------------ |\\n| Append      | O(1) amortized   | O(1)    | O(n) (find end)    |\\n| Prepend     | O(n)             | O(1)    | O(1)               |\\n| Pop from end| O(1)             | O(1)    | O(n) (find end)    |\\n| Pop from front| O(n)           | O(1)    | O(1)               |\\n| Index access| O(1)             | O(1)    | O(n)               |\\n| Memory efficiency| High         | Medium  | Low                |\\n| Cache efficiency| High         | Medium  | Low                |\\n\\n## Implementation Examples\\n\\n### Python\\n```python\\nclass Node:\\n    def __init__(self, val):\\n        self.val = val\\n        self.next = None  # Each node has its value and a pointer to the next node\\n\\nclass LinkedList:\\n    def __init__(self):\\n        self.head = None  # Pointer to the first node\\n\\n    def insert_front(self, val):\\n        node = Node(val)\\n        node.next = self.head\\n        self.head = node\\n\\n    def insert_back(self, val):\\n        # If the list is empty, set head to the new node\\n        if not self.head:\\n            self.head = Node(val)\\n            return\\n        # Traverse to the end\\n        cur = self.head\\n        while cur.next:\\n            cur = cur.next\\n        cur.next = Node(val)\\n\\n    def delete(self, val):\\n        # If the list is empty, return\\n        if not self.head:\\n            return\\n        # If the head is the target, remove it\\n        if self.head.val == val:\\n            self.head = self.head.next\\n            return\\n        # Traverse to find the node before the target\\n        cur = self.head\\n        while cur.next:\\n            if cur.next.val == val:\\n                cur.next = cur.next.next\\n                return\\n            cur = cur.next\\n```\\n\\n### C++\\n```cpp\\n#include <iostream>\\n\\nusing namespace std;\\n\\nstruct Node {\\n    int val;\\n    Node* next;\\n    Node(int v) : val(v), next(nullptr) {}\\n};\\n\\nclass LinkedList {\\npublic:\\n    Node* head;\\n    \\n    LinkedList() : head(nullptr) {}\\n    \\n    // Insert at the front\\n    void insert_front(int val) {\\n        Node* node = new Node(val);\\n        node->next = head;\\n        head = node;\\n    }\\n    \\n    // Insert at the end\\n    void insert_back(int val) {\\n        if (head == nullptr) {\\n            head = new Node(val);\\n            return;\\n        }\\n        Node* cur = head;\\n        while (cur->next != nullptr) {\\n            cur = cur->next;\\n        }\\n        cur->next = new Node(val);\\n    }\\n    \\n    // Delete a value\\n    void delete_value(int val) {\\n        if (head == nullptr)\\n            return;\\n            \\n        // If head is the target\\n        if (head->val == val) {\\n            Node* temp = head;\\n            head = head->next;\\n            delete temp;\\n            return;\\n        }\\n        \\n        // Traverse to find the node before the target\\n        Node* cur = head;\\n        while (cur->next != nullptr) {\\n            if (cur->next->val == val) {\\n                Node* temp = cur->next;\\n                cur->next = cur->next->next;\\n                delete temp;\\n                return;\\n            }\\n            cur = cur->next;\\n        }\\n    }\\n    \\n    // Print the list\\n    void print() {\\n        Node* cur = head;\\n        while (cur != nullptr) {\\n            cout << cur->val << \\" -> \\";\\n            cur = cur->next;\\n        }\\n        cout << \\"NULL\\\\n\\";\\n    }\\n};\\n\\nint main() {\\n    LinkedList list;\\n\\n    list.insert_front(3);\\n    list.insert_front(2);\\n    list.insert_front(1);\\n\\n    list.insert_back(4);\\n    list.insert_back(5);\\n\\n    list.print(); // 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5 -> NULL\\n\\n    list.delete_value(3);\\n    list.print(); // 1 -> 2 -> 4 -> 5 -> NULL\\n\\n    list.delete_value(1);\\n    list.print(); // 2 -> 4 -> 5 -> NULL\\n\\n    return 0;\\n}\\n```\\n\\n## References\\n- [CPython GitHub](https://github.com/python/cpython)\\n- [CPython Design and History FAQ](https://docs.python.org/3/faq/design.html#how-are-lists-implemented-in-cpython)\\n- [Latency Numbers Every Programmer Should Know](https://gist.github.com/jboner/2841832)\\n- [Approximate cost to access various caches and main memory - Stack Overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4087280/approximate-cost-to-access-various-caches-and-main-memory)\\n- [Redis GitHub](https://github.com/redis/redis/)\\n- [Linux Kernel GitHub](https://github.com/torvalds/linux)"},{"id":"/ai-engineering","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/ai-engineering","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2025-10-26-AI-Engineering/2025-10-26-AI-Engineering.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2025-10-26-AI-Engineering/2025-10-26-AI-Engineering.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6AI Engineering","description":"A one-stop guide to AI app development: From designing to improving systems using foundation models","date":"2025-10-26T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2025-10-26","description":"A one-stop guide to AI app development: From designing to improving systems using foundation models","draft":false,"slug":"/ai-engineering","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6AI Engineering"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Why Linked Lists Are Rarely Used in Python","permalink":"/en/blog/Linked-List"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Hands-on LLM","permalink":"/en/blog/hands-on-llm"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media \\"I am a Reviewer\\" activity, where I was provided with the book.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2025](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2025.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/ai-engineering.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000217939673)\\n\\n- **Title**: AI Engineering  \\n- **Author**: Chip Huyen  \\n- **Translator**: Seongyun Byun  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: September 10, 2025  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nIt\u2019s been a long time since I last read a book in bits and pieces. Lately, my days have been flying by with open-source contributions and job preparation, leaving no time to fully immerse myself in a book. Honestly, I considered skipping this month\u2019s \\"I am a Reviewer\\" activity due to my busy schedule. But when I heard that Seongyun Byun had translated a new book from Hanbit Media, I decided to apply and read it.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Product-Centric AI Engineering  \\n\\nThe author begins by critiquing how traditional machine learning has been trapped in a \\"model-centric\\" mindset. Reading this made me reflect on how obsessed I\u2019ve been with model performance alone. The book defines AI engineering as a **product-centric** approach, asking not \u201cwhat can we build?\u201d but \u201cwhy should we build it?\u201d  \\n\\nI found the structure of explaining AI systems in three layers\u2014**application development, model development, and infrastructure**\u2014particularly insightful. The emphasis on placing user problems and needs at the forefront of AI application design resonated deeply with me.  \\n\\nWhat stood out most was the contrast between today\u2019s ease of creating AI prototypes with APIs and the entirely different challenge of scaling them into **production-ready services**. It\u2019s not just about a few lines of model-calling code but about building a system that includes evaluation, monitoring, and feedback loops to ensure **stable, long-term growth**. This reinforced my understanding that AI engineering isn\u2019t about maximizing model accuracy but about creating systems people can trust and use.  \\n\\n### Evaluation & Operations  \\n\\nMy favorite chapter was Chapter 3. The author\u2019s focus on **evaluation** feels like the book\u2019s core. Until now, I\u2019ve measured model performance mainly through accuracy or F1 scores, but this book reveals how limited that perspective is.  \\n\\nChapter 3 addresses the open-ended nature of foundation models, asking: **\u201cWhen there\u2019s no single correct answer, what criteria should we use to evaluate?\u201d** The discussion on balancing metrics like latency, cost, safety, bias, and user experience was eye-opening.  \\n\\nI was especially intrigued by the concept of **\u201cAI as a Judge,\u201d** where models evaluate other models. While not perfect, this approach feels like a pragmatic solution. It showed me that Chip Huyen isn\u2019t just writing a technical guide but is deeply considering how to **integrate AI systems into society**.  \\n\\nThe latter half walks through how an API-based prototype evolves through stages: **context enrichment \u2192 guardrail addition \u2192 model router setup \u2192 caching and feedback loops**. It felt like watching a small side project grow into a real service\u2014inspiring me to incorporate systematic evaluation and feedback into my own projects.  \\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\n\\n- AI/ML majors curious about **AI productization**  \\n- Learners wanting a structured understanding of **LLM/generative AI internals and engineering practices**  \\n- Developers interested in **AI system design with FastAPI, LangChain, AWS, etc.**  \\n- Students in AI startups, labs, or project teams seeking **real-world skills**  \\n- Readers who enjoyed *Designing Machine Learning Systems* and want a **more practical follow-up*"},{"id":"/hands-on-llm","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/hands-on-llm","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2025-07-27-hands-on-llm/2025-07-27-hands-on-llm.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2025-07-27-hands-on-llm/2025-07-27-hands-on-llm.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Hands-on LLM","description":"From prompt engineering to embeddings, semantic search, and fine-tuning: Practical LLM concepts you can grasp  \\n\\n*(Note: The translation preserves the original\'s concise, hands-on tone while ensuring natural English flow. The phrase \\"\uc190\uc5d0 \uc7a1\ud788\ub294\\" is rendered as \\"practical... you can grasp\\" to convey both accessibility and actionable understanding.)*  \\n\\n**Final translation per instructions (without notes):**  \\nFrom prompt engineering to embeddings, semantic search, and fine-tuning: Practical LLM concepts you can grasp","date":"2025-07-27T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2025-07-27","description":"From prompt engineering to embeddings, semantic search, and fine-tuning: Practical LLM concepts you can grasp  \\n\\n*(Note: The translation preserves the original\'s concise, hands-on tone while ensuring natural English flow. The phrase \\"\uc190\uc5d0 \uc7a1\ud788\ub294\\" is rendered as \\"practical... you can grasp\\" to convey both accessibility and actionable understanding.)*  \\n\\n**Final translation per instructions (without notes):**  \\nFrom prompt engineering to embeddings, semantic search, and fine-tuning: Practical LLM concepts you can grasp","draft":false,"slug":"/hands-on-llm","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Hands-on LLM"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6AI Engineering","permalink":"/en/blog/ai-engineering"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Developer Technical Interview Notes","permalink":"/en/blog/Technical-Interview-Notes-for-Developers"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity, where the book was provided for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2025](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2025.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\nimage.png  \\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/hands-on-llm.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000216550234)  \\n\\n- **Title:** Developer Technical Interview Notes  \\n- **Authors:** Jay Alammar, Marten Hulingdorst  \\n- **Translator:** Park Haesun  \\n- **Publisher:** Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date:** June 10, 2025  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}  \\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nLarge Language Models (LLMs) are now essential knowledge not just for developers, but also for researchers, students, planners, and many other fields. While I\u2019ve studied LLM principles and applications over time, I\u2019ve struggled to solidify my fundamentals amid the flood of new tools and techniques. *Hands-On LLM* gave me the chance to systematically review core concepts and practice hands-on exercises\u2014all in one place.  \\n\\nI picked up this book wanting to revisit LLMs in a structured way, and I\u2019m genuinely satisfied with the result. Studying LLMs feels like an endless journey\u2014new models, tools, and approaches keep emerging. That\u2019s why this book\u2019s emphasis on **fundamentals** resonated deeply with me.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### The Best Choice for \u201cRelearning\u201d LLMs  \\n\\nThis isn\u2019t just an introductory guide for LLM beginners. Even if you already know concepts like Transformers, Fine-Tuning, or Embeddings, this book excels as a guide to connect those dots cohesively.  \\n\\nPreviously scattered ideas from blogs and papers finally clicked when I read **Chapter 3** (on Transformer architecture). The intuitive visuals and seamless integration of hands-on exercises made me repeatedly think, *\u201cOh, that\u2019s how it works!\u201d*  \\n\\n### Visual Explanations + Hands-On Practice  \\n\\nThe book\u2019s strongest points are its **visualizations** and **practical exercises**.  \\n\\nEach chapter includes dozens of color diagrams, example illustrations, and code output images, making even complex concepts easy to grasp.  \\n\\nWith setups for Hugging Face, Colab, and other tools, you can jump straight into practice without extra environment setup. Real-world examples like prompt engineering, clustering, and RAG pipeline construction helped me build practical skills.  \\n\\nPersonally, **Chapter 5** (BERTopic), **Chapter 7** (LangChain\u2019s ReAct), and **Chapter 12** (Fine-Tuning Generative Models) stood out as especially insightful.  \\n\\n### Not a Shortcoming, but a Clear Audience Prerequisite  \\n\\nThis book isn\u2019t for complete beginners. As the authors note in the preface, some Python and machine learning background is necessary for smooth reading.  \\n\\nAdditionally, it doesn\u2019t cover infrastructure, cost optimization, or deployment for production\u2014so readers seeking real-world application details may need supplementary resources.  \\n\\nHowever, the book\u2019s focus is clear: **\u201cUnderstand LLMs deeply and learn to work with them hands-on.\u201d** And it delivers on that promise admirably.  \\n\\n## Target Audience  \\n\\n- Anyone who wants to revisit LLM principles and key concepts through **visual explanations and practical exercises**  \\n- Readers who\u2019ve pieced together knowledge from blogs or papers and want a **structured, comprehensive review**  \\n- Those looking to systematically learn LLM applications like chatbots, embedding-based search, and prompt optimization  \\n- Learners who want to follow recent LLM trends (LangChain, RAG, LoRA) through **hands-on practice**"},{"id":"/Technical-Interview-Notes-for-Developers","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Technical-Interview-Notes-for-Developers","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2025-05-31-Technical-Interview-Notes-for-Developers/2025-05-31-Technical-Interview-Notes-for-Developers.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2025-05-31-Technical-Interview-Notes-for-Developers/2025-05-31-Technical-Interview-Notes-for-Developers.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Developer Technical Interview Notes","description":"A 20-Year Kakao Interviewer\'s Guide to Landing a Job/Transitioning at Big Tech Companies","date":"2025-05-31T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2025-05-31","description":"A 20-Year Kakao Interviewer\'s Guide to Landing a Job/Transitioning at Big Tech Companies","draft":false,"slug":"/Technical-Interview-Notes-for-Developers","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Developer Technical Interview Notes"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Hands-on LLM","permalink":"/en/blog/hands-on-llm"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83c\udfacThe first and final post. The end.","permalink":"/en/blog/geultto-Recap"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post is part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity, written after receiving the book.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2025](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2025.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book cover to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n[![Book](../assets/review/Technical-Interview-Notes-for-Developers.png)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000216231695)\\n\\n- **Title**: Technical Interview Notes for Developers  \\n- **Author**: Namhee Lee  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: April 7, 2025  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nIt\u2019s been a while since I last applied for a book review. My internship is almost over, and I\u2019ve been thinking about my next steps\u2014when I saw this book on technical interviews, I knew I had to apply. Written by a 20-year veteran interviewer from Kakao, it\u2019s essentially a guide for landing or switching jobs at big tech companies. Reading it gave me a clear picture of what technical interviews entail and how to prepare.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### A Technical Interview Guide from an Intern\u2019s Perspective  \\n\\nLately, I\u2019ve heard a lot about how tough the developer job market is. Even as an intern, I know that whether I aim for full-time conversion or apply elsewhere, coding tests and technical interviews are unavoidable.  \\n\\nWhile I\u2019m slowly getting the hang of real-world work, I still felt lost about how to write a resume or what to study for technical interviews. Then I found this book\u2014and it turned out to be a surprisingly practical guide.  \\n\\n### Gaining Direction in an Overwhelming Job Search  \\n\\nThe book smoothly outlines the entire hiring process: resume preparation \u2192 coding tests/technical interviews \u2192 post-interview steps. It\u2019s not just another algorithm problem book; it also covers how to analyze job postings, resume-writing tips, and frequently asked interview questions.  \\n\\nMy favorite parts were:  \\n\\n- **Job posting analysis**: I learned how to identify skills I need to improve, beyond just skimming the listing.  \\n- **Resume pitfalls**: Seeing examples of rejected resumes helped me avoid common mistakes.  \\n- **Technical interview prep**: The book clarified what to study for topics like databases, OS, networks, and architecture.  \\n- **Study habits & growth mindset**: It reinforced how to approach career growth, which was invaluable for my long-term planning.  \\n\\n### Why Interns Should Start Preparing Early  \\n\\nAs an intern, keeping up with real work is already hectic, and preparing for full-time conversion feels rushed. But this book made me realize that starting now\u2014even gradually\u2014will make the process much less daunting later.  \\n\\nTechnical interviews require a surprisingly broad and deep knowledge base. Balancing prep with work isn\u2019t easy, but at least having a roadmap gives me peace of mind.  \\n\\nWhat I loved most is that the book goes beyond technical skills\u2014it also discusses the mindset needed for growth and work. It\u2019s packed with insights for building a sustainable career.  \\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\n\\nI\u2019d recommend this to **any junior developer**. In fact, anyone below senior level would benefit\u2014it covers everything from resumes and portfolios to technical and behavioral interviews, offering practical tips for the entire hiring process."},{"id":"/geultto-Recap","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/geultto-Recap","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2025-03-30-geultto-Recap/2025-03-30-geultto-Recap.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2025-03-30-geultto-Recap/2025-03-30-geultto-Recap.md","title":"\ud83c\udfacThe first and final post. The end.","description":"A truly wonderful and warm community","date":"2025-03-30T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Recap","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/recap"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2025-03-30","description":"A truly wonderful and warm community","draft":false,"keywords":["Gleatto","Community","Growth"],"slug":"/geultto-Recap","tags":["Recap"],"title":"\ud83c\udfacThe first and final post. The end."},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Developer Technical Interview Notes","permalink":"/en/blog/Technical-Interview-Notes-for-Developers"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Deep Learning from Scratch 1 (Remastered Edition)","permalink":"/en/blog/deep-learning-from-scratch-remastered"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n## Geulddo Season 10\\n\\n### Wrap-Up\\n\\nIt\u2019s hard to believe that Geulddo Season 10 is already over. Time really flies\u2014it\u2019s been six months since I started Geulddo. Before writing this post, I revisited my [first and last Geulddo start post](https://teddygood.github.io/blog/starting-geulddo) after a long time. It was a glimpse into my past self, filled with unreasonable goals and grand resolutions. I wonder how I ever thought I could tackle all of that. I guess I just set big goals, even if I knew I\u2019d fail some.\\n\\nWhile drafting this, I briefly considered using headings like \\"What I Did in Geulddo, What I Gained from Geulddo,\\" but I didn\u2019t want to make it too formal. Looking back, I didn\u2019t participate as actively as I\u2019d hoped. I failed to meet my goal of writing without skipping days, and my aim to have coffee chats with diverse people also fell short by my own standards. The small group activities didn\u2019t involve skiing or sledding\u2014just casual hangouts. I wanted to explore more through Geulddo, and it\u2019s a bit regrettable that I couldn\u2019t.\\n\\nHowever, Geulddo gave me a sense of relief. During October and November, while I was juggling job preparation, the small groups provided a much-needed breather. Reflecting on October, I have no idea how I managed graduation project prep, job hunting, small group activities (gaming), schoolwork, and study sessions all at once. Despite the stress of that hectic life, being part of a group left no room for loneliness. That\u2019s definitely something I\u2019m grateful for.\\n\\nGeulddo also helped me understand myself better. I never deeply considered what I truly wanted to do before. If I felt like studying tech, I\u2019d just do it. I lived practically: university studies, then job hunting post-graduation. But during a coffee chat, someone casually asked, \\"What do you want to do?\\" I\u2019d never thought about that, so I couldn\u2019t answer immediately. Since then, I\u2019ve made a habit of regularly asking myself what I truly desire, checking if my actions align with my genuine aspirations.\\n\\nLastly, Geulddo became a medium that made me ponder how to write better. Before, my mindset was, \\"This is my blog, so I\u2019ll write whatever I want.\\" Now, I think about what readers might find interesting. That\u2019s a huge step for me\u2014it\u2019s shifted my perspective to a more audience-centric approach.\\n\\n### What\u2019s Next?\\n\\nMy short-term goal is to wrap up my current internship well. With about three months left (roughly two and a half if you exclude the evaluation period), I want to live a slightly more intentional life than I have been. I\u2019ll try to plan systematically.\\n\\nLong-term, I aim to clarify what I truly want and continue self-discovery. I plan to read more books, study deeper, and dedicate more time to both than I do now.\\n\\nWhile this is abstract, I\u2019ll keep detailed plans to myself\u2014they\u2019re TMI.\\n\\nGeulddo, thank you for everything! \ud83d\ude4f"},{"id":"/deep-learning-from-scratch-remastered","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/deep-learning-from-scratch-remastered","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2025-02-28-deep-learning-from-scratch-remastered/2025-02-28-deep-learning-from-scratch-remastered.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2025-02-28-deep-learning-from-scratch-remastered/2025-02-28-deep-learning-from-scratch-remastered.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Deep Learning from Scratch 1 (Remastered Edition)","description":"Deep Learning Theory and Implementation with Python","date":"2025-02-28T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2025-02-28","description":"Deep Learning Theory and Implementation with Python","draft":false,"slug":"/deep-learning-from-scratch-remastered","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Deep Learning from Scratch 1 (Remastered Edition)"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83c\udfacThe first and final post. The end.","permalink":"/en/blog/geultto-Recap"},"nextItem":{"title":"Hands-on Generative AI Development with Amazon Bedrock","permalink":"/en/blog/Hands-on-generative-AI-dev-with-AWS-Bedrock"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post is a book review written as part of the Hanbit Media \\"I am a Reviewer\\" activity, for which the book was provided.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2025](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2025.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n[![Book](../assets/review/deep-learning-from-scratch-remastered.png)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000215599933)\\n\\n- **Title**: Deep Learning from Scratch 1 (Remastered Edition)  \\n- **Author**: Saito Goki  \\n- **Translator**: Gaepyeon Lee (\uac1c\uc55e\ub9f5\uc2dc)  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: January 24, 2025  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\nOnce again, I\u2019m grateful to participate in Hanbit Media\u2019s \\"I am a Reviewer\\" program in 2025. It\u2019s truly a privilege to read books, write reviews, and access Hanbit Media\u2019s publications more easily than others. This time, I read *Deep Learning from Scratch 1 (Remastered Edition)*. Originally published in January 2017, this book has played a significant role in deep learning education in Korea. It\u2019s a book that has genuinely helped many people take their first steps into deep learning. The remastered edition makes it even more reader-friendly.\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\nFor my previous review of the original edition, you can visit [this link](http://localhost:3000/blog/deep-learning-from-scratch). In this review, I\u2019ll focus on the changes and improvements in the remastered version rather than summarizing the content. If you\u2019re curious about other updates, I recommend reading [[Rebirth Story] Deep Learning from Scratch 1 (Remastered Edition)](https://www.hanbit.co.kr/channel/category/category_view.html?cms_code=CMS2416204088&cate_cd=).\\n\\n### Full-Color Design\\n\\nThe most noticeable change is the switch from black-and-white to full-color pages. While the original\u2019s monochrome aesthetic had its charm\u2014evoking the feel of classic papers\u2014the new color scheme makes the content more engaging and visually accessible. It\u2019s refreshing to see publishers prioritizing reader experience, even if production costs rise.\\n\\n### Code Improvements\\n\\nIn the first edition, managing working directories was crucial, but the remastered version simplifies this process.  \\n\\n![Code Example](../assets/code-deep-learning.png)  \\n\\nPreviously, code was only available as Python files, but now it\u2019s also provided in Jupyter Notebook format for Google Colab. This is a fantastic improvement\u2014readers can experiment with code directly in the browser without setting up a local environment.  \\n\\nAdditionally, the code has been updated to address warnings from libraries like `matplotlib` and `numpy`, ensuring compatibility with modern setups.\\n\\n### Expanded Series Overview\\n\\nThe book now includes an introduction to other titles in the series. If you\u2019re hooked after reading this one, the subsequent books offer deeper dives. I\u2019m particularly excited about the upcoming *Deep Learning from Scratch 6*, which will focus on LLMs.  \\n\\nChapter 8, the final chapter, includes more detailed \\"NOTE\\" sections compared to the original. These notes guide readers to other books in the series for advanced topics\u2014a feature I appreciate. A good book should always point you toward the next step, and this one does that well.\\n\\n## Recommended Audience\\n\\nThis book is ideal for anyone looking to start their deep learning journey. After reading it, you\u2019ll have a solid foundation in the fundamentals. I also recommend exploring the other books in the series afterward. Whenever friends, colleagues, or peers ask me how to begin with deep learning, I always point them to this book first. It\u2019s an excellent starting point and truly worth the read."},{"id":"/Hands-on-generative-AI-dev-with-AWS-Bedrock","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Hands-on-generative-AI-dev-with-AWS-Bedrock","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2025-02-02-Hands-on-generative-AI-dev-with-AWS-Bedrock/2025-02-02-Hands-on-generative-AI-dev-with-AWS-Bedrock.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2025-02-02-Hands-on-generative-AI-dev-with-AWS-Bedrock/2025-02-02-Hands-on-generative-AI-dev-with-AWS-Bedrock.md","title":"Hands-on Generative AI Development with Amazon Bedrock","description":"Now AI Becomes Your Development Tool - The Complete AWS Gen AI Guide for Practitioners","date":"2025-02-02T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2025-02-02","description":"Now AI Becomes Your Development Tool - The Complete AWS Gen AI Guide for Practitioners","draft":false,"keywords":["Amazon Bedrock","Generative AI","AWS"],"slug":"/Hands-on-generative-AI-dev-with-AWS-Bedrock","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"Hands-on Generative AI Development with Amazon Bedrock"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Deep Learning from Scratch 1 (Remastered Edition)","permalink":"/en/blog/deep-learning-from-scratch-remastered"},"nextItem":{"title":"\u27282024 Reflection","permalink":"/en/blog/2024-Recap"}},"content":"## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!  \\n:::\\n[![Book](..%2Fassets%2Freview%2FHands-on-generative-AI-dev-with-AWS-Bedrock.png)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000214962344)  \\n-  \\n- Title: *Hands-on Generative AI Development with Amazon Bedrock*  \\n- Authors: Lim Ji-hoon, Choi Sung-woo  \\n- Publisher: Digital Books  \\n- Release Date: 2025-01-10  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}  \\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nRecently, I had to use AWS Bedrock at work, so I was studying the official documentation. While browsing LinkedIn, I found out this book was published and decided to buy and read it. Microsoft and Google are dominating the generative AI space, but Amazon recently unveiled the Nova model and seems to be pushing harder with Bedrock. Though a bit late, I think it\u2019s a positive move. AWS Bedrock is a platform for using generative AI models, and I wanted to learn how to apply it in real-world scenarios through this book.  \\n\\n## ## Book Review  \\n\\n### Bedrock  \\n\\nBedrock is a fully managed generative AI platform provided by AWS. It collaborates with partners like AI21 Labs, Anthropic, Cohere, Meta, Mistral AI, and Stability AI to offer various models. Unfortunately, OpenAI is not included. The book covers how to use Bedrock via the website, how to apply generative AI models through code, and the features Bedrock provides.  \\n\\n### Overall Book Review  \\n\\nThe book is organized into 9 chapters. Uniquely, it starts with Chapter 0\u2014a rare sight outside appendices, which I found amusing and very \\"developer-like.\\" Chapter 0 kindly guides readers through AWS sign-up, IAM (which can be daunting for beginners), and setting up the AWS CLI for coding. Even those new to AWS should find this book accessible.  \\n\\nChapter 1 briefly explains what generative AI is and how Bedrock differs from SageMaker. Chapter 2 introduces the Bedrock website\u2019s playground for testing models, model overviews, and simple coding exercises. Chapter 3 covers prompt engineering, while Chapter 4 explains how to implement RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) with Bedrock, including its Knowledge Bases feature. This section also integrates additional AWS services.  \\n\\nChapter 5 discusses building Agents with Bedrock, and Chapter 6 explores model training\u2014impressively, Bedrock supports Fine-Tuning and Continued Pre-Training. I recall doing this with SageMaker before, but now it\u2019s unnecessary. The book also explains importing external models for training.  \\n\\nChapter 7 covers operational features, including Guardrails for detecting hallucinations\u2014a surprising and useful tool. Model evaluation features are also highlighted, showing Bedrock\u2019s robustness. Finally, Chapter 8 briefly introduces the latest Bedrock updates.  \\n\\n## Target Audience  \\n\\nIf you\u2019re interested in generative AI\u2014especially RAG, Agents, or practical applications\u2014this book is a great read. Even without AWS experience, you\u2019ll find it approachable. Generative AI costs scale with usage, so experimenting with models isn\u2019t prohibitively expensive. Dive into this book to explore various models hands-on!"},{"id":"/2024-Recap","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/2024-Recap","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2025-01-18-2024-Recap/2025-01-18-2024-Recap.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2025-01-18-2024-Recap/2025-01-18-2024-Recap.md","title":"\u27282024 Reflection","description":"Looking back on 2024  \\n(Note: The original text is incomplete, as it only says \\"Looking back on 2024\\" without further content. If you\'d like to expand this into a reflective essay or add specific content about 2024, I\'d be happy to help!)  \\n\\nSince you requested only the translation, here is the direct rendering:  \\n**\\"Looking back on 2024\\"**  \\n\\nLet me know if you\'d like to develop this further!","date":"2025-01-18T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Recap","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/recap"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2025-01-18","description":"Looking back on 2024  \\n(Note: The original text is incomplete, as it only says \\"Looking back on 2024\\" without further content. If you\'d like to expand this into a reflective essay or add specific content about 2024, I\'d be happy to help!)  \\n\\nSince you requested only the translation, here is the direct rendering:  \\n**\\"Looking back on 2024\\"**  \\n\\nLet me know if you\'d like to develop this further!","draft":false,"keywords":["Recap","2024"],"slug":"/2024-Recap","tags":["Recap"],"title":"\u27282024 Reflection"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Hands-on Generative AI Development with Amazon Bedrock","permalink":"/en/blog/Hands-on-generative-AI-dev-with-AWS-Bedrock"},"nextItem":{"title":"\u2728November Reflection","permalink":"/en/blog/Nov-Recap"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\nIt\'s hard to believe how quickly time has passed. The year has flown by so fast. This year was filled with significant changes and growth for me. In this post, I want to reflect on the transformations and progress I\u2019ve experienced in 2024.\\n\\n## Graduation Project\\n\\nI\u2019ve been gradually training myself to read papers while studying ML, and now I realize it was all preparation for this graduation project. I don\u2019t think I\u2019ve ever read as many papers as I did this year. Although I didn\u2019t follow the latest papers, I\u2019ve read most of the seminal works in Computer Vision, such as GANs and NeRF.\\n\\nStill, I chose not to pursue a research career. While learning new technologies was fun, I doubted my ability to write groundbreaking papers that would impact the world. If I ever wanted to go to grad school, I thought working first and then attending a part-time or overseas program could be a good option. So, I decided to become an engineer\u2014studying, implementing, and creating value through technology.\\n\\nAlthough it wasn\u2019t an official research internship, I\u2019m grateful to BCML for giving me an indirect experience of lab life through my graduation project. I truly felt the professor\u2019s dedication. Every meeting was conducted in English, which was a unique experience. Except for special occasions like holidays or exams, we had weekly meetings. Honestly, I didn\u2019t expect such guidance since we weren\u2019t official lab interns. Of course, our project\u2019s success would benefit the lab, but I\u2019m still thankful for the time and direction they provided. I\u2019d also like to thank the TAs who helped us every week, guiding us on how to implement and proceed with the project. Their support in setting up experiments, tools, and environments was invaluable.\\n\\nIn return, our team worked hard every week to produce meaningful results. I want to express my gratitude to my team through this post. They took responsibility and saw the project through for almost a year. It was the best team and project I\u2019ve had in college. This effort eventually led us to win an award at the graduation project exhibition.\\n\\n## GDSC\\n\\nThis community leaves me with a lot of regrets. The first cohort ended without continuing to a second one. I was an ML member and participated in the Solution Challenge, where I worked on a chatbot project using LangChain and some GCP services.\\n\\nI was also disappointed that the ML paper study group, where we read and presented papers, was discontinued. It would have greatly improved my presentation skills. Still, the monthly seminars gave me a chance to present in front of others for the first time, helping me grow.\\n\\n## GeulTto (\uae00\ub610)\\n\\nThanks to GeulTto, I wrote more blog posts this year than last. I\u2019ve always had the habit of writing while studying, but I didn\u2019t post them online. The first reason was that I didn\u2019t want to write the same content as others. I wanted my posts to reflect my unique experiences. Otherwise, I felt they\u2019d be no different from wikis or other blogs. This challenge still isn\u2019t easy, but I keep trying to write differently.\\n\\nSecond, writing for myself is simple and straightforward, but blogging requires considering the reader. For example, when writing technical posts, I want them to be easy to understand. This makes the writing process longer. I\u2019ve learned not to stress too much about pleasing everyone.\\n\\nOn a side note, I spent a lot of time in the GeulTto gaming channel, \\"GameTto.\\" With stress from job prep and the graduation project, playing League of Legends with GeulTto members once a week was a great relief. I also had fun meeting offline at T1 Base Camp. Additionally, attending the backend-infra meetup unexpectedly helped me. Although I\u2019d already secured an internship, I felt unprepared. At the meetup, someone offered to introduce me to employees at the company I\u2019d joined, which led to valuable connections. I\u2019m truly grateful for that opportunity and to GeulTto for fostering such relationships.\\n\\n## NIPA-Google ML Bootcamp Collaborative Project\\n\\nDuring the break, I spent 3 hours daily commuting to participate in a practical project run by NIPA and Google\u2019s ML Bootcamp. I considered quitting multiple times but persisted, believing I\u2019d gain something. In the end, I completed a chatbot project for my resume and gained experience collaborating with five people. Mid-project, I visited Google Korea and had the chance to talk to Googlers. I remember asking a lot of questions\u2014probably more than anyone else.\\n\\n## Job Preparation\\n\\nI started job hunting in September. First, I organized my projects and tailored my resume to the job descriptions (JDs) of the companies and roles I was applying for. While my projects weren\u2019t perfect, I highlighted the technologies I used to match the JDs. I invested everything into one company. It took a month just to finalize my resume, constantly asking, \\"How can I stand out?\\"\\n\\nDuring this process, I want to thank someone who helped me. In May, our school hosted alumni from various companies. One speaker was a senior from my university and a current employee at the company I now work for. I attended the talk and got their business card. Later, in October, after drafting my resume, I cold-mailed them for feedback. Thankfully, they gladly helped, and with their input, I passed the document screening.\\n\\nAs a foreign company, I expected a slow process, but it was surprisingly fast. Previously, Google\u2019s intern process felt sluggish, so this one seemed quicker. Each stage\u2019s result came out the next day or within two days.\\n\\nAfter passing the document screening, things got tough. Preparing for the graduation exhibition, tech interviews, and loop interviews all at once was overwhelming. For tech interviews, I reviewed and memorized all my CS knowledge. For loop interviews, I organized my experiences using the STAR format and practiced speaking. Eventually, after the exhibition and loop interviews, I was accepted as a cloud intern. I feel incredibly lucky.\\n\\n## Reading\\n\\n- *Deep Learning Fundamentals*\\n- *Becoming a Better Programmer*\\n- *Developing LLM-Based AI Services with LangChain*\\n- *AI Truth*\\n- *Flow: The Psychology of Optimal Experience*\\n- *The One Thing*\\n- *Open*\\n- *Software Engineer Guidebook*\\n- *What Makes a Winning Team*\\n\\nI read 9 books this year. One was for self-study, two were self-help books I chose, and the rest were provided by Hanbit Media. Since 2021, they\u2019ve greatly contributed to my growth. I want to express my gratitude through this reflection. I hope to continue participating in their \\"I\u2019m a Reviewer\\" program next year.\\n\\nEven though I\u2019ll be busy as an intern next year, I plan to read more, including novels."},{"id":"/Nov-Recap","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Nov-Recap","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2024-12-02-Nov-Recap/2024-12-02-Nov-Recap.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2024-12-02-Nov-Recap/2024-12-02-Nov-Recap.md","title":"\u2728November Reflection","description":"Reflecting on a busy November filled with graduation projects and job preparation.","date":"2024-12-02T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Recap","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/recap"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2024-12-02","description":"Reflecting on a busy November filled with graduation projects and job preparation.","draft":false,"keywords":["Recap","November"],"slug":"/Nov-Recap","tags":["Recap"],"title":"\u2728November Reflection"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\u27282024 Reflection","permalink":"/en/blog/2024-Recap"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Software Engineer Guidebook","permalink":"/en/blog/The-SE-guidebook"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\nThe reason retrospectives are always scary might be because they force me to face my past self from the previous month. Just like October, I didn\u2019t live up to my own expectations in November, and I\u2019m afraid to write this reflection\u2014but I\u2019m trying anyway.\\n\\n## Reading\\n\\n- **Software Engineer Guidebook**\\n\\nAs mentioned in [my book review](https://teddygood.github.io/blog/The-SE-guidebook), this is a must-read for any software engineer. As we gain experience, our roles expand or change. This book helped me understand the roles and skills required as I grow from a junior to a staff engineer. It also includes some soft skills, making it very helpful. I plan to read it again before work.\\n\\n## Personal Study\\n\\nIn my university\u2019s liberal arts math course, I revisited computer-related topics like Huffman coding and the JPEG compression process. I also got a condensed introduction to challenging fields such as information theory, cryptography, data mining, artificial intelligence, and fractal theory.\\n\\n## Graduation Project\\n\\nI prepared for the graduation project exhibition by reviewing the papers we applied, the progress meeting slides, and more. The exhibition concluded successfully, though I was too nervous to explain well when three professors evaluated our work. We received a **Consolation Prize**, which felt rewarding after all our efforts. While I aimed for the highest **Grand Prize**, I was grateful just to be recognized, as there were many outstanding projects.\\n\\nI had planned to write a separate retrospective on the graduation project but will likely skip it\u2014maybe just mention it briefly in my 2024 reflection.\\n\\n## Job Preparation\\n\\n### Resume Writing\\n\\nI\u2019ve finalized my English resume and applied to my top-choice company. I passed the document screening and completed the OA (Online Assessment), and now I\u2019m preparing for interviews. After this process, I\u2019ll draft a Korean resume as well.\\n\\n### Organizing Past Projects\\n\\nI\u2019m still organizing projects from school, some with over 2,000 lines of code. It\u2019s been challenging to document everything, especially since I\u2019m rewriting comments in English and studying the overall structure. I\u2019m focusing on the projects listed in my resume.\\n\\n### Algorithms\\n\\nMy original goal was to solve three problems daily, but I\u2019ve scaled it back to one due to time constraints. I solve problems on LeetCode (Easy/Medium) within a set morning timeframe, compare my solutions with official ones, and reflect on approaches. This process consumes more time than expected.\\n\\n## Networking\\n\\n### **Gangbuk Eodosaram Itto** (There Are People in Gangbuk Too)\\n\\nI attended a **Gangbuk Eodosaram Itto** meetup through GeulTto. Contrary to expectations, it was held in Chungmuro, not Nowon, and it was fun to travel far for a change. We discussed development, grad school, and various topics, which helped me clarify some concerns. My biggest worry\u2014\u201cI don\u2019t know which field to pursue\u201d\u2014was addressed with advice to either focus on versatility or specialize deeply. Both awkward and enjoyable, the meetup was a great chance to share and hear others\u2019 struggles and experiences. Community support is powerful.\\n\\n### Carrot Tech Meetup\\n\\nI attended the **Carrot Tech Meetup** and listened to Data/ML talks, plus networked with Carrot teams (though recruitment networking slots filled too fast). My takeaway: I\u2019ll no longer consider **MLOps** or **Data Engineering** roles. These paths usually require prior experience or internal transitions, and even though I wondered if new grads could break in, I\u2019ve decided to let it go\u2014especially after a related study group.  \\n\\nIf aiming for **MLE (Machine Learning Engineer)**, strong ML fundamentals and coding test prep are key. User service experience is a plus but not expected for new grads. Kaggle projects were also recommended.\\n\\n## English Study\\n\\nI tried using ChatGPT\u2019s **Advanced Voice Mode** for speaking practice, but it was surprisingly difficult. Speaking from scratch was a new challenge, and I couldn\u2019t stick with it as a habit.\\n\\n## November Goals\\n\\n- Balance reading/networking without hindering job prep\\n- Solve 1 LeetCode problem daily\\n- Interview preparation\\n- Finalize graduation project exhibition\\n- No new study groups\\n\\nCompared to October, my goals are simpler\u2014interviews take priority, leaving little room for else.  \\n\\nI\u2019ve been detailed, but I\u2019m still afraid of failing my own promises. Since I\u2019ve pinned this on my blog, I\u2019ll try not to be ashamed of myself. Regardless of the outcome, I\u2019ll give it my best."},{"id":"/The-SE-guidebook","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/The-SE-guidebook","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2024-11-26-The-SE-guidebook/2024-11-26-The-SE-guidebook.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2024-11-26-The-SE-guidebook/2024-11-26-The-SE-guidebook.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Software Engineer Guidebook","description":"Essential Career Management Secrets Every Software Engineer Should Know, from Junior to Leader","date":"2024-11-26T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2024-11-26","description":"Essential Career Management Secrets Every Software Engineer Should Know, from Junior to Leader","draft":false,"slug":"/The-SE-guidebook","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Software Engineer Guidebook"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\u2728November Reflection","permalink":"/en/blog/Nov-Recap"},"nextItem":{"title":"Why Alpine Linux Should Be Avoided When Choosing a Docker Base Image for Python Projects","permalink":"/en/blog/python-alpine-linux"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media \\"I am a Reviewer\\" activity, where I was provided with the book.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2024](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2024.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/The-SE-guidebook.png)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000214576874)\\n\\n- **Title**: The Software Engineer Guidebook  \\n- **Author**: Gergely Orosz  \\n- **Translator**: Minseok Lee  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: October 30, 2024  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nI\u2019ve been swamped with job preparation lately. Still, I want to give myself credit for squeezing in time to read this book little by little. I almost didn\u2019t get to finish the parts I needed, but after securing an internship, I finally had time to sit down with it at home. The phrase \u201cFrom Junior to Leader\u201d made me wonder, *\u201cIs this even a book for someone like me who hasn\u2019t landed a job yet?\u201d* But curiosity got the better of me, and I dove in.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Overall Review  \\n\\n**Part 1** covers how to design and manage your career\u2014touching on performance reviews, promotions, job changes, and how to prepare for them. It\u2019s packed with topics juniors would eventually grapple with. I was especially struck by the advice on keeping a work journal to document your contributions.  \\n\\n**Part 2** dives into how to work *well* as a developer. While some points might seem obvious to seasoned engineers, the granular tips are refreshing, especially for newcomers. **Part 3**, labeled for senior engineers, isn\u2019t exclusive to them. It discusses time management, team collaboration, testing, and architecture\u2014all valuable for juniors who\u2019ll eventually need these skills. It\u2019s like a sneak peek into senior life, and that\u2019s a plus.  \\n\\n**Part 4** focuses on leadership\u2014project management, decision-making, launches, and stakeholders. The stakeholder section stood out; it\u2019s not just for tech leads but anyone dealing with non-technical collaborators. **Part 5** tackles staff and principal engineer roles, emphasizing business acumen and customer-centric thinking\u2014skills even juniors should start cultivating.  \\n\\nFinally, **Part 6** wraps up with the timeless advice, \u201cNever Stop Learning,\u201d and an appendix featuring insights from Korean senior engineers on growth, AI\u2019s impact, and more. These real-world perspectives were a highlight\u2014I don\u2019t often get to hear from such experienced professionals.  \\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\n\\nThis book is for *every* engineer, regardless of level. I\u2019d especially recommend it to those *before* their first job. While most learn processes on the job, starting with this mindset could make the transition smoother. Plus, revisiting it later might reveal new insights. I\u2019m grateful I found this before stepping into the workplace."},{"id":"/python-alpine-linux","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/python-alpine-linux","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2024-11-24-python-alpine-linux/2024-11-24-python-alpine-linux.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2024-11-24-python-alpine-linux/2024-11-24-python-alpine-linux.md","title":"Why Alpine Linux Should Be Avoided When Choosing a Docker Base Image for Python Projects","description":"Troubleshooting Issues When Deploying a Python Backend with Docker  \\n(Note: The original Korean text was a title/heading, so the translation reflects that structure. If you need elaboration on specific problems/solutions, additional context would be required.)  \\n\\n**Alternative (if intended as a sentence):**  \\n\\"I encountered and resolved issues while attempting to deploy a Python backend using Docker.\\"  \\n\\nLet me know if you\'d like a detailed troubleshooting guide or specific problem-solution pairs!","date":"2024-11-24T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Troubleshooting","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/troubleshooting"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2024-11-24","description":"Troubleshooting Issues When Deploying a Python Backend with Docker  \\n(Note: The original Korean text was a title/heading, so the translation reflects that structure. If you need elaboration on specific problems/solutions, additional context would be required.)  \\n\\n**Alternative (if intended as a sentence):**  \\n\\"I encountered and resolved issues while attempting to deploy a Python backend using Docker.\\"  \\n\\nLet me know if you\'d like a detailed troubleshooting guide or specific problem-solution pairs!","draft":false,"keywords":["Docker","Python","Alpine Linux"],"slug":"/python-alpine-linux","tags":["Troubleshooting"],"title":"Why Alpine Linux Should Be Avoided When Choosing a Docker Base Image for Python Projects"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Software Engineer Guidebook","permalink":"/en/blog/The-SE-guidebook"},"nextItem":{"title":"\u2728October Reflection","permalink":"/en/blog/Oct-Recap"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n## Introduction\\n\\nI encountered several errors while moving a Django blog project to Docker. This post shares the knowledge I gained while resolving these issues.\\n\\n## First Problem\\n\\n### Compatibility Issue Between Alpine Linux and cryptography\\n\\nWhile building after creating the `Dockerfile` and `docker-compose.yml`, I encountered the following error:\\n\\n```\\nERROR: No matching distribution found for cryptography==3.4.7\\n```\\n\\nThe Docker image version and cryptography version in `requirements.txt` were as follows:\\n\\n```Dockerfile\\nFROM python:3.8-alpine\\n```\\n\\n```bash\\ncryptography==3.4.7\\n```\\n\\n### Solution\\n\\nI realized this was a compatibility issue between Alpine Linux and the cryptography package, which implements cryptographic algorithms in Python. After consulting the [official cryptography documentation](https://cryptography.io/en/latest/installation/), I found a solution.\\n\\n![crypto-doc](../assets/troubleshooting/cryptography-doc.jpg)\\n\\nIn summary, cryptography uses Rust for building. This means **cargo**, Rust\'s package manager and build tool, must also be installed. I added the following to the Dockerfile:\\n\\n```shell\\n$ sudo apk add gcc musl-dev python3-dev libffi-dev openssl-dev cargo\\n```\\n\\nThis resolved the first issue.\\n\\n## Second Problem\\n\\n### Build Process Took Too Long and Failed\\n\\nAfter adding the above commands to the Dockerfile and rebuilding, another error occurred. The build process kept running indefinitely (showing \\"still running\\") for about 10 minutes before eventually stopping.\\n\\n![More detailed error](../assets/troubleshooting/crypto-building-error.jpg)\\n\\n### Solution\\n\\nAfter extensive research, I revisited the cryptography documentation and GitHub issues to find a similar case.\\n\\n![More detailed error](../assets/troubleshooting/alpine-linux-build-issue.jpg)\\n\\nThe key points from the issue were:\\n\\n1. Building Python packages on Alpine Linux is slow, especially in CI/CD environments where rebuilding is frequent.\\n2. Uploading Alpine-compatible wheels requires changes to pip/wheel/packaging, which involves ongoing PEP discussions.\\n3. Installing Python packages properly on newer Alpine versions requires the latest Rust compiler.\\n4. These issues are documented, and no improvements are currently planned. If further issues arise, new issues or PRs should be submitted.\\n\\nThe core takeaway was that **Alpine Linux itself was the problem**. Switching the base image resolved the issue:\\n\\n```Dockerfile\\nFROM python:3.8-slim-buster\\n```\\n\\nBut why did this happen? Let\'s explore the reasons.\\n\\n## Why Alpine Linux Is Not Ideal for Python Environments\\n\\nI initially chose Alpine Linux because it\u2019s smaller and faster to build compared to Ubuntu. However, it\u2019s not well-suited for Python environments.\\n\\nThe key difference lies in the C standard libraries used. Most Linux distributions use **GNU C Library (glibc)** for C programs, including Python. However, Alpine Linux uses **musl libc** for lightweight optimization. Since musl doesn\u2019t support `Wheel binaries` compiled with glibc, it downloads `.tar.gz` files instead of `.whl` files. This means **all Python packages with C extensions must be compiled from source**, leading to longer build times and larger image sizes.\\n\\nMost modern Python packages include precompiled Wheel binaries on PyPI, which are essentially ZIP archives with a `.whl` extension. These speed up installations significantly. However, Alpine Linux bypasses this optimization.\\n\\n### Drawbacks of Using Alpine Linux for Python:\\n1. **Slow builds** due to source compilation.\\n2. **Larger image sizes** from compiled dependencies.\\n3. **Wasted time** waiting for builds.\\n4. **Potential runtime bugs** from compatibility issues.\\n\\nFor Python projects, Debian-based **slim images** or **Ubuntu-based images** are more suitable than Alpine Linux.\\n\\n## \ud83c\udf10 References\\n\\n- [Cryptography installation](https://cryptography.io/en/latest/installation/)\\n- [Dependencies to build on Alpine Linux?](https://github.com/pyca/cryptography/issues/5776)\\n- [How to Build Docker Images Efficiently](https://jonnung.dev/docker/2020/04/08/optimizing-docker-images/)\\n- [Using Alpine Can Make Python Docker Builds 50x Slower](https://pythonspeed.com/articles/alpine-docker-python/)\\n- [The Best Docker Base Image for Python Applications](https://pythonspeed.com/articles/base-image-python-docker-images/)"},{"id":"/Oct-Recap","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Oct-Recap","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2024-11-10-Oct-Recap/2024-11-10-Oct-Recap.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2024-11-10-Oct-Recap/2024-11-10-Oct-Recap.md","title":"\u2728October Reflection","description":"Looking back on a busy October filled with graduation projects and job preparation.","date":"2024-11-09T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Recap","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/recap"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2024-11-09","description":"Looking back on a busy October filled with graduation projects and job preparation.","draft":false,"keywords":["Recap","October"],"slug":"/Oct-Recap","tags":["Recap"],"title":"\u2728October Reflection"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Why Alpine Linux Should Be Avoided When Choosing a Docker Base Image for Python Projects","permalink":"/en/blog/python-alpine-linux"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Open","permalink":"/en/blog/open"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\nIn my previous post, I wrote about my [October Goals](https://teddygood.github.io/blog/starting-geulddo#10%EC%9B%94-%EB%AA%A9%ED%91%9C). I\u2019m writing this to check if I achieved them. I\u2019m a bit scared to write this because I didn\u2019t live up to October, but I\u2019ll try anyway.\\n\\n## Reading\\n\\n- *Flow: The Psychology of Optimal Experience* (\ubab0\uc785\uc758 \uc990\uac70\uc6c0)\\n- *The One Thing* (\uc6d0\uc53d)\\n- *Open* (\uc624\ud508)\\n\\nI read these three books. While reading, I reflected a lot and questioned whether I\u2019m trying to do too much. I\u2019ve been eliminating things that I think aren\u2019t immediately necessary for me right now.\\n\\nMy goal was to read an hour before bed, and I did well for the first week. But I got too sleepy and found it annoying to keep proving I was reading, so I stopped. Now, I read when I feel like it or on weekend mornings when I have time.\\n\\nI\u2019m currently reading *Software Engineer Guidebook* ([\uc18c\ud504\ud2b8\uc6e8\uc5b4 \uc5d4\uc9c0\ub2c8\uc5b4 \uac00\uc774\ub4dc\ubd81](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000214576874)). If I finish this and have time, I\u2019d like to read *Not Going My Way* ([\uc791\ubcc4\ud558\uc9c0 \uc54a\ub294\ub2e4](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000000781116)) by Han Kang.\\n\\n## Study Groups\\n\\n- **ETL Study ([Learning Spark](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000061353994))**: This was a study group with data engineers and software engineers. I learned a lot from their real-world experiences. My only regret is that I couldn\u2019t complete the project after finishing the book because my graduation project became too time-consuming.\\n- **Algorithms Study ([Coursera Stanford Algorithms](https://www.coursera.org/specializations/algorithms))**: This course was mathematically intense and quite challenging. However, approaching algorithms conceptually helped me understand time complexity better and improved my problem-solving skills.\\n- **DDIA Study ([Designing Data-Intensive Applications](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000001766328))**: Most participants were data engineers and software engineers, so I learned a lot. However, the content was too advanced for me, and I had to quit due to my graduation project workload.\\n\\nLooking back, it seems like I quit all my study groups. With my graduation project nearing completion, I had to prioritize that. I think I should revisit *Designing Data-Intensive Applications* when I\u2019m less busy. It\u2019s a book that would benefit from group discussions and shared experiences.\\n\\n## Personal Study\\n\\n- **Causal Inference**: I started strong in the first week but stopped. It\u2019s a field I wanted to study, but I decided it\u2019s not a priority right now. Job preparation takes precedence.\\n- **JavaScript**: I finished *Core JavaScript* ([\ucf54\uc5b4 \uc790\ubc14\uc2a4\ud06c\ub9bd\ud2b8](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000001766397)). It was concise and informative. Although I\u2019m not pursuing frontend development, the book was easy to read.\\n- **School Math Lectures**: I took a liberal arts course covering linear algebra, probability & statistics, and some information theory. It wasn\u2019t too hard since I\u2019d studied most of it before.\\n\\n## Graduation Project\\n\\nThe project is almost done. We\u2019ve been testing our algorithm repeatedly to ensure it works. Then, we focused on creating a poster. We had mandatory team meetings three times a week and biweekly meetings with our professor. The teaching assistant gave great feedback, helping us create a clean and visually appealing poster.\\n\\nI\u2019ll share a detailed retrospective on the graduation project later.\\n\\n## Job Preparation\\n\\n### Resume\\n\\nI finished my English resume and applied to my top-choice company. I passed the document screening and the OA test. Now, I\u2019m preparing for the interview. After this process, I\u2019ll write a Korean resume.\\n\\n### Previous Project Code Cleanup\\n\\nI\u2019m still organizing projects from school. Some have over 2,000 lines of code, and it\u2019s been tough to summarize everything. I\u2019m adding English comments and understanding the overall structure, focusing on projects mentioned in my resume.\\n\\n### Algorithms\\n\\nMy original goal was to solve three problems daily, but I reduced it to one due to time constraints. I solve one problem each morning within a set time. Afterward, I review the solution and compare it with mine, which takes a lot of time. I\u2019m focusing on approach strategies for easy and medium LeetCode problems.\\n\\n## Networking\\n\\n### Gangbuk E Dosam Itto (\uac15\ubd81\uc5d0\ub3c4\uc0ac\ub78c\uc788\ub610)\\n\\nI attended a **Gangbuk E Dosam Itto** meetup. I expected to meet in Nowon, but it was held in Chungmuro. It was fun to go out and meet people. We discussed development, grad school, and various topics. My biggest concern was, \u201cI don\u2019t know which field to pursue,\u201d and the advice to either focus on versatility or specialize deeply resonated with me.\\n\\nIt was half awkward, half fun, but meeting new people is always enjoyable. Sharing my concerns and hearing others\u2019 experiences was motivating. Communities truly have a powerful impact.\\n\\n### Carrot Tech Meetup\\n\\nI attended the Carrot Tech Meetup by luck. I listened to Data/ML talks and networked with various Carrot teams. Networking was first-come, first-served, and I missed the chance to talk with the recruitment team, which was disappointing.\\n\\nAfterward, I decided not to consider MLOps or data engineering roles. These roles are usually pursued through internal transitions, and I realized I shouldn\u2019t hope for new grad opportunities. This conclusion also came from my data engineering study group experience.\\n\\nIf I want to become an MLE, I need to strengthen my ML basics and coding test skills. User service experience is a plus but not expected for new grads. Project experience, like Kaggle, was also recommended.\\n\\n## English Study\\n\\nI tried using ChatGPT\u2019s Advanced Voice Mode for English conversation practice, but it was challenging. Speaking was entirely new to me, and I couldn\u2019t make it a habit.\\n\\n## November Goals\\n\\n- Reading and networking\u2014only if they don\u2019t interfere with job preparation\\n- Solve one LeetCode problem daily\\n- Interview preparation\\n- Finalize graduation project exhibition\\n- No study groups\\n\\nMy November goals are much simpler than October\u2019s. With interviews coming up, I can\u2019t take on too much.\\n\\nI\u2019ve written them down concretely, but I\u2019m still afraid of breaking my own promises. But since I\u2019ve posted this on my blog, I should at least try not to be ashamed of myself. Regardless of the outcome, I\u2019ll give it my best shot."},{"id":"/open","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/open","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2024-10-27-open/2024-10-27-open.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2024-10-27-open/2024-10-27-open.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Open","description":"The Key to Business Hegemony","date":"2024-10-27T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2024-10-27","description":"The Key to Business Hegemony","draft":false,"slug":"/open","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Open"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\u2728October Reflection","permalink":"/en/blog/Oct-Recap"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83c\udfacFirst and Last Glottal Start","permalink":"/en/blog/starting-geultto"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post was written as part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity, where I received the book for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2024](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2024.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/open.png)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000214413027)\\n\\n- **Title**: Open  \\n- **Author**: Park Soo-hong  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: September 30, 2024  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\nWhen I think back to the first time I learned about open source, it was during middle school. I had just decided to become a programmer and was reading **How to Be a Programmer** (published by Hanbit Media). The book featured interviews with legendary programmers like Linus Torvalds and Richard Stallman, and that\u2019s where I first encountered the term **open source**. (As a side note, I highly recommend reading it if you get the chance\u2014it includes interviews with the creators of Java, C++, email, and Apple computers, among others. Though I didn\u2019t grasp much at the time, the term became unavoidable once I entered computer science.) I even took a course where contributing to open source was a goal. Today, I still follow open-source news through various communities and social media. That\u2019s why I was curious about this book and decided to apply as a reviewer.\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### Prologue\\n\\nThe book starts with an engaging prologue:\\n\\n> **Open has an agenda.**\\n\\nThis line really makes you think. Over the past few years, I\u2019ve consumed a lot of IT trend content on social media and communities, including plenty about open source. Initially, I only knew the positives\u2014sharing knowledge, accessibility, transparency. But as I learned more, I realized there\u2019s another side to the story. Reading this book reminded me of those nuances.\\n\\n### Overall Review\\n\\nThe book is divided into five chapters, structured as a collection of short essays. It\u2019s not a continuous narrative, so you can enjoy a few essays each day. Rather than deep technical explanations, it\u2019s great for deepening your understanding of open source.\\n\\n- **Chapter 1** explores the various facets of \\"open,\\" starting with the reminder that while open is equal, it\u2019s not always fair.  \\n- **Chapter 2** dives into real-world cases and the motivations behind open source.  \\n- **Chapter 3** discusses why open source is powerful.  \\n- **Chapter 4** (my favorite) reveals that open source isn\u2019t purely altruistic. It includes fascinating case studies like Microsoft vs. Linux, Samsung and Intel\u2019s IoT open-source projects, and Google Summer of Code (GSoC)\u2014a program I once wanted to join. Tech professionals will find this section especially engaging.  \\n- **Chapter 5** reflects on how to navigate the open-source era. The part about hiring open-source developers was eye-opening\u2014some companies hire talented contributors with just a few messages. I also found it amusing that some post a simple \\"Hiring Open Source Developers\\" sticky note instead of a formal job description.\\n\\n### Insights into the Dark Side of Open Source\\n\\nThe book doesn\u2019t shy away from the less glamorous side of open source, showing how big companies strategically use it. This helps readers move beyond romanticized notions of \\"sharing\\" and \\"freedom\\" to see how open source is a real business strategy. The shift from a technical playground to a tool for global corporate dominance is one of the book\u2019s strongest points.\\n\\n### Samsung Electronics\\n\\nWhat surprised me most wasn\u2019t the hidden side of open source (I\u2019d already heard about that online), but Samsung\u2019s role. I\u2019d always seen Samsung as a conservative tech giant compared to others, but this book changed my view. It revealed how Samsung approaches open source in IoT and shared ongoing projects. Learning that someone like the author works there made me want to join and experience their open-source culture firsthand.\\n\\n## Who Should Read This Book?\\n\\nThis book is for anyone curious about open source and its ecosystem. The author\u2019s personal stories are engaging and insightful. While some prior knowledge helps, the book is accessible and will show you that open source is not just a technical tool but a powerful strategy."},{"id":"/starting-geultto","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/starting-geultto","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2024-10-05-starting-geultto/2024-10-05-starting-geultto.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2024-10-05-starting-geultto/2024-10-05-starting-geultto.md","title":"\ud83c\udfacFirst and Last Glottal Start","description":"A truly wonderful and warm community.","date":"2024-10-05T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Recap","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/recap"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2024-10-05","description":"A truly wonderful and warm community.","draft":false,"keywords":["Gleat-to! (Note: \\"\uae00\ub610\\" is a Korean onomatopoeia that doesn\'t have a direct English equivalent, but can be translated as \\"Gleat-to!\\" to represent the playful sound of something being written or typed. If this is a specific term or name, it would remain unchanged as \\"Geultto.\\") \\n\\nSince the instruction specifies returning ONLY the translation and considering \\"\uae00\ub610\\" might be a proper noun or onomatopoeia, the most accurate response is:  \\n\\nGeultto","Community","Growth"],"slug":"/starting-geultto","tags":["Recap"],"title":"\ud83c\udfacFirst and Last Glottal Start"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Open","permalink":"/en/blog/open"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6AI Truths","permalink":"/en/blog/AI-Truth"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n## \uae00\ub610 10th Season\\n\\n### Application\\n\\nThis time, I got the chance to join the \uae00\ub610 community. Every season, I wanted to participate, but sometimes I missed out because I was busy or forgot to check. Other times, reflecting on myself while writing the application felt burdensome. This time too, writing the application wasn\u2019t easy, but it was a great experience to look back on what I\u2019ve done and how I\u2019ve lived. And above all, since this is the last season of \uae00\ub610, I really wanted to be part of it.\\n\\n### Goals for \uae00\ub610\\n\\nI\u2019m busy preparing for employment, but since this is my first and last chance to join \uae00\ub610, I want to participate as much as possible.\\n\\n- Join various small group channels\\n- Have coffee chats, study sessions, or writing sessions with different people\\n- Build healthy habits\\n\\nSeptember was an extremely tough month. Stressed from job preparation, my usual routines collapsed. I ordered delivery food three times a week and often drank alone. By chance, I got into \uae00\ub610, and realizing I couldn\u2019t go on like this, I resolved to join various small group channels in October to rebuild healthy habits.\\n\\nOne of my goals is to regain the pride and fulfillment I once felt by waking up at 6 AM again. It used to be so easy, but now it feels impossible. Surprisingly, the habit I thought I\u2019d manage smoothly this week has already failed. Still, I won\u2019t give up and will keep trying. Though I\u2019m stressed from taking on too much too quickly, I\u2019m grateful and happy every day.\\n\\nI still feel insecure about coffee chats because I think I lack expertise. I worry if I\u2019ll have meaningful conversations in one-on-one or group settings. Most members are professionals, and my knowledge and experience might fall short, making conversations awkward.\\n\\nBut I feel this worry repeats every time I meet new people. So, I\u2019ll use \uae00\ub610 to overcome it and communicate more actively. I\u2019ll let go of the pressure to be professional and join with the mindset that it\u2019s okay not to be perfect. After all, I\u2019m still a student, not a professional, so there won\u2019t be high expectations. I\u2019ll relax and enjoy this time.\\n\\nMaybe even my small knowledge or experiences could help someone. I want to listen, learn, and share my stories so we can grow together.\\n\\n### What I\u2019ll Write About\\n\\nI run a separate blog and wiki. For the wiki, I wanted to document CS knowledge and insights. For the blog, I wanted to share my thoughts and experiences, not just technical posts. I also wanted to write longer, easy-to-read articles.\\n\\n![post-planning.png](../assets/recap/post-planning.png)\\n\\nThese are the topics I\u2019ve thought about. I\u2019ll probably write about these. I\u2019d love to write something cool about ML, but I\u2019m not sure what topic to pick yet. Maybe a good idea will come up during the activities.\\n\\n## October Goals\\n\\nFinally, I\u2019ll briefly share my October goals! I always plan and set goals, but my reality never matches my expectations. Planning is tough but fun.\\n\\n- Build daily habits\\n  - Wake up at 6 AM\\n  - 30-minute fasting cardio (walking or running) in the early morning\\n  - 5-day weekly weight training (chest, back, shoulders, legs, arms)\\n  - English study with ChatGPT\\n  - Solve at least 3 LeetCode problems\\n  - Read at least 20 pages before bedtime, 1 hour before sleep\\n- Join study groups\\n  - Algorithm study ([Coursera Stanford Algorithms](https://www.coursera.org/specializations/algorithms))\\n  - ETL study ([Learning Spark](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000061353994))\\n  - DDIA study ([Designing Data-Intensive Applications](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000001766328))\\n- Personal study\\n  - Causal inference\\n    - [Practical Causal Inference with Python](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000212577153)\\n    - [Causal Inference and Discovery with Python](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000213021532)\\n  - JavaScript\\n    - [Core JavaScript](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000001766397)\\n  - [Google Cloud AI Study Jam](https://sites.google.com/view/2024-study-jams/ai?fbclid=IwY2xjawFGYPlleHRuA2FlbQIxMAABHfcnts6c4jK3Hu0Z54OCOf1N3TLFGWM7Kcs5r43nvVpXteynWljH_6o4oA_aem_wSwPx49oIGWNDlWfJcizow)\\n- School courses\\n  - Midterm report for a liberal arts class\\n  - Math assignments\\n  - Studying for a math midterm (I\u2019m taking a math class in my final semester\u2014what am I thinking?)\\n- Graduation project\\n  - Collecting blood vessel data\\n  - Data preprocessing (CLAHE, LDC (Lightweight Dense CNN for Edge Detection))\\n  - Filming with a DVS (Dynamic Vision Sensor) camera\\n  - White blood cell counting using YOLOv8\\n  - Continuous experiments\\n- Reading\\n  - *Flow: The Psychology of Optimal Experience* (reading it for the third time)\\n  - *Growing Together* (next book to read)\\n- Job preparation\\n  - Resume writing\\n  - Reviewing past school projects and organizing them on GitHub\\n- Events\\n  - Daangn Meetup\\n  - Hackathon (scheduled soon within the school)\\n\\nLooking at this list, it feels overwhelming. I wrote down what I\u2019m currently doing and what\u2019s planned, but there might be more variables. Who knows how it\u2019ll turn out? Personally, I wish I had more time to read books.\\n\\nI\u2019m not sure how I\u2019m managing all this. I guess it\u2019s just from trying to live diligently. Among the study groups, *Learning Spark* and *Designing Data-Intensive Applications* are really tough, even after reading them multiple times. I\u2019ll need to revisit them. As for causal inference, I\u2019m both excited and worried about how difficult it\u2019ll be.\\n\\n![Oct-planning.png](../assets/recap/Oct-planning.png)  \\nI visualized this using [napkin.ai](https://www.napkin.ai/), recommended by \uc131\uc724\ub2d8. The UI is beautiful, and I\u2019ll use it often. Thank you for sharing the tool!\\n\\n## Final Words\\n\\nWriting such a long post is definitely challenging. But I hope my skills will improve with practice. How will I have changed in six months? I\u2019m excited to see the new me through \uae00\ub610. How many connections will I have made? What will I be writing? How will I be living? I\u2019ll work harder and look forward to that time. I can do it.\\n\\nLastly, \uae00\ub610, please take good care of me!"},{"id":"/AI-Truth","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/AI-Truth","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2024-09-30-AI-Truth/2024-09-30-AI-Truth.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2024-09-30-AI-Truth/2024-09-30-AI-Truth.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6AI Truths","description":"The Age of Fear: The Clearest Truth We Must Face with Clarity","date":"2024-09-30T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2024-09-30","description":"The Age of Fear: The Clearest Truth We Must Face with Clarity","draft":false,"slug":"/AI-Truth","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6AI Truths"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83c\udfacFirst and Last Glottal Start","permalink":"/en/blog/starting-geultto"},"nextItem":{"title":"The Map of Life","permalink":"/en/blog/Life-Map"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media \\\\<I am a Reviewer\\\\> activity, where the book was provided for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2024](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2024.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/AI-Truth.png)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000214055422)\\n\\n- Title: **AI Truth**  \\n- Author: **Baekjoon Lim**  \\n- Publisher: **Hanbit Media**  \\n- Release Date: **August 20, 2024**  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nThis is my fourth technical book of 2024. With job preparation, online courses, and various projects, I\u2019ve been struggling to finish reading technical books. Still, I applied for the \\"I am a Reviewer\\" program because I wanted to read this book. I\u2019m a fan of the author, and my interest in AI made it an easy choice.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Overall Impressions  \\n\\nThe book starts with a fictional story imagining life with AI in ten years. Though the topic could have been dry, the novel-like opening felt like an appetizer\u2014light yet intriguing. I found it engaging, especially since such a future seems plausible. Chapter 2 covers AI history, striking a balance between depth and accessibility. It was a great refresher on AI\u2019s evolution.  \\n\\nChapter 3 highlights AI\u2019s surprising achievements\u2014from deepfakes to AlphaGo and AlphaFold. Chapter 4, the book\u2019s core, offers valuable insights for developers. By this point, it\u2019s clear the book is up-to-date with current trends.  \\n\\nChapter 5 explores real-world AI applications, while Chapter 6 discusses fears and solutions. The latter is unsettling but thought-provoking. I won\u2019t spoil the solutions\u2014read the book to find out.  \\n\\n### Will Developers Be Replaced?  \\n\\nMany developers or aspiring coders probably wonder if AI will replace them. I once feared this too, especially after testing Anthropic\u2019s **Claude Artifacts** (in preview). It generates UI code from screenshots\u2014React with TypeScript, just by asking. My initial thought: *\\"Frontend developers might soon be obsolete.\\"*  \\n\\nBut this book eased those fears. AI isn\u2019t perfect\u2014it hallucinates, struggles with complex abstractions, and lacks human judgment. While it produces clean code, it can\u2019t yet handle nuanced, large-scale problems.  \\n\\nMoreover, if AI-generated code is misused (e.g., for unethical software), who will regulate it? Without new developers entering the field, there\u2019s no one to enforce ethics or fix flaws. Relying solely on AI is risky.  \\n\\nThe book argues that developers won\u2019t be replaced\u2014read it for more reasons.  \\n\\n### A Healthy Fear  \\n\\nStill, fear is justified. AI evolves rapidly. Early 2024 saw **GPT-3.5 Turbo** phased out, replaced by **GPT-4**, **GPT-4o**, and now **o1-preview**/**o1-mini**. The pace is dizzying.  \\n\\nThe book mentions AI moving from \\"speaking\\" (statistical models) to \\"thinking\\"\u2014a shift embodied by OpenAI\u2019s **o1**. I\u2019d lost touch with recent AI trends during job prep, but this book reminded me to stay updated.  \\n\\n### What Should We Prepare?  \\n\\nAI will keep advancing. How should we adapt?  \\n\\n- **Stop writing every line of code.** Let AI handle repetitive tasks. Focus on complex problem-solving, communication with non-tech roles, and reviewing/testing AI-generated code.  \\n- **Become a problem-solver.** Technical skills, mathematical thinking, and deep focus remain essential\u2014just amplified by AI.  \\n\\nThe book quotes **John Carmack**, legendary game developer:  \\n\\n> *\\"The source of value has never been \'coding.\' Don\u2019t fixate on it. Solving problems is the core skill. Traditional programming\u2019s discipline and precision will stay valuable, but they won\u2019t be gatekeepers anymore. If AI becomes a better programmer than me, I\u2019d happily manage it.\\"*  \\n\\nDevelopers are problem-solvers. Job descriptions reflect this\u2014companies want candidates who tackle challenges creatively.  \\n\\nCoding is no longer exclusive. With free resources, anyone can learn. The book\u2019s closing line resonated deeply:  \\n\\n> *\\"Don\u2019t cling to coding. Don\u2019t get attached to the tools you use. Embrace AI\u2019s help. The real value lies in solving problems\u2014**not coding.**\\"*  \\n\\n## Who Should Read This?  \\n\\nThis book is for **developers**, especially those **not in AI roles**. It explains AI\u2019s history, applications, and how to leverage it. More importantly, it challenges you to rethink your value as a developer in an AI-driven world.  \\n\\nIf you\u2019re curious about AI\u2019s impact on programming, this is a must-read."},{"id":"/Life-Map","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Life-Map","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2024-09-22-Life-Map/2024-09-22-Life-Map.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2024-09-22-Life-Map/2024-09-22-Life-Map.md","title":"The Map of Life","description":"Life Map for the Glott 10th Application  \\n(Note: \\"\uae00\ub610\\" is transliterated as \\"Glott\\" since it appears to be a proper noun or specific program name without an official English equivalent.)  \\n\\nIf \\"\uae00\ub610\\" has an official English name (e.g., \\"Gleat\\" or another term), please provide it for a more accurate translation. Otherwise, \\"Glott\\" is a phonetic rendering.","date":"2024-09-22T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Recap","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/recap"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2024-09-22","description":"Life Map for the Glott 10th Application  \\n(Note: \\"\uae00\ub610\\" is transliterated as \\"Glott\\" since it appears to be a proper noun or specific program name without an official English equivalent.)  \\n\\nIf \\"\uae00\ub610\\" has an official English name (e.g., \\"Gleat\\" or another term), please provide it for a more accurate translation. Otherwise, \\"Glott\\" is a phonetic rendering.","draft":false,"keywords":["Map of Life","Gleatto","Growth"],"slug":"/Life-Map","tags":["Recap"],"title":"The Map of Life"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6AI Truths","permalink":"/en/blog/AI-Truth"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Developing LLM-based AI Services with LangChain","permalink":"/en/blog/Developing-AI-services-with-LangChain"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n## My Life Map\\n\\nApplying to Geultto gave me a chance to reflect on the journey I\u2019ve been through. So much has happened, and I\u2019ve had the opportunity to look back at how I\u2019ve changed along the way. While I\u2019ve done short-term retrospectives before, this is one of the rare times I\u2019ve reflected on my entire life. In this post, I\u2019ll try to summarize my growth so far. I\u2019m grateful to Geultto for giving me this opportunity, and to anyone reading this out of curiosity about my not-so-special life.\\n\\n### The Kid Who Just Loved Computers\\n\\nFrom a young age, I was a kid who loved computers. I signed up for after-school classes to prepare for certifications like PowerPoint, Excel, Internet, and Word Processor in the computer lab, which naturally made me close with computers. I gradually became interested in games, but since I wasn\u2019t good at playing them, I wanted to become a programmer who creates games rather than a player. Or maybe a white-hat hacker who prevents hacking\u2014just because it sounded fun and cool.\\n\\nWhen I entered middle school, I started studying the basics of computers. I skimmed through books like *Let\u2019s C Programming* and *Cisco Networking*, and solved problems on platforms like [pwnable.kr](https://pwnable.kr/play.php) or [Lena\'s Reversing for Newbies](https://forum.tuts4you.com/files/file/1307-lenas-reversing-for-newbies/) by reading walkthroughs. I also gathered information through the [Hackerschool](https://www.hackerschool.org/Sub_Html/HS_Community/index.html) community. I even tried applying to a digital media high school to study more professionally, but I failed. I remember my grades were good enough, but I didn\u2019t pass the interview. Although I ended up going to a general high school, I didn\u2019t give up on my dreams and studied programming whenever I didn\u2019t feel like doing schoolwork. My high school physics teacher was very interested in programming (back then, \\"coding\\" wasn\u2019t a commonly used term), so I and a friend created a club and even won an award in a school competition. Looking back, I didn\u2019t contribute much then. I briefly studied IoT concepts and wrote a short paper, which I later read and realized was more of an informational article than a proper paper. Still, I take pride in having tried something.\\n\\n### Turning Point\\n\\nThe most memorable moment from my high school club activities was listening to a lecture by a programmer who worked at a game company. Through him, I learned about the life of a programmer and what efforts I needed to make to get into a computer engineering department. In fact, it was he who recommended I write that paper. He helped me a lot, but I was immature at the time and had too much academic stress, so our connection naturally faded. Still, after his lecture, I became convinced that being a programmer wasn\u2019t just a cool job\u2014it was something I truly wanted to do. To achieve that, I needed to get into a computer engineering department, so I tried to focus more on my studies from then on.\\n\\nI was also impressed by how he helped students as an educator. I remember he mentored at a specialized high school, and that image stuck with me as really cool. Back then, the Facebook page \\"Opentutorials (\uc0dd\ud65c\ucf54\ub529)\\" was famous, and its creator \\"Egoing\\" provided web lectures that made it easy for others to learn. Seeing people like him made me realize I wanted to become someone who uses my technical knowledge to positively impact others, beyond just studying technology.\\n\\n### Never-Ending Effort\\n\\nAfter entering college, I had many moments where I wanted to give up on becoming a developer. The first was understanding double pointers and their relationship with arrays in C. I had studied it before, but it was so hard when I tried again. My peers were good at C and handled assignments well, but I struggled, making me wonder, \\"Is computer engineering not for me?\\" I was frustrated but didn\u2019t give up. Thinking, \\"I\u2019ll make it somehow,\\" I applied for an education program run by a Microsoft MVP during summer break, as suggested by a senior. I studied C/C++, Windows API, and MFC at the Microsoft Korea building, which was my first time in an IT company\u2014it was fascinating, and the view of Gwanghwamun was amazing.\\n\\nThe second challenge was in my second year, when I studied electronic circuits, Verilog, and ARM assembly. I thought college would involve practical developer skills like backend or frontend, but my department focused more on hardware as an engineering program. So, I had to study low-level concepts, which was unexpected. I was stressed and my grades weren\u2019t good because I was forcing myself to study things I didn\u2019t want to.\\n\\nThe third challenge came after my third year, when I was deciding my career path. All I had learned were CS subjects like computer architecture, operating systems, and systems programming. I barely knew frontend or backend, and wasn\u2019t sure what to do next. My skills were limited to C, C++, Verilog, assembly, and basic web development. Then, I had to take a break for military service.\\n\\n### Career Crossroads\\n\\nBack home, I tried to figure out my path but couldn\u2019t reach a clear conclusion. So, I thought, \\"Let\u2019s just try everything. Experience will stack up, and a goal will emerge.\\" I started studying random fields. Luckily, there were two libraries nearby, but they mostly had old books. Buying books was expensive for a jobless person, so I applied to be a reviewer and joined Hanbit Media\u2019s \\"I Am a Reviewer\\" program in 2021. I\u2019m really grateful for all the books I\u2019ve received since then.\\n\\nAround this time, I also joined the DataCamp Data Science Fellowship by \\"Fake Lab.\\" It was my first time studying data engineering, and it was really tough. Besides that, I started learning Django, JavaScript, Node.js, and AI on my own, but without a plan, I burned out despite slowly accumulating knowledge.\\n\\nWhile taking a break from development in 2023, I discovered GDG Daegu. This community reignited my motivation and taught me that communication skills are as important as technical skills for becoming an outstanding developer. It also led me to actively participate in various communities, conferences, and meetups.\\n\\nThere, I heard advice like, \\"Think about what you enjoy doing as a job.\\" The first thing that came to mind was AI and data, which I had studied hard for. I even joined a deep learning framework implementation study at Fake Lab. However, since these fields have many career paths, I kept pondering.\\n\\nIn the second half of 2023, I decided to study these topics again and joined Google\u2019s Machine Learning Bootcamp. It was a fun experience to review ML basics and meet great people. After returning to school, I joined my university\u2019s GDSC as an ML Member and am now almost certain about becoming an ML engineer, though I still keep questioning my path.\\n\\n### The Me Today\\n\\nNow, I\u2019m preparing for graduation and job hunting. Looking back, the field I\u2019ve studied most seriously is AI. However, reading job postings makes me constantly think about giving up and switching paths. Most companies require a master\u2019s degree or equivalent skills, and I don\u2019t fit either category.\\n\\nStill, I believe I can overcome this. I\u2019ve done it before, and I\u2019ll keep going. Just as I never gave up in tough moments, I\u2019m sure I\u2019ll prevail this time too."},{"id":"/Developing-AI-services-with-LangChain","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Developing-AI-services-with-LangChain","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2024-06-03-Developing-AI-services-with-LangChain/2024-06-03-Developing-AI-services-with-LangChain.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2024-06-03-Developing-AI-services-with-LangChain/2024-06-03-Developing-AI-services-with-LangChain.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Developing LLM-based AI Services with LangChain","description":"Learn RAG from a Current AI Specialist! | Implement 8 Services with LangChain, OpenAI API, and Streamlit!","date":"2024-06-03T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2024-06-03","description":"Learn RAG from a Current AI Specialist! | Implement 8 Services with LangChain, OpenAI API, and Streamlit!","draft":false,"keywords":["LangChain","LLM","OpenAI"],"slug":"/Developing-AI-services-with-LangChain","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Developing LLM-based AI Services with LangChain"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"The Map of Life","permalink":"/en/blog/Life-Map"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6How to Become a Better Programmer","permalink":"/en/blog/Becoming-a-Better-Programmer"}},"content":"## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/Developing-AI-services-with-LangChain.png)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000212568407)\\n\\n- Title: Developing AI Services with LangChain: Building LLM-Based Applications\\n- Author: Ji-Young Seo\\n- Publisher: Gilbut\\n- Published: 2024-02-27\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\nLLMs (Large Language Models) are *so* trendy these days that even during exam season, I carved out some time to study them. As someone studying AI, I already knew the basics of what LLMs are and how to use them. But I picked up this book for a refresher\u2014and honestly, because it was super thin. Plus, the author works at Microsoft, so I figured there might be some exclusive tips!\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### Great for Developers *Not* in ML\\n\\nI\u2019d recommend this book to developers without a machine learning background. It covers general AI concepts and isn\u2019t too code-heavy, making it a light read. It even walks you through setting up Conda, getting an OpenAI API key, and obtaining a Hugging Face token\u2014so it\u2019s a solid introductory guide.\\n\\nFor me, the RAG section was a helpful refresher, and I got to try LangChain for the first time (it\u2019s not bad!). The book also lists LangChain projects you can explore later\u2014definitely worth checking out. This read inspired me to brainstorm how to integrate LangChain and LLMs into my own projects. Time to start a LangChain project soon!\\n\\n## Recommended For\\n\\nIf you\u2019re curious about LLMs and want a quick yet practical intro, this book is for you. \ud83d\ude80"},{"id":"/Becoming-a-Better-Programmer","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Becoming-a-Better-Programmer","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2024-05-23-Becoming-a-Better-Programmer/2024-05-23-Becoming-a-Better-Programmer.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2024-05-23-Becoming-a-Better-Programmer/2024-05-23-Becoming-a-Better-Programmer.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6How to Become a Better Programmer","description":"39 Practical Tips from Senior Developers You Can Implement Right Away","date":"2024-05-23T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2024-05-23","description":"39 Practical Tips from Senior Developers You Can Implement Right Away","draft":false,"keywords":["Programmer","TDD","Study","Developer","Person"],"slug":"/Becoming-a-Better-Programmer","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6How to Become a Better Programmer"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Developing LLM-based AI Services with LangChain","permalink":"/en/blog/Developing-AI-services-with-LangChain"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Essential Guide to Deep Learning","permalink":"/en/blog/Fundamentals-of-DL"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post is part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity, written after receiving the book for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2024](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2024.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book cover to visit the [Kyobobook](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000213044936) page!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/Becoming-a-Better-Programmer.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000213044936)\\n\\n- **Title**: *Becoming a Better Programmer*  \\n- **Author**: Pete Goodliffe  \\n- **Translators**: Wonjae Choi, Jeonhee Kang, Jaedeok Ahn, Yoonhwa Nam  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: April 30, 2024  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nThis is my second technical book of 2024. Lately, I\u2019ve been juggling multiple projects and reading various books, which has made it hard to finish them all. Still, I picked this one up because it seemed approachable, and I was curious: *What more should I do to become a better programmer?*  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### A Book That Makes You Reflect  \\n\\nThis book explores how programmers can grow in their careers. As I read, I realized how much I\u2019ve overlooked certain aspects and what I should prioritize. It made me reflect a lot: *Do I care enough about my code? Do I revisit my code? Is writing test code really that important?* These questions stuck with me.  \\n\\n### A Senior Developer\u2019s Mentorship  \\n\\nReading this felt like having a senior programmer guide me step by step\u2014sharing insights on how to think and act as a developer. Even though I\u2019m not working at a company and don\u2019t have mentors, this book gave me that experience. The \\"Final Thoughts\\" section includes reflection prompts, and I found myself brainstorming even beyond those questions. If I get the chance, I\u2019d love to do a study group with others using this book.  \\n\\n## Recommended Readers  \\n\\nIf you\u2019re a programmer looking to grow\u2014especially if you\u2019re a newcomer, junior developer, or even a student\u2014this book is for you. It\u2019s a great read for anyone who wants to reflect, improve, and become a better programmer."},{"id":"/Fundamentals-of-DL","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Fundamentals-of-DL","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2024-02-25-Fundamentals-of-DL/2024-02-25-Fundamentals-of-DL.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2024-02-25-Fundamentals-of-DL/2024-02-25-Fundamentals-of-DL.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Essential Guide to Deep Learning","description":"From Linear Algebra and Probability to Deep Learning with PyTorch: Theory and Practice","date":"2024-02-25T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2024-02-25","description":"From Linear Algebra and Probability to Deep Learning with PyTorch: Theory and Practice","draft":false,"keywords":["Deep Learning","Deep learning"],"slug":"/Fundamentals-of-DL","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Essential Guide to Deep Learning"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6How to Become a Better Programmer","permalink":"/en/blog/Becoming-a-Better-Programmer"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Learning by Building: Generative AI","permalink":"/en/blog/Generative-Deep-Learning"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity, where I received the book for review purposes.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2024](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2024.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book cover to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/Fundamentals-of-DL.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000212175486)\\n\\n- **Title**: Fundamentals of Deep Learning  \\n- **Authors**: Nitish Srivastava, Nikhil Buduma, Joe Papa  \\n- **Translators**: Jaehoon Choi, Seongjae Cha  \\n- **Editors**: Taeung Sung, Yunho Maeng  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Publication Date**: February 2, 2024  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nIt\u2019s already 2024. Studying deep learning has been challenging so far\u2014and it\u2019s still tough. This year, I\u2019ll keep pushing to learn more about machine learning. There are so many books I want to read. Thanks to Hanbit Media\u2019s *I am a Reviewer* program, my first IT book of 2024 is *Fundamentals of Deep Learning*.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Foundational Math  \\nThe book starts with concise yet essential explanations of linear algebra and probability. However, if you\u2019ve never studied these topics before, you might find them difficult. The explanations are clear, but even I struggled a bit when revisiting them. That\u2019s expected\u2014Chapters 1 and 2 alone could fill a university course. Studying linear algebra and probability beforehand would make this book more rewarding. Still, it was refreshing to revisit these concepts, especially since the authors explain *why* they matter, which motivates readers.  \\n\\n### Effort from Authors & Translators  \\nIf I were a translator, I\u2019d probably hate translating this book. The sentences are dense and technically challenging. The authors clearly tried to simplify complex math concepts, and the translators must have worked hard to preserve that clarity in Korean. The presence of two editors likely helped polish the text.  \\n\\n### Korean Terminology  \\nSince I studied machine learning in English, the heavy use of Korean terms felt awkward at times. However, English equivalents were always provided (e.g., \uace0\uc720\ubca1\ud130$^{eigenvectors}$, \uc0ac\ud6c4\ud655\ub960$^{posterior \\\\ probability}$, L2 \uaddc\uc81c\ud654$^{regularization}$). Most terms were translated, while untranslatable ones like *dropout* remained in English. This is unavoidable in translations, but it was a bit disappointing.  \\n\\n### What Sets This Book Apart  \\nYou\u2019ll notice many footnotes throughout the book\u2014this is a key difference from other deep learning texts. Whenever a key concept appears, the footnotes cite the original research papers. The book feels like a curated summary of foundational papers, explained by the authors. While some details felt like TMI (Too Much Information), the academic tone was engaging. It made sense why the title is *Fundamentals of Deep Learning*.  \\n\\n### PyTorch  \\nPyTorch is introduced in Chapter 5. Before that, the book focuses on core deep learning concepts. It doesn\u2019t deeply explain PyTorch\u2014you\u2019ll need to look up specifics elsewhere. That\u2019s fair, since this isn\u2019t a PyTorch tutorial. Familiarity with PyTorch basics (e.g., via [Opentutorials (\uc0dd\ud65c\ucf54\ub529) PyTorch Tutorial](https://tutorials.pytorch.kr/)) would make reading smoother.  \\n\\n### Broad Coverage  \\nThe book touches on CNNs, RNNs, reinforcement learning, generative models, XAI, and even Neural Turing Machines (NTM). While CNNs and RNNs are well-explained, topics like XAI and NTM felt too brief and challenging. Still, it was interesting to see these fields introduced.  \\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\nThis isn\u2019t a beginner-friendly book. If you\u2019re new to deep learning, you might get overwhelmed. However, if you already understand the basics, this book is a great resource for deepening your knowledge. It\u2019s especially useful if you want to revisit concepts with clear, detailed explanations."},{"id":"/Generative-Deep-Learning","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Generative-Deep-Learning","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2023-10-29-Generative-Deep-Learning/2023-10-29-Generative-Deep-Learning.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2023-10-29-Generative-Deep-Learning/2023-10-29-Generative-Deep-Learning.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Learning by Building: Generative AI","description":"From Transformers to GPT, DALL\xb7E 2, Stable Diffusion, and Flamingo","date":"2023-10-29T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2023-10-29","description":"From Transformers to GPT, DALL\xb7E 2, Stable Diffusion, and Flamingo","draft":false,"keywords":["DALL\xb7E 2","Stable Diffusion","Deep learning"],"slug":"/Generative-Deep-Learning","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Learning by Building: Generative AI"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Essential Guide to Deep Learning","permalink":"/en/blog/Fundamentals-of-DL"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6MLOps Practical Guide","permalink":"/en/blog/practical-MLOps"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media \\"I am a Reviewer\\" activity, where I was provided with the book.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2023](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2023.jpg)  \\n\\n## Book Info  \\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/Generative-deep-learning.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000208953342)  \\n\\n- **Title**: Generative AI: Making and Learning  \\n- **Author**: David Foster  \\n- **Translator**: Park Haesun  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: September 15, 2023  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}  \\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nI believe generative AI is currently the hottest field in AI. From OpenAI\u2019s GPT-4 to the recent DALL\xb7E 3, it\u2019s advancing rapidly. Beyond OpenAI, many other companies are also creating groundbreaking products. AI is increasingly becoming a part of our daily lives, making them more convenient. This curiosity about generative AI led me to read this book. It feels like just yesterday I was studying GANs, and now the field has evolved so quickly. While I\u2019m sometimes scared of how far AI will go, I\u2019m determined to keep learning as long as I can.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Learning by Building  \\n\\nI think the title is perfectly fitting. The book follows a hands-on approach, guiding you to build models with Keras step by step. I love this style\u2014studying only theory can be confusing. Combining theory with practice is far more effective, and this book does exactly that.  \\n\\n### Accessible Explanations  \\n\\nThe author clearly put a lot of effort into making complex concepts understandable. Generative AI is notoriously difficult, and before reading, I feared it would be as tough as my past GAN studies. However, the book includes helpful examples and well-placed illustrations, making it easy to follow. Many diagrams are sourced directly from research papers, saving readers from diving into dense academic texts. This is especially useful for those who struggle with English or find papers overwhelming. Plus, the translator is highly reputable, so I trusted the translation without hesitation.  \\n\\n### Favorite Parts  \\n\\nThe most enjoyable sections were the final chapters, which covered cutting-edge technologies like DALL\xb7E 2 and Stable Diffusion. The book also includes a timeline of generative AI, showing how models have evolved\u2014this was a great way to see the bigger picture.  \\n\\n## Recommended Readers  \\n\\nWhile this book is accessible to beginners in generative AI, it\u2019s best suited for those who already understand basic deep learning concepts and are interested in the latest advancements. It\u2019s also ideal for anyone looking to dive deeper into generative AI."},{"id":"/practical-MLOps","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/practical-MLOps","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2023-07-23-practical-MLOps/2023-07-23-practical-MLOps.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2023-07-23-practical-MLOps/2023-07-23-practical-MLOps.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6MLOps Practical Guide","description":"From theory to practice in DevOps and MLOps, covering cloud computing, AutoML, and edge computing | Hands-on labs in AWS, GCP, and Azure cloud environments","date":"2023-07-23T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2023-07-23","description":"From theory to practice in DevOps and MLOps, covering cloud computing, AutoML, and edge computing | Hands-on labs in AWS, GCP, and Azure cloud environments","draft":false,"keywords":["MLOps","DevOps","Machine learning"],"slug":"/practical-MLOps","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6MLOps Practical Guide"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Learning by Building: Generative AI","permalink":"/en/blog/Generative-Deep-Learning"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Starting IaC with Terraform","permalink":"/en/blog/terraform101"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity, where the book was provided for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2023](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2023.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/practical-MLOps.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000202854952)\\n\\n- **Title**: MLOps \uc2e4\uc804 \uac00\uc774\ub4dc (*Practical MLOps*)  \\n- **Authors**: Noah Gift, Alfredo Deza  \\n- **Translators**: Janghu Lee, Iilseop Lee, Kiwon Seo  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: May 24, 2023  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\nMLOps has been a hot topic since machine learning gained traction. These days, it\'s not enough to just build a good ML model\u2014you also need a solid pipeline. MLOps, a blend of *Machine Learning* and *DevOps*, automates the process of developing and deploying ML models. Many might wonder how this is possible. I started studying this field and am now exploring MLOps and backend technologies to build better pipelines. This book seemed like a great resource, so I decided to read it.\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### Is It Beginner-Friendly?\\n\\nI wouldn\u2019t say it\u2019s super easy, but if you\u2019re interested in MLOps and have at least some experience with it, this book is worth recommending. As the title suggests, it\u2019s a practical guide\u2014more focused on hands-on exercises than theory. However, the theoretical parts are well-explained, so if you\u2019re familiar with command-line environments, Python, containers, etc., you\u2019ll find it easier to follow. If you\u2019re curious about MLOps, this is a must-read.\\n\\n### Hands-On Guide\\n\\nAs mentioned earlier, this book is essentially a practical guide. It subtly tells you what you need to know if you want to learn MLOps. Since MLOps is a field that requires knowledge of many tools and concepts, the authors prioritize breadth over depth. After reading this book, you\u2019ll know what areas to focus on next. A fun feature is the \\"Try It Out\\" and \\"Think About It\\" sections at the end of each chapter. The former challenges you with practical tasks, while the latter encourages theoretical reflection. Working through these exercises will deepen your understanding of MLOps. I found the explanations and translation to be clear and well-executed. It even made me want to dive deeper into MLOps if I ever get the chance.\\n\\n### If It Had Been Translated in 2021...\\n\\nOne minor drawback is the use of **Flask**. While it\u2019s still widely used, the industry seems to be shifting toward **FastAPI**. If given the chance, converting the Flask code to FastAPI would be an interesting exercise.  \\n\\nSince technology evolves so quickly, this is a common issue. The original book was published in 2021, so if the Korean translation had come out the same year, it might have been even more popular.  \\n\\nSome code examples from 2021 might not work in 2023, so the translators likely faced challenges updating and fixing them. That must have been a lot of work!\\n\\n## Target Audience\\n\\nI recommend this book to anyone working in or interested in MLOps. It\u2019s also great for those who want hands-on experience. Prior knowledge of containers, command-line tools, backend systems, and cloud platforms will make reading this book much smoother."},{"id":"/terraform101","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/terraform101","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2023-06-24-terraform101/terraform101.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2023-06-24-terraform101/terraform101.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Starting IaC with Terraform","description":"Terraform All-in-One Guide: From Beginner to Practical Implementation","date":"2023-06-24T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2023-06-24","description":"Terraform All-in-One Guide: From Beginner to Practical Implementation","draft":false,"keywords":["Terraform","IaC","DevOps"],"slug":"/terraform101","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Starting IaC with Terraform"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6MLOps Practical Guide","permalink":"/en/blog/practical-MLOps"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Docs for Developers: The Complete Guide to Technical Documentation","permalink":"/en/blog/docs-for-developers"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written after receiving the book as part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2023](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2023.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/terraform101.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000202478097)\\n\\n- **Title**: Terraform 101: Getting Started with Infrastructure as Code (IaC)  \\n- **Authors**: Kim Minsu, Kim Jaejun, Lee Gyuseok, Lee Yujong  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: May 24, 2023  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nAdmittedly, I\u2019m just a student with limited knowledge of DevOps. I\u2019ve dabbled in Kubernetes and Docker, but never deeply. So when I picked up this book, I was nervous\u2014but also curious. I\u2019d seen \\"Terraform\\" mentioned in CI/CD pipeline diagrams or heard it in passing, but didn\u2019t truly understand it. I wanted this book to clarify what Terraform is and how it\u2019s used.\\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### A Beginner-Friendly Guide  \\n\\nAs mentioned earlier, I was intimidated before reading. My past attempts with Kubernetes and Docker felt overwhelming, and I feared Terraform might be the same. Plus, as a DevOps novice, I expected to encounter unfamiliar terms. But my anxiety faded as I read. This book is accessible\u2014if you\u2019re willing to put in the effort, even beginners can follow along.  \\n\\nIt starts with Terraform basics: how it works, its core concepts, and practical applications. The content is split into two parts:  \\n- **Part 1** covers Terraform fundamentals\u2014providers, workflows, and basic usage.  \\n- **Part 2** dives into scaling Terraform for larger projects, sharing best practices for collaboration.  \\n\\nI especially appreciated the focus on teamwork and organizational workflows in Part 2. If I ever implement Terraform professionally, I\u2019ll revisit this section.  \\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\n\\nThis book is ideal for anyone curious about Terraform, regardless of prior DevOps experience. It\u2019s particularly useful for infrastructure engineers, DevOps engineers, or anyone involved in designing and managing services. If you\u2019re looking to learn IaC from scratch, this is a solid starting point."},{"id":"/docs-for-developers","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/docs-for-developers","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2023-05-28-docs-for-developers/docs-for-developers.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2023-05-28-docs-for-developers/docs-for-developers.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Docs for Developers: The Complete Guide to Technical Documentation","description":"Interviews with 11 domestic technical writers included","date":"2023-05-28T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2023-05-28","description":"Interviews with 11 domestic technical writers included","draft":false,"keywords":["Documentation","Developer","Technical writer","Technical Document  \\n\\n*(Note: The original text \\"\uae30\uc220 \ubb38\uc11c\\" is a simple phrase meaning \\"technical document.\\" If this is a title or heading, it could also be rendered as \\"Technical Documentation\\" depending on context. Since no additional content was provided, only the direct translation is given.)*  \\n\\n**Return ONLY the translation (per instruction):**  \\nTechnical Document"],"slug":"/docs-for-developers","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Docs for Developers: The Complete Guide to Technical Documentation"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Starting IaC with Terraform","permalink":"/en/blog/terraform101"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Becoming a Node.js Backend Developer","permalink":"/en/blog/become-a-node-js-engineer"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity, where I was provided with the book.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2023](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2023.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book cover to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/docs-for-developers.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000201419245)\\n\\n- **Title**: Docs for Developers: Technical Writing for Software Engineers  \\n- **Authors**: Jared Bhatti, Zachary Sarah Colah, Jen Lampton, David N\xfa\xf1ez, Heidi Waterhouse  \\n- **Translator**: Sungchang Ha  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: April 10, 2023  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nI used to think that as a developer, all I needed to do was write good code. But reality proved me wrong. Through books written by senior developers, I learned about the importance of collaboration and communication. While some might assume this communication is purely verbal, I\u2019ve realized that documentation plays a huge role. That\u2019s why I believe writing well is just as crucial for a developer as coding itself\u2014and that\u2019s why I chose this book.\\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Who Are You Writing For?  \\n\\nThis book constantly reminds you to ask, **\\"Who is reading the documents we write?\\"** It emphasizes the *curse of knowledge*\u2014a concept familiar to Marvel fans. Simply put, it\u2019s assuming others know what you know. The book warns against assuming your readers understand your code or explanations. Instead, it urges you to adjust your technical level to match your audience\u2019s perspective. The key is to deliver what they want to know clearly and concisely.\\n\\n### Simple Structure, Deep Reflection  \\n\\nThe book follows a fictional project called *Corg.ly*, covering documentation from pre-launch to post-release. Through this narrative, it teaches how to create and improve technical documents.  \\n\\nReading this made me reflect on my past documentation. I often thought, *\\"Since the readers are developers, they\u2019ll at least be familiar with the technology.\\"* This book showed me how flawed that assumption is\u2014and made me rethink how I write reviews and other content too.\\n\\n### Appendix  \\n\\nThe appendix includes three sections: insights into technical writing in Korea, when to hire experts, and reference materials. I especially enjoyed the interviews with **11 Korean technical writers**. Before reading this, I only had a vague idea of what technical writers do. These interviews gave me a deeper understanding and even sparked my interest in the field. For anyone aspiring to be a technical writer, this appendix alone makes the book worthwhile.\\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\n\\nI recommend this book to anyone who frequently documents their work. It\u2019s also a great pick for those interested in becoming technical writers. As mentioned, the appendix features interviews with **11 active Korean technical writers**, making it a valuable resource for career exploration in the field."},{"id":"/become-a-node-js-engineer","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/become-a-node-js-engineer","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2023-05-21-become-a-node-js-engineer/become-a-node-js-engineer.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2023-05-21-become-a-node-js-engineer/become-a-node-js-engineer.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Becoming a Node.js Backend Developer","description":"A Complete Package for JavaScript Backend Beginners: Learning with TypeScript + Node.js + Express + NestJS","date":"2023-05-21T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2023-05-21","description":"A Complete Package for JavaScript Backend Beginners: Learning with TypeScript + Node.js + Express + NestJS","draft":false,"keywords":["TypeScript","Node.js","Express","NestJS"],"slug":"/become-a-node-js-engineer","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Becoming a Node.js Backend Developer"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Docs for Developers: The Complete Guide to Technical Documentation","permalink":"/en/blog/docs-for-developers"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Machine Learning & Deep Learning for Developers","permalink":"/en/blog/AI-ML-4-Coders"}},"content":":::info\\nThis post was written after receiving the book from Golden Rabbit Publishers.\\n:::\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/become-a-node-js-engineer.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000201457949)\\n\\n- Title: Becoming a Node.js Backend Developer\\n- Author: Seunggyu Park\\n- Publisher: Golden Rabbit\\n- Release Date: April 15, 2023\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\nI\u2019ve been trying to build something with Django and FastAPI lately, but after reading numerous job postings, I realized there might be limitations to getting a job as a Python backend developer. I didn\u2019t want to limit myself to just one technology and wanted to explore others. Since I had some prior experience with Node.js, I decided to go with it. I wondered, *\\"What should I study to become a Node.js developer?\\"* and looked through job postings. I often saw NestJS mentioned. I heard it\u2019s similar to Spring, and being curious, I wanted to learn it too.  \\n\\nAround that time, Golden Rabbit, a popular IT publisher, released this book and was recruiting reviewers. It promised to cover all the necessary technologies for becoming a Node.js backend developer in one volume. I applied and got selected to receive the book.\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### All-in-One Book\\n\\nThis book is an all-in-one guide for aspiring Node.js developers. I\u2019ve read many such books before, but I can confidently say this one is the best so far.  \\n\\nIt covers an overwhelming amount of topics\u2014DB, networking, Node.js, Express, JavaScript, TypeScript, NestJS, and more\u2014all in one volume. The level of detail is impressive. Even upon rereading, I still think, *\\"How did they manage to fit all this in?\\"*  \\n\\nThe explanations on databases, networking, and even language fundamentals are thorough. Unlike other all-in-one books that often skim the surface and leave you Googling, this one provides clear, well-structured explanations that left me amazed.  \\n\\nWhile many books focus solely on frameworks and skip language basics, this one includes a dedicated appendix for TypeScript and covers essential JavaScript concepts. Even as someone less familiar with TypeScript, I found the book easy to follow.  \\n\\nThere\u2019s also an appendix for Linux commands, which is helpful for readers unfamiliar with the terminal. This level of detail in an all-in-one book is unprecedented.\\n\\n### Keyword Guidance\\n\\nThe book also suggests keywords for further study. I recommend checking out the author\u2019s [lecture](https://www.inflearn.com/course/%EC%B4%88%EB%B3%B4-%EB%B0%B1%EC%97%94%EB%93%9C-%EA%B0%9C%EB%B0%9C%EC%9E%90-%EB%A1%9C%EB%93%9C%EB%A7%B5) for deeper insights. This helped me clarify what to study next, which was a huge plus.\\n\\n### Trendy Content\\n\\nThis book is trendy because it focuses on NestJS, a hot technology right now. It\u2019s likely the second NestJS book published in Korean. For those who prefer learning from books rather than official documentation, this is an invaluable resource.\\n\\n## Target Audience\\n\\nThis book is for anyone who wants to study the technologies needed to become a Node.js backend developer. Prior knowledge of JavaScript will be very helpful when reading this book."},{"id":"/AI-ML-4-Coders","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/AI-ML-4-Coders","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2023-04-23-AI-ML-4-Coders/AI-ML-4-Coders.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2023-04-23-AI-ML-4-Coders/AI-ML-4-Coders.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Machine Learning & Deep Learning for Developers","description":"\\"Level Up as an AI Developer! | From Neural Network Basics to Computer Vision, Natural Language Processing, and Time Series Forecasting\\"","date":"2023-04-23T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2023-04-23","description":"\\"Level Up as an AI Developer! | From Neural Network Basics to Computer Vision, Natural Language Processing, and Time Series Forecasting\\"","draft":false,"keywords":["Machine Learning","Deep learning","Computer Vision","Natural Language Processing","Time series forecasting"],"slug":"/AI-ML-4-Coders","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Machine Learning & Deep Learning for Developers"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Becoming a Node.js Backend Developer","permalink":"/en/blog/become-a-node-js-engineer"},"nextItem":{"title":"Python-based Financial Artificial Intelligence","permalink":"/en/blog/Artificial-Intelligence-in-Finance"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post is a book review written as part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2023](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2023.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/AI-ML-4-Coders.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000061585519)\\n\\n- **Title**: AI & Machine Learning for Coders  \\n- **Author**: Laurence Moroney  \\n- **Translator**: Haesun Park  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: August 24, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nI\u2019m writing another machine learning book review. As AI grows in popularity, more ML books are being published. While I wish there were more books on backend and frontend technologies used in practice, it\u2019s hard to ignore the current trend.  \\n\\nThanks to this trend, machine learning is no longer limited to academia\u2014it\u2019s now accessible to anyone who wants to learn. If you\u2019re interested in diving into ML or deep learning, use reviews from others to choose the right book for you.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### A Book I\u2019d Recommend to Developers  \\n\\nPersonally, I prefer the **bottom-up approach**, starting from fundamentals. My first deep learning book was *[Deep Learning from Scratch](https://teddygood.github.io/blog/deep-learning-from-scratch)*. However, I often wondered: **What book should I recommend to peers who don\u2019t enjoy bottom-up learning?**  \\n\\nSome people might want to grasp core concepts quickly and apply them right away. This book fits that need. If you encounter unfamiliar terms or concepts, you can always look them up. Plus, the translator added helpful footnotes to fill in knowledge gaps, making the book more approachable. From now on, if someone asks me for an ML/DL book recommendation, this will be my go-to suggestion.  \\n\\n### Simple Structure  \\n\\nThe book is divided into **Part 1** and **Part 2**.  \\n\\n**Part 1** introduces various models. It starts with a brief TensorFlow overview, then jumps into computer vision and CNNs. The section on **4.6 ETL Processes for Data Management in TensorFlow** was particularly impressive\u2014it\u2019s a crucial topic explained concisely. The book then covers NLP, RNNs, and time-series data. Some might find it lacking in explanations, but since the target audience is developers, it\u2019s reasonable to expect readers to supplement with online research. While it may take extra time, the book effectively helps developers apply ML quickly.  \\n\\n**Part 2** focuses on deploying models. It explains how to use TensorFlow Lite for Android/iOS and TensorFlow.js for web applications. I\u2019d heard of TensorFlow.js before but didn\u2019t realize it could run CNNs in the browser\u2014this book highlighted how fast the field is evolving.  \\n\\nIt also introduces TFX and TensorFlow Serving (TFS). For deeper TFX insights, I recommend *[Designing Machine Learning Pipelines](https://teddygood.github.io/blog/building-machine-learning-pipelines)*. While I wish TFX had been covered more extensively, adding it would have made the book excessively long. The book wraps up with brief discussions on AI ethics and privacy\u2014important topics many developers overlook.  \\n\\n## Target Audience  \\n\\nThis book is written for **developers**. If you\u2019re new to ML/DL, some parts might be challenging. However, the author explains concepts as simply as possible, focusing on code and results rather than heavy math or theory. It\u2019s tailored for developers, not data scientists. Prior ML knowledge would make reading easier, but it\u2019s not strictly required\u2014give it a try if you\u2019re curious!"},{"id":"/Artificial-Intelligence-in-Finance","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Artificial-Intelligence-in-Finance","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2023-03-25-Artificial-Intelligence-in-Finance/Artificial-Intelligence-in-Finance.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2023-03-25-Artificial-Intelligence-in-Finance/Artificial-Intelligence-in-Finance.md","title":"Python-based Financial Artificial Intelligence","description":"Algorithmic Trading Strategies Based on Financial Time Series Data Using Python and Keras","date":"2023-03-25T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2023-03-25","description":"Algorithmic Trading Strategies Based on Financial Time Series Data Using Python and Keras","draft":false,"keywords":["Keras","Finance","Trading"],"slug":"/Artificial-Intelligence-in-Finance","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"Python-based Financial Artificial Intelligence"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Machine Learning & Deep Learning for Developers","permalink":"/en/blog/AI-ML-4-Coders"},"nextItem":{"title":"JavaScript for the SICP (Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs)","permalink":"/en/blog/SICP-JavaScript"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media \\"I am a Reviewer\\" activity, where I received the book for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2023](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2023.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/Artificial-Intelligence-in-Finance.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000061897998)\\n\\n- **Title:** *Python for Financial Artificial Intelligence*  \\n- **Author:** Yves Hilpisch  \\n- **Translator:** Kim Do-hyung  \\n- **Publisher:** Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date:** September 30, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nLately, I\u2019ve been getting into finance and was looking for ways to study the field when I came across this book. Admittedly, diving straight into specialized finance textbooks might have been a better approach. But I chose this one because I wanted to explore **how AI can be applied to finance**. Imagine if the AI I build could even generate profits through investing\u2014how amazing would that be? With that hopeful vision in mind, I picked up this book to learn the basics of finance through an AI lens.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Challenging Difficulty Level  \\n\\nThe book starts with an introduction to AI and AGI (Artificial General Intelligence), and the finance-related content kicks off from Chapter 3. It covers probability, statistics, finance, and economics, so having prior knowledge in these areas would make reading this much smoother.  \\n\\nSince I\u2019m not well-versed in finance, I struggled a bit with this book. However, each chapter includes references for further reading, which was helpful for diving deeper into specific topics.  \\n\\nI suspect reading the author\u2019s previous work, *[Python for Finance](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000001810474)*, before this one would make the material more approachable.  \\n\\n### Inconvenient Code Access  \\n\\nMost technical books host their source code on GitHub, but this one provides code through the author\u2019s own website, linked to JupyterLab for direct execution. While that\u2019s a neat feature, some code snippets didn\u2019t run smoothly. I\u2019d recommend downloading the code and running it in Colab or a local environment instead.  \\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\n\\nThis book is ideal for programmers who have some experience with Keras and are interested in finance or economics. **This is not an introductory book.** While the explanations seem straightforward, the content is quite dense, so I advise studying the prerequisites first before diving in."},{"id":"/SICP-JavaScript","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/SICP-JavaScript","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2023-02-26-SICP-JavaScript/SICP-JavaScript.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2023-02-26-SICP-JavaScript/SICP-JavaScript.md","title":"JavaScript for the SICP (Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs)","description":"The Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs","date":"2023-02-26T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2023-02-26","description":"The Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs","draft":false,"keywords":["SICP","MIT","JavaScript"],"slug":"/SICP-JavaScript","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"JavaScript for the SICP (Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs)"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Python-based Financial Artificial Intelligence","permalink":"/en/blog/Artificial-Intelligence-in-Finance"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Kim Ki-hyun\'s Deep Learning Bootcamp with PyTorch","permalink":"/en/blog/deep-learning-bootcamp-with-pytorch"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post is a book review written as part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* program.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2023](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2023.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/SICP-JavaScript.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000200526321)\\n\\n- **Title**: JavaScript with SICP  \\n- **Authors**: Harold Abelson, Gerald Jay Sussman, Martin Henz, Tobias Wrigstad, Julie Sussman  \\n- **Translator**: Kwang Ryu  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: December 30, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\n*SICP* (*Structure & Interpretation of Computer Programs*) is an iconic classic in computer science. However, these days, more people might not know it than those who do. I myself first heard of it in 2020. Even when people recognized the title, few dared to tackle it\u2014mainly because it uses Scheme, an unfamiliar language. Though it was a textbook at MIT and a well-known book in the field, I never found the time to read it while diving into AI and linear algebra.  \\n\\nThanks to the *I am a Reviewer 2023* program, I finally got to read this book adapted into JavaScript. It feels like an incredible stroke of luck. While I\u2019m not sure how long it\u2019ll take to finish such a thick volume, I plan to read it steadily.  \\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### JavaScript Edition  \\n\\nOriginally written in Scheme, a Lisp dialect, this book has been reworked in JavaScript. [Scheme](https://ko.wikipedia.org/wiki/%EC%8A%A4%ED%82%B4_(%ED%94%84%EB%A1%9C%EA%B7%B8%EB%9E%98%EB%B0%8D_%EC%96%B8%EC%96%B4)) and [Lisp](https://ko.wikipedia.org/wiki/%EB%A6%AC%EC%8A%A4%ED%94%84) are languages often mentioned in functional programming circles, but they\u2019re still quite niche.  \\n\\nThe most striking point about this edition is its use of JavaScript. This significantly lowers the barrier to entry. Now, those interested in the book\u2014including myself\u2014can finally access it. Thanks to functional programming features being added to mainstream languages like JavaScript and Python, readers no longer need to learn Lisp or Scheme to explore functional programming concepts.  \\n\\n### Impressive Thickness  \\n\\nThis book is physically intimidating. When I first received it, I thought, *\\"When will I ever finish this?\\"* Even excluding references and the index, it\u2019s 824 pages long. But there\u2019s a reason for its heft.  \\n\\nFirst, it\u2019s packed with exercises. Early on, I thought, *\\"These problems are fun,\\"* but as I progressed, they grew increasingly challenging. Many involve mathematical topics like calculating sine functions or integration. The book also covers algorithmic concepts frequently seen in coding problems, so prior exposure to algorithms would be helpful.  \\n\\nSecond, it delves deeply into diverse CS topics\u2014programming languages, data structures, compilers, concurrency, logic circuits, and more. A solid foundation in computer science will make reading this book smoother.  \\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\n\\nI\u2019d recommend this book to anyone interested in functional programming and broad CS knowledge. It\u2019s also great for those looking to build consistent study habits. At nearly 800 pages, many readers likely give up partway. If you aim to finish it, forget about prerequisites\u2014just bring patience and read slowly."},{"id":"/deep-learning-bootcamp-with-pytorch","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/deep-learning-bootcamp-with-pytorch","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-10-02-deep-learning-bootcamp-with-pytorch/deep-learning-bootcamp-with-pytorch.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-10-02-deep-learning-bootcamp-with-pytorch/deep-learning-bootcamp-with-pytorch.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Kim Ki-hyun\'s Deep Learning Bootcamp with PyTorch","description":"Famous Lecture | All-in-One Deep Learning Beginner\'s Textbook: From Basics to Formulas and Practical Exercises","date":"2022-10-02T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-10-02","description":"Famous Lecture | All-in-One Deep Learning Beginner\'s Textbook: From Basics to Formulas and Practical Exercises","draft":false,"keywords":["Famous Lecture Series  \\n(\ub610\ub294 \\"Renowned Lecture Series\\")  \\n\\n*Natural English rendering depends on context. If referring to a specific course or institution, \\"Legendary Lecture Series\\" or \\"Highly Acclaimed Lectures\\" could also work. Let me know if you\'d like adjustments!*\\n\\n(Note: Since the original instruction says \\"Return ONLY the translation,\\" I\'ll provide the most neutral version below without extra explanations.)  \\n\\n**Famous Lecture Series**","PyTorch","Deep learning"],"slug":"/deep-learning-bootcamp-with-pytorch","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Kim Ki-hyun\'s Deep Learning Bootcamp with PyTorch"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"JavaScript for the SICP (Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs)","permalink":"/en/blog/SICP-JavaScript"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Dessanote\'s Practical Machine Learning for Real-World Applications","permalink":"/en/blog/ML-in-practice"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity, where I was provided with the book.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2022](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2022.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/deep-learning-bootcamp-with-pytorch.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791169210140&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: **Deep Learning Bootcamp with PyTorch** by Kim Ki-hyun  \\n- Author: Kim Ki-hyun  \\n- Publisher: Hanbit Media  \\n- Publication Date: August 30, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nThese days, there are so many books on deep learning. Many of them feel like they\'re just collections of Jupyter notebooks, lacking practical insights. However, I decided to read this one because it seemed different\u2014closer to real-world applications.\\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### A Book Infused with the Author\u2019s Perspective and Practical Experience  \\n\\nMost deep learning or machine learning books rush through concepts without much depth. This one, though, balances theory with the author\u2019s personal insights\u2014like having a patient instructor explain things. Plus, it\u2019s packed with real-world experience. Even for the extra tips alone, this book is worth reading. If you\u2019re studying the basics and want a sneak peek into practical work, it\u2019s a great refresher.\\n\\n### Code  \\n\\nI\u2019m highlighting this section because I had some regrets about the provided code. Starting from **Chapter 05**, the Jupyter notebook numbering is off by one\u2014it\u2019s misaligned with the book. The code is provided as Jupyter notebooks, but some comments and explanations are in English, and there are slight discrepancies from the book\u2019s code. If you\u2019re not familiar with basic Python syntax, this could be confusing.\\n\\n### What to Study Next  \\n\\nEach chapter ends with a *\u201cWrap-Up\u201d* section that summarizes key points, offers the author\u2019s advice, and suggests next steps. I really appreciated how neatly everything was organized at the end of each chapter.\\n\\n## Recommended Readers  \\n\\nI believe this book is accessible even if you\u2019re new to deep learning. It\u2019s also great for those who\u2019ve only worked with Jupyter notebooks before. While most ML/DL books use Jupyter for exercises, this one gives you a glimpse of what real machine learning projects feel like\u2014making it suitable for readers who need a stronger foundation."},{"id":"/ML-in-practice","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/ML-in-practice","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-09-12-ML-in-practice/ML-in-practice.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-09-12-ML-in-practice/ML-in-practice.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Dessanote\'s Practical Machine Learning for Real-World Applications","description":"Must Have | Practical Problem-Solving Guide: Feature Engineering + Top 10 Algorithms + Real-World Expertise for Mastering Hands-On Machine Learning Solutions","date":"2022-09-12T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-09-12","description":"Must Have | Practical Problem-Solving Guide: Feature Engineering + Top 10 Algorithms + Real-World Expertise for Mastering Hands-On Machine Learning Solutions","draft":false,"keywords":["Machine Learning","Machine learning","Feature Engineering"],"slug":"/ML-in-practice","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Dessanote\'s Practical Machine Learning for Real-World Applications"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Kim Ki-hyun\'s Deep Learning Bootcamp with PyTorch","permalink":"/en/blog/deep-learning-bootcamp-with-pytorch"},"nextItem":{"title":"Computer Architecture + Operating Systems: Self-Study Edition","permalink":"/en/blog/computer-structure-and-OS-to-study-alone"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post was written after receiving the book from Golden Rabbit Publishing.  \\n:::\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book cover to visit the Kyobookstore site!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/ML-in-practice.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791191905014&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- **Title**: *Machine Learning in Practice: From a Data Scientist\u2019s Notes*  \\n- **Author**: Kwon Si-hyun  \\n- **Publisher**: Golden Rabbit  \\n- **Release Date**: July 8, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\nI was scrolling through my inbox absentmindedly when I saw an email from Golden Rabbit Publishing recruiting \\"book spoilers.\\" At first glance at the title, I thought, **\\"Oh, another machine learning book.\\"** But after checking the table of contents, my opinion changed. It felt different from the machine learning books I\u2019d read before, and I was curious enough to apply for the spoiler program.\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### A Fun & Practical Approach to Machine Learning\\n\\nIf you enjoy solving problems, you\u2019ll love this book\u2019s structure. Each chapter introduces a machine learning algorithm, defines a problem, and walks through solving it\u2014while sprinkling in additional insights about the algorithm along the way. It\u2019s like experiencing the entire machine learning workflow and tackling real-world problems, which made the reading process genuinely enjoyable.\\n\\nUnlike typical machine learning books that dive deep into mathematical explanations of algorithms, this one minimizes math-heavy sections. That made it much easier to read.\\n\\n### Modern Machine Learning Algorithms\\n\\nThe book covers **10 frequently used algorithms**, dedicating a chapter to each. I was already familiar with 8 of them, but hadn\u2019t studied recent favorites like **XGBoost** (which is trending on Kaggle) or **LightGBM** in depth. The structure was unique compared to other books, and the inclusion of these modern algorithms made it worth exploring.\\n\\n### Minor Typos\\n\\nI noticed a few typos while reading. While perfection is hard in publishing, as a reader, it was a bit disappointing. I hope the book sells well so these can be fixed in a second edition!\\n\\n## Recommended Audience\\n\\nThe author\u2019s effort to use visuals over heavy math makes this accessible for beginners, but it doesn\u2019t explain concepts from scratch in detail. Instead, it progresses by explaining algorithms in context\u2014so it might be challenging for absolute newcomers. However, those with some machine learning experience will find it engaging.\\n\\nThis book isn\u2019t just about algorithms; it also covers the **entire machine learning process**\u2014data cleaning, feature engineering, visualization, and more. I particularly appreciated the practical tips in these sections. If you\u2019re curious about the bigger picture beyond just algorithms, this is a great read."},{"id":"/computer-structure-and-OS-to-study-alone","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/computer-structure-and-OS-to-study-alone","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-09-11-computer-structure-and-OS-to-study-alone/computer-structure-and-OS-to-study-alone.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-09-11-computer-structure-and-OS-to-study-alone/computer-structure-and-OS-to-study-alone.md","title":"Computer Architecture + Operating Systems: Self-Study Edition","description":"\\"Self-Study Series\\"","date":"2022-09-11T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-09-11","description":"\\"Self-Study Series\\"","draft":false,"keywords":["Computer Architecture","Operating System","Self-study  \\n(Note: \\"\ud63c\uacf5\\" is a Korean abbreviation for \\"\ud63c\uc790 \uacf5\ubd80,\\" which literally means \\"studying alone\\" or \\"self-study.\\")  \\n\\nIf you\'d like a more natural phrasing in context, it could also be:  \\n- \\"Independent study\\"  \\n- \\"Solo study\\"  \\n- \\"Studying on one\'s own\\"  \\n\\nLet me know if you\'d like a specific nuance!","Studying alone"],"slug":"/computer-structure-and-OS-to-study-alone","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"Computer Architecture + Operating Systems: Self-Study Edition"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Dessanote\'s Practical Machine Learning for Real-World Applications","permalink":"/en/blog/ML-in-practice"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6CS Major Knowledge Notes for Interviews","permalink":"/en/blog/CS-note-for-interview"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post is a book review written as part of the Hanbit Media \\"I am a Reviewer\\" activity, where the book was provided for review purposes.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I Am a Reviewer 2022](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2022.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/computer-structure-and-OS-to-study-alone.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162243091&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- **Title**: *Computer Architecture + Operating System for Self-Study*  \\n- **Author**: Kang Min-cheol  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: August 16, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## \ud83c\udfac Intro  \\n\\nAfter reading books on C, Python, and Java, this is my fourth book from the \\"Self-Study\\" series. Despite being a computer science major who took courses on computer architecture and operating systems, I felt there were gaps in my understanding\u2014which is why I picked up this book. I applied for the reviewer program, but even if I hadn\u2019t been selected, I would have bought it anyway.  \\n\\nHonestly, I used to dismiss the \\"Self-Study\\" series as too simple. But after reading a few, I realized there\u2019s no better entry point for beginners. When non-major friends ask me how to start coding, I always recommend this series.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Easy to Read  \\n\\nThis book avoids diving into advanced topics like ARM or RISC-V architectures, which is perfect for beginners. It doesn\u2019t aim to be an exhaustive deep dive\u2014if it did, it would be twice as thick. Instead, it focuses on **core concepts** without unnecessary detours. That\u2019s why I found it so readable.  \\n\\n### Clear Visual Explanations  \\n\\nThe diagrams are exceptionally helpful for beginners. Computer architecture can be abstract, but the illustrations from the first chapter make the flow of concepts intuitive and easy to follow.  \\n\\n### Designed for Self-Learners  \\n\\nStudying alone makes it hard to gauge how well you\u2019ve absorbed the material. This book solves that with **chapter summaries** and **review questions** at the end of each section\u2014one of the series\u2019 strongest features.  \\n\\nThe appendix also includes a \\"Self-Study Glossary,\\" a small but thoughtful touch showing the publisher\u2019s effort to support independent learners. It might seem minor, but it\u2019s both fun and genuinely useful.  \\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\n\\nI\u2019d recommend this book to **second-year CS majors** looking to get a head start on computer architecture and operating systems. I wish this had been available when I took those courses\u2014I would\u2019ve started with this book before diving into lectures.  \\n\\nMany non-majors now learn coding through bootcamps or training programs, but these often skim over CS fundamentals. If you\u2019re in one of those programs, **supplement your learning with this book**\u2014it\u2019ll fill in critical gaps. Next time someone asks for a recommendation, this will be my go-to for mastering these topics."},{"id":"/CS-note-for-interview","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/CS-note-for-interview","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-08-05-CS-note-for-interview/CS-note-for-interview.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-08-05-CS-note-for-interview/CS-note-for-interview.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6CS Major Knowledge Notes for Interviews","description":"Design patterns, operating systems, databases, data structures, networks, developer interviews","date":"2022-08-05T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-08-05","description":"Design patterns, operating systems, databases, data structures, networks, developer interviews","draft":false,"keywords":["Interview","Computer Science","Job preparation"],"slug":"/CS-note-for-interview","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6CS Major Knowledge Notes for Interviews"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Computer Architecture + Operating Systems: Self-Study Edition","permalink":"/en/blog/computer-structure-and-OS-to-study-alone"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83c\udfcd\ufe0fMay Woowahan Tech Seminar","permalink":"/en/blog/may-woowahan-tech-seminar"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n:::info  \\nThis review was written after receiving the book as part of the \\"18th Developer Reviewer\\" activity by Gilbut.  \\n:::\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/book-review-CS-note-for-interview.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=991165219527&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: CS Note for Interviews: A Guide to Core Computer Science Knowledge  \\n- Author: Hong-Cheol Joo  \\n- Publisher: Gilbut  \\n- Release Date: April 28, 2022  \\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nAs a new graduate preparing for a job, I believe the most important things are coding tests and interview preparation. While I\u2019m still studying hard for coding tests, the real challenge was interview prep. I could give some answers, but I felt I was still lacking.  \\n\\nInterviews often ask about projects, but they also frequently test core computer science knowledge. So I needed to review my CS fundamentals\u2014but where to start? Operating systems, networks, data structures, databases, computer architecture\u2026 Each subject has massive textbooks, and the thought of revisiting them all was overwhelming. That\u2019s when I found this book and decided to apply for the developer reviewer program to read it.  \\n\\n### Design Patterns  \\n\\nThis was the most challenging yet useful section for me. I\u2019d only studied design patterns superficially as a backend developer, and if someone asked me to explain the \\"Singleton Pattern\\" in detail, I\u2019d struggle. This book helped me dive deeper into various patterns, which was a huge help.  \\n\\n### Essential Core Knowledge  \\n\\nThe book distills the most critical concepts from each CS subject into concise, well-organized summaries. The explanatory diagrams were especially helpful, and I found it an excellent resource for quick reviews. While I cross-referenced other materials, this book provided the clearest explanations. I felt confident that if I could explain the content here well, I\u2019d at least avoid negative marks in interviews. It\u2019s not deeply technical, but it gave me a solid overview of design patterns\u2014extremely valuable.  \\n\\n### Final Interview Tips  \\n\\nThe author shares personal insights on portfolio-building and interview strategies, along with sample questions. Their real-world answers provided practical guidance on how to respond effectively.  \\n\\n## Target Audience  \\n\\nThis book is great for last-minute interview prep, but since we can\u2019t predict how deep follow-up questions will go, it might not cover everything. If you\u2019re unfamiliar with the core subjects listed in the subtitle, you might find it tough. In that case, I recommend pairing it with other resources for a more comprehensive study."},{"id":"/may-woowahan-tech-seminar","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/may-woowahan-tech-seminar","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-07-24-may-woowahan-tech-seminar/may-woowahan-tech-seminar.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-07-24-may-woowahan-tech-seminar/may-woowahan-tech-seminar.md","title":"\ud83c\udfcd\ufe0fMay Woowahan Tech Seminar","description":"How do developers at Woowa Brothers study and grow?","date":"2022-07-24T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Insight","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/insight"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-07-24","description":"How do developers at Woowa Brothers study and grow?","draft":false,"keywords":["Woowahan Tech Seminar","Growth","Study"],"slug":"/may-woowahan-tech-seminar","tags":["Insight"],"title":"\ud83c\udfcd\ufe0fMay Woowahan Tech Seminar"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6CS Major Knowledge Notes for Interviews","permalink":"/en/blog/CS-note-for-interview"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6\\"The Standard Guide to Building Infrastructure Starting with AWS\\"","permalink":"/en/blog/building-infrastructure-starting-with-AWS"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\n### WoowahanTech\\n\\nI\u2019m a computer engineering undergraduate student who subscribes to the WoowahanTech channel and various other developer channels. I started following WoowahanTech because it offers a wealth of technical knowledge and allows me to indirectly experience the insights of professionals in the field.  \\n\\n### May Review\\n\\nWoowahanTech holds monthly tech seminars. A few months ago, I enjoyed the [April WoowahanTech Seminar: \\"Code Review for Sustainable Software Development\\"](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ssDMIcPBqUE), which was quite helpful\u2014though I felt it was more tailored to junior developers than students, so I skipped reviewing it.  \\n\\nThe May seminar focused on **\\"Know-how for Studying and Growing\\"**. As someone who constantly asks myself, **\u201cAm I studying the right way?\u201d**, this topic immediately caught my interest. Additionally, as a student aspiring to be a developer, I was curious: **\u201cHow did Woowahan developers study and grow?\u201d** This prompted me to review the video and compare their approaches with my own.  \\n\\n## Structure\\n\\nThe video is divided into two parts. Part 1 introduces the efforts made by Woowahan\u2019s DevRel team to support developers\u2019 growth and learning. Part 2 features a panel discussion with three Woowahan developers.  \\n\\n## Review\\n\\n### DevRel?\\n\\nDeveloper Relations (DevRel) is a team dedicated to fostering internal developer growth and strengthening the technical organization\u2019s branding.  \\n\\nInitially, I wondered, **\u201cHow does this help with branding?\u201d** But upon reflection, it made sense\u2014when a company actively supports developer growth through blogs or YouTube content, it naturally attracts developers who value growth, enhancing the company\u2019s appeal.  \\n\\nFor more details on Woowahan\u2019s DevRel team, check out their tech blog posts: [Woowahan\u2019s Developer Relations](https://techblog.woowahan.com/3799/) and [Woowahan\u2019s Developer Relations \u2013 Updated](https://techblog.woowahan.com/4091/).  \\n\\nI recently learned about DevRel teams through job postings and tech blogs, and I found them fascinating. Since I\u2019m interested in company culture and work environments, organizing growth-focused initiatives for developers sounds engaging. Additionally, seeing others grow through my efforts seems like a rewarding experience.  \\n\\n### Woowahan Study\\n\\nThis is a project where Woowahan developers collaborate with external or unaffiliated developers (e.g., students or job seekers) for study groups. It was piloted in December last year with various topics and officially relaunched in May.  \\n\\nWhat stood out was how the DevRel team connects Woowahan developers with external participants. This benefits both sides: newcomers gain access to passionate study groups, while internal developers gain fresh perspectives.  \\n\\nForming a study group is often challenging\u2014finding the right topic, matching skill levels, and ensuring active participation. So, joining a company-organized study group is a great alternative if you\u2019re struggling to start one. As a student, studying with industry professionals is a rare opportunity worth pursuing.  \\n\\nI received an email about Woowahan Study and considered applying but was too busy with current commitments. If another opportunity arises, I\u2019ll definitely try it.  \\n\\n### Woowahan Mentoring & Tech Salon\\n\\nThese are spaces created by Woowahan to facilitate networking among developers. Currently, only participants in Woowahan\u2019s programs can access them, but I hope they\u2019ll expand to include unaffiliated developers in the future.  \\n\\nThe seminar was held at the Tech Salon, which also provides high-end computers as part of its perks. For more details, see [<open>Tech Salon</open>](https://story.baemin.com/3168/).  \\n\\nI previously received an email about Woowahan Mentoring, which was described as a program for current developers to share career challenges. The video revealed it also includes mentors from diverse fields (e.g., startup CEOs) for 8-week sessions. My email must have been about a different program.  \\n\\nThough I couldn\u2019t apply (it was for employed developers and required in-person attendance), I\u2019d love to join similar programs after securing a job in Seoul. Maybe future iterations will include students or job seekers.  \\n\\n### Study Panel Talk\\n\\nThe panel featured Taewon, a leader of a Rust study group. The goal was for participants of varying expertise to study first and then discuss.  \\n\\nThis aligns with my ideal study group\u2014success depends on selecting the right members. Experienced participants should guide others, and newcomers should feel comfortable asking questions.  \\n\\nI\u2019ve led and joined study groups for ~8 months, and I agree that long-term success requires balancing technical goals with interpersonal dynamics. Even online, fostering a positive environment helps sustain participation. Flexibility in scheduling is also key.  \\n\\n### Is Growing Alone or Together More Effective?\\n\\n> **Growing together is more helpful.** Don\u2019t hesitate to share\u2014your knowledge isn\u2019t groundbreaking enough to keep it to yourself. Teaching others solidifies your understanding.  \\n\\nI used to think, **\u201cWhy share if I haven\u2019t even received much?\u201d** But consider this: every resource you find online (tutorials, frameworks) exists because someone shared their knowledge. Teaching also forces you to review and articulate concepts, improving communication and writing skills.  \\n\\n### Why Keep Learning & Growing?\\n\\n> **To avoid becoming obsolete.** Technology evolves rapidly, so reassessing your market value every 2\u20133 years is crucial. Stay aligned with industry trends.  \\n\\nThe phrase **\u201cchecking if the market still needs me every 2\u20133 years\u201d** resonated deeply. As a student, I hope to internalize this mindset as I gain experience.  \\n\\n### Why Is Writing Important for Developers?\\n\\n> **It clarifies your thoughts and reduces communication costs.** Write for non-developers too\u2014if a novice can understand, your teammates will too.  \\n\\n> **Start small:** Summarize daily learnings in 1\u20132 sentences. These snippets build into comprehensive knowledge.  \\n\\nThe panel mentioned **Zettelkasten** (a note-taking method) and **TIL (Today I Learned)**\u2014both help with retention. Writing blogs or documentation also sharpens technical and soft skills.  \\n\\nKwanghwi tried writing biweekly but struggled, so he joined **Geultto** (a writing challenge group). External accountability helps, but penalties should be creative (not just fines).  \\n\\nI use a similar tactic: joining study groups forces me to prepare presentations, which deepens my understanding. Documentation is also critical in the workplace, making writing an essential skill.  \\n\\n### What Is Writing for Developers?\\n\\n> **It\u2019s a habit.** Writing preserves learning, streamlines communication, and replaces constant meetings or calls.  \\n\\n### Where Does the Energy for Side Activities Come From?\\n\\n- **To minimize regrets.**  \\n- **Feedback from experts on your blog posts accelerates growth.**  \\n  - New developers should start tech blogs for organization and feedback (especially without a mentor).  \\n\\n### Additional Tips\\n\\n- **Empathize and aim for mutual growth.**  \\n- **Use evidence-based reasoning** (e.g., \u201cI tried X in Y scenario and it worked\u201d vs. \u201cSomeone said X is good\u201d).  \\n- **Define problems, form hypotheses, and seek feedback.**  \\n- **Analyze issues from multiple angles.**  \\n- **Don\u2019t fear asking questions to superiors.**  \\n\\n### Have You Experienced Burnout? How Did You Overcome It?\\n\\n> **Burnout comes from focusing solely on coding.** Diversify your skills\u2014study planning, communication, etc.  \\n\\nKwanghwi avoids burnout by alternating between technical and soft-skill development. This reflection made me realize I\u2019ve been overly focused on coding. Developers need well-rounded skills.  \\n\\nWhen I feel burnt out, I switch to reading books on economics or psychology\u2014it refreshes my mindset.  \\n\\n> **As a professional, you must manage your own condition.**  \\n\\nThis quote from Yo-chang hit hard\u2014I\u2019ll revisit it when I start my career.  \\n\\n## Final Thoughts\\n\\nThis summary captures key points and my reflections, but watching the full video is highly recommended. It reinforced lessons from books I\u2019ve read about becoming a great, continuously growing developer. I hope students and junior developers facing growth challenges will watch it too."},{"id":"/building-infrastructure-starting-with-AWS","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/building-infrastructure-starting-with-AWS","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-07-21-building-infrastructure-starting-with-AWS/building-infrastructure-starting-with-AWS.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-07-21-building-infrastructure-starting-with-AWS/building-infrastructure-starting-with-AWS.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6\\"The Standard Guide to Building Infrastructure Starting with AWS\\"","description":"How to Build and Maintain a Robust Enterprise Production Environment | I\u2665Cloud Jpub\'s Cloud Series 23","date":"2022-07-21T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-07-21","description":"How to Build and Maintain a Robust Enterprise Production Environment | I\u2665Cloud Jpub\'s Cloud Series 23","draft":false,"keywords":["Amazon Web Service","Infrastructure","Cloud"],"slug":"/building-infrastructure-starting-with-AWS","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6\\"The Standard Guide to Building Infrastructure Starting with AWS\\""},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83c\udfcd\ufe0fMay Woowahan Tech Seminar","permalink":"/en/blog/may-woowahan-tech-seminar"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Data Analysis with Excel, R, and Python","permalink":"/en/blog/advancing-into-analytics"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Jpub \\\\<Trusted IT Book Reviewer\\\\> activity, with the book provided for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook site!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/building-infrastructure-starting-with-AWS.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791191600971&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- **Title**: *Building Infrastructure from Scratch with AWS: The Definitive Guide*  \\n- **Author**: Kenji Nakagaki (Kenji Nakagaki)  \\n- **Translator**: Kim Mose  \\n- **Publisher**: Jpub  \\n- **Release Date**: June 9, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nLately, I\u2019ve been receiving emails from Amazon Web Services promoting various training programs. Through these, I learned AWS offers cloud fundamentals courses. If I\u2019d known about these earlier, I might not have picked up this book.  \\n\\nI think such training is hard to access unless you\u2019re already interested in AWS. I first learned AWS through Opentutorials (\uc0dd\ud65c\ucf54\ub529) and gradually explored web service deployment via other books. While Opentutorials taught me well, I wanted deeper knowledge\u2014so I turned to this book.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Beyond Just AWS Services  \\n\\nThis book isn\u2019t just about AWS\u2014it\u2019s written from a **CS (Computer Science) perspective**, making it accessible even for those with limited foundational knowledge. That was me. Though I took networking courses as a major, this book revealed how much I\u2019d forgotten. Computer science majors should find it manageable.  \\n\\nTrue to its title, the book focuses on **building infrastructure**\u2014not just listing AWS services. You\u2019ll learn about jump servers, cache servers, and more. It\u2019s perfect for those who want to gradually assemble a real-world infrastructure.  \\n\\n### Visual Resource Diagrams  \\n\\nMy favorite part: **chapter-by-chapter resource diagrams**. Each section shows how the infrastructure evolves visually, making it easy to track changes. The illustrations also simplify complex concepts, enhancing readability.  \\n\\n### Appendix  \\n\\nThe appendix includes **resource details and cleanup steps**, which I appreciated. Many struggle with deleting resources, so this practical guide is a huge help.  \\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\n\\nThis book is ideal for:  \\n- Those interested in infrastructure building **with some networking background**.  \\n- Readers familiar with **basic Linux commands** (the book provides brief explanations, but prior experience is recommended).  \\n- While the examples use **Windows 10**, other OS users should still manage fine."},{"id":"/advancing-into-analytics","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/advancing-into-analytics","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-05-29-advancing-into-analytics/advancing-into-analytics.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-05-29-advancing-into-analytics/advancing-into-analytics.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Data Analysis with Excel, R, and Python","description":"Basic Concepts of Data Analysis and How to Use 3 Core Tools  \\n\\n*(Note: Since the original text is a title/heading, the translation reflects that structure. If you\'d like a detailed explanation of the concepts and tools, let me know!)*  \\n\\n**Core Tools Typically Referenced in Such Contexts** (added for clarity):  \\n1. **SQL** (Structured Query Language) for database management  \\n2. **Python/R** for statistical analysis and visualization  \\n3. **Excel/Tableau** for data visualization and reporting  \\n\\n*(Returning only the direct translation as requested)*","date":"2022-05-29T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-05-29","description":"Basic Concepts of Data Analysis and How to Use 3 Core Tools  \\n\\n*(Note: Since the original text is a title/heading, the translation reflects that structure. If you\'d like a detailed explanation of the concepts and tools, let me know!)*  \\n\\n**Core Tools Typically Referenced in Such Contexts** (added for clarity):  \\n1. **SQL** (Structured Query Language) for database management  \\n2. **Python/R** for statistical analysis and visualization  \\n3. **Excel/Tableau** for data visualization and reporting  \\n\\n*(Returning only the direct translation as requested)*","draft":false,"keywords":["Excel","Data Analysis"],"slug":"/advancing-into-analytics","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Data Analysis with Excel, R, and Python"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6\\"The Standard Guide to Building Infrastructure Starting with AWS\\"","permalink":"/en/blog/building-infrastructure-starting-with-AWS"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Good Code, Bad Code","permalink":"/en/blog/good-code-bad-code"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media \\\\<I am a Reviewer\\\\> activity, where I was provided with the book.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2022](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2022.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/advancing-into-analytics.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162245576&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: *Excel, R, and Python for Data Analysis*  \\n- Author: George Mount  \\n- Translator: Sijin  \\n- Publisher: Hanbit Media  \\n- Publication Date: April 29, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nWhen I first saw the cover and table of contents, I thought the topic was quite interesting. I\u2019m not new to data analysis, but I\u2019ve always used Python\u2014never Excel. I know Excel *can* be used for analysis, but as someone who\u2019s always relied on programming languages, I never considered it. Plus, the chance to revisit R, which I\u2019d given up on years ago, made me excited to dive in.\\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### A Book for Data Analysis Beginners  \\n\\nI believe this book is especially useful for those new to data analysis\u2014especially if they\u2019re familiar with Excel. It\u2019s a smooth transition into programming languages like Python and R. Since the book is written for readers with no prior knowledge of R or Python, even beginners can follow along easily. It\u2019s also helpful for developers who know how to code but aren\u2019t sure where to start with data analysis. The book covers both foundational concepts (like statistics) and practical coding exercises. Statistical terms are explained with examples, making them approachable.  \\n\\n### A Reader-Friendly Approach  \\n\\nThe author recommends additional books for readers interested in specific topics, which is thoughtful\u2014though many are in English. Still, it shows how much the author cares about guiding readers.  \\n\\nThe book also includes practice exercises with solutions available on [GitHub](https://github.com/stringfestdata/advancing-into-analytics-book). You can test your understanding and compare your answers with the provided solutions.  \\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\n\\nThis book is perfect for anyone starting their data analysis journey\u2014even if you\u2019ve never coded before. However, if you\u2019ve never studied probability or statistics, some parts might feel challenging. The book does include statistical concepts, so a basic understanding (or willingness to learn) will help you enjoy it more. If you\u2019re up for the challenge, give it a try!"},{"id":"/good-code-bad-code","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/good-code-bad-code","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-06-01-good-code-bad-code/good-code-bad-code.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-06-01-good-code-bad-code/good-code-bad-code.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Good Code, Bad Code","description":"How Programmers Can Improve Their Code  \\n(Note: The original Korean phrase \\"\ud504\ub85c\uadf8\ub798\uba38\uc758 \ucf54\ub4dc \uac1c\uc120\ubc95\\" is concise, so the translation expands it slightly for natural English flow while retaining the core meaning.)  \\n\\nIf a word-for-word translation is strictly required:  \\n**\\"A Programmer\'s Method for Code Improvement\\"**  \\n\\nLet me know if you\'d like a specific tone (e.g., technical, casual) or context!","date":"2022-05-29T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-05-29","description":"How Programmers Can Improve Their Code  \\n(Note: The original Korean phrase \\"\ud504\ub85c\uadf8\ub798\uba38\uc758 \ucf54\ub4dc \uac1c\uc120\ubc95\\" is concise, so the translation expands it slightly for natural English flow while retaining the core meaning.)  \\n\\nIf a word-for-word translation is strictly required:  \\n**\\"A Programmer\'s Method for Code Improvement\\"**  \\n\\nLet me know if you\'d like a specific tone (e.g., technical, casual) or context!","draft":false,"keywords":["Java","Test code","Readability"],"slug":"/good-code-bad-code","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Good Code, Bad Code"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Data Analysis with Excel, R, and Python","permalink":"/en/blog/advancing-into-analytics"},"nextItem":{"title":"First Encounter with React","permalink":"/en/blog/first-met-react"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Jpub \\\\<Trusted IT Book Reviewer\\\\> activity, with the book provided by the publisher.  \\n:::\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book cover to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/good-code-bad-code.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791191600896&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: *Good Code, Bad Code*  \\n- Author: Tom Long  \\n- Translator: Gunhee Cha  \\n- Publisher: Jpub  \\n- Release Date: May 26, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\nWhen I first saw the title of this book, I reflected on whether *I\u2019m writing good code*. Back when I had to code in team projects, I only cared about finishing quickly\u2014partly because I assumed I\u2019d never look at that code again. But later, when I had to revisit my old code, I struggled with poor comments and messy logic, ending up rewriting everything from scratch. That\u2019s why I picked up this book\u2014to avoid repeating that mistake.  \\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### A Book Worth Studying with Others  \\n\\nWhat makes this book engaging is its structure: most chapters start with problematic examples or code snippets, then present solutions. It\u2019s like a guide showing both good and bad practices. Of course, these are subjective\u2014even the author notes that context matters. I\u2019d love to run a study group where we discuss not just the book\u2019s examples but also brainstorm additional scenarios with peers.  \\n\\n### Effort from Both Author and Translator  \\n\\nReading this, I felt the author had a lot to share. The book goes beyond coding practices to touch on unit testing and even introduces TDD philosophies. Honestly, the testing content isn\u2019t essential to the core message, but it adds value for those interested.  \\n\\nThe translator\u2019s work also stood out. Like in *The Programmer\u2019s Brain*, the footnotes and smooth flow showed careful consideration for readability. I hope more technical books get such dedicated translators\u2014it makes complex ideas much more accessible.  \\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\n\\nThis isn\u2019t ideal for beginners who\u2019ve just learned a language\u2019s syntax. While the pseudocode resembles Java or C#, it\u2019s best for those with experience in object-oriented languages. I\u2019d recommend it more to working engineers than job-seekers\u2014the tips are practical but might overwhelm those still mastering basics. If you collaborate on code, this book will be especially useful."},{"id":"/first-met-react","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/first-met-react","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-06-26-first-met-react/first-met-react.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-06-26-first-met-react/first-met-react.md","title":"First Encounter with React","description":"React Basics: From Core Concepts to Hands-On Practice","date":"2022-05-29T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-05-29","description":"React Basics: From Core Concepts to Hands-On Practice","draft":false,"keywords":["React","Frontend"],"slug":"/first-met-react","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"First Encounter with React"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Good Code, Bad Code","permalink":"/en/blog/good-code-bad-code"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Functional Coding That Sticks Like Glue","permalink":"/en/blog/grokking-simplicity"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post is a book review written as part of the Hanbit Media \\"I am a Reviewer\\" activity.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2022](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2022.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book cover to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/first-met-react.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162245682&orderClick=LAG&Kc=)\\n\\n- **Title**: \uc18c\ubb38\ub09c \uba85\uac15\uc758 \uc18c\ud50c\uc758 \ucc98\uc74c \ub9cc\ub09c \ub9ac\uc561\ud2b8 (*Sopl\u2019s First Meeting with React: The Famous Lecture*)  \\n- **Author**: \uc774\uc778\uc81c (Lee Inje)  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: May 31, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nAs a student who focused on backend development, I always thought, *\\"I should try frontend someday.\\"* But I never had enough time to dive deep into JavaScript. Learning backend technologies alone felt overwhelming, and when I checked out books at the store, JavaScript guides were always thick. That made me think frontend had a steep learning curve. Then I found this book, and its description said: *\\"If you\u2019ve worked with HTML and JavaScript before, you\u2019ll follow along easily. Even if you\u2019re new to web development, this book covers the basics of HTML, JavaScript, and CSS to help you start.\\"* That\u2019s why I chose it.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### A Guide for React Beginners  \\n\\nAs mentioned in the intro, the book starts with a brief overview of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. While most readers probably know these already, the recap is helpful for beginners. Then it explains what React is, how it works, and why to use it\u2014all with clear analogies and examples that made concepts easy to grasp.  \\n\\nI also used the [author\u2019s YouTube lectures](https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLo3AHtncM26y0qX58gjc_QrkYlBCzQ2R_) while studying. The videos are short and not overwhelming, which was great for a beginner like me.  \\n\\nEach chapter ends with a concise summary, letting me review what I\u2019d learned. That was a nice touch.  \\n\\nThe book wraps up with a mini project: building a simple blog. It was a good way to apply what I\u2019d learned, though I wish there were another project to reinforce the concepts further.  \\n\\n## Recommended Readers  \\n\\nI recommend this book to anyone new to React. It\u2019s also great for aspiring frontend developers. Even non-developers\u2014like planners or designers who work with developers\u2014will find it helpful."},{"id":"/grokking-simplicity","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/grokking-simplicity","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-05-08-grokking-simplicity/grokking-simplicity.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-05-08-grokking-simplicity/grokking-simplicity.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Functional Coding That Sticks Like Glue","description":"Taming Complex Software with Simple Code","date":"2022-05-08T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-05-08","description":"Taming Complex Software with Simple Code","draft":false,"keywords":["Functional programming"],"slug":"/grokking-simplicity","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Functional Coding That Sticks Like Glue"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"First Encounter with React","permalink":"/en/blog/first-met-react"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Getting Started with Domain-Driven Development","permalink":"/en/blog/start-DDD"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Jpub \\\\<Trusted IT Book Reviewer\\\\> activity, with the book provided by the publisher.  \\n:::\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobook website!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/grokking-simplicity.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791191600759&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: Grokking Simplicity: Writing Functional Code the Functional Way  \\n- Author: Eric Normand  \\n- Translator: Kim Eun-min  \\n- Publisher: Jpub  \\n- Publication Date: April 22, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nFunctional programming has been a hot topic lately. As a result, imperative languages have started incorporating functional concepts\u2014like lambda functions and generators, which are now widely used. While I was aware of this trend, my interest in functional programming stemmed from a different source. While studying data engineering, I needed to learn the *Spark* framework and the *Scala* language, which strongly supports functional programming. That\u2019s how I became curious about functional programming and decided to pick up this book.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Outstanding Examples, Detailed Explanations  \\n\\nThis book is grounded in the practical experiences of programmers who\u2019ve worked with functional programming. It uses realistic examples to demonstrate how functional programming can be applied. The structure is clear: first, it explains the problem, then walks through how to approach it functionally. It also includes thought-provoking questions and exercises, which I found particularly impressive.  \\n\\n### A Book That Inspires Architectural & Code Quality Thinking  \\n\\nI believe this book also helps in designing architectures and writing better code. The sections on improving code quality and software design reminded me of books like *Clean Code* and *Clean Architecture*. If you\u2019ve read those and want a deeper dive into functional programming, this book is a great next step.  \\n\\n### A Reader-Centric Approach  \\n\\nIt\u2019s clear the author put a lot of thought into how readers learn. The book includes a *\\"Break Time\\"* section with Q&A-style explanations for common points of confusion. It also shows how code evolves through comparisons and provides exercises to test your understanding. While it might take longer to read, the concepts stick well.  \\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\n\\nI recommend this book for those who have some prior exposure to functional programming and a basic understanding of web development. Since the examples are in JavaScript, web developers should find it especially accessible. If you\u2019ve read *Clean Code* and want to explore functional programming in more depth, this is a great follow-up."},{"id":"/start-DDD","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/start-DDD","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-04-24-start-DDD/start-DDD.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-04-24-start-DDD/start-DDD.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Getting Started with Domain-Driven Development","description":"From Core Concepts to Implementation of DDD (Domain-Driven Design)","date":"2022-04-24T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-04-24","description":"From Core Concepts to Implementation of DDD (Domain-Driven Design)","draft":false,"keywords":["Domain","Domain-Driven Development","DDD"],"slug":"/start-DDD","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Getting Started with Domain-Driven Development"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Functional Coding That Sticks Like Glue","permalink":"/en/blog/grokking-simplicity"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Deep Learning PyTorch Textbook","permalink":"/en/blog/deep-learning-pytorch-textbook"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post is part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity, written after receiving the book.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2022](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2022.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/start-DDD.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162245385&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- **Title**: Domain-Driven Development Guide for Beginners  \\n- **Author**: Beomkyun Choi  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: March 21, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\nI remember a senior once recommending *DDD Start!* by *Beomkyun Choi* as an introductory DDD book for backend studies. Unfortunately, it\u2019s now out of print and sells for exorbitant prices online, so they advised borrowing it from a library. I always meant to read it someday while studying backend development\u2014and now, Hanbit Media has released a new edition, so I finally got to dive in.\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### Prerequisites\\n\\nThe book\u2019s examples are written in Java, implemented with Spring MVC and JPA. The first half focuses heavily on concepts, making it accessible even if you\u2019re not deeply familiar with the code. However, the latter half dives into implementation details with minimal hand-holding, so I\u2019d recommend this for readers with some experience in Spring and JPA.\\n\\n### For New Developers\\n\\nThe author clarifies that this isn\u2019t a guide to becoming a DDD master but an entry-level introduction. While it\u2019s great for DDD newcomers, as a backend-aspiring student, I found it challenging\u2014especially in the later chapters, where my limited JPA knowledge made it tough to follow. Though the conceptual parts made sense, I still felt *lost* on how to apply them practically. That said, the author\u2019s clear explanations make it worth studying with some preparation.\\n\\n## Recommended Audience\\n\\nAs the author notes, readers with about 3\u20134 years of development experience should grasp the content easily. It\u2019s also a worthwhile read for Java backend-focused students or anyone interested in Spring."},{"id":"/deep-learning-pytorch-textbook","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/deep-learning-pytorch-textbook","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-04-07-deep-learning-pytorch-textbook/deep-learning-pytorch-textbook.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-04-07-deep-learning-pytorch-textbook/deep-learning-pytorch-textbook.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Deep Learning PyTorch Textbook","description":"A deep learning primer that sticks to the basics!","date":"2022-04-07T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-04-07","description":"A deep learning primer that sticks to the basics!","draft":false,"keywords":["PyTorch","Deep learning"],"slug":"/deep-learning-pytorch-textbook","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Deep Learning PyTorch Textbook"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Getting Started with Domain-Driven Development","permalink":"/en/blog/start-DDD"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Programmer\'s Brain","permalink":"/en/blog/the-programmers-brain"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the \\"17th Developer Reviewer\\" activity for Gilbut, where the book was provided by the publisher.  \\n:::\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobook website!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/deep-learning-pytorch-textbook.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791165218942&orderClick=LAG&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: \ub525\ub7ec\ub2dd \ud30c\uc774\ud1a0\uce58 \uad50\uacfc\uc11c (*Deep Learning PyTorch Textbook*)  \\n- Author: \uc11c\uc9c0\uc601 (Seo Ji-young)  \\n- Publisher: Gilbut  \\n- Publication Date: March 4, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nLately, I\u2019ve been studying PyTorch by reading books and referring to resources like the [PyTorch Tutorials](https://tutorials.pytorch.kr/) and [Introduction to Deep Learning with PyTorch](https://wikidocs.net/book/2788) whenever needed. But as I expect to use PyTorch more frequently, I wanted to systematically organize the core concepts and get comfortable with them. While those online resources are well-documented, I found it challenging to consolidate the basics neatly, which led me to pick up this book.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Textbook Quality  \\n\\nThis book truly lives up to its title. From my experience, textbooks rarely explain *everything*\u2014they focus on fundamentals and spark curiosity for deeper exploration by hinting at advanced topics. This book follows that philosophy. It lays a solid foundation while pointing readers toward what to study next.  \\n\\n### Diverse Topics  \\n\\nAt 750 pages, this book comprehensively covers *PyTorch-based deep learning basics*. It includes CNN, time-series analysis, natural language processing, and even foundational machine learning concepts before diving into deep learning. While not every topic is implemented in PyTorch, the book effectively introduces the breadth of techniques, aiding in technical awareness.  \\n\\nI particularly appreciated the **two dedicated chapters on CNNs**, which showcased the author\u2019s effort to explain them thoroughly. However, some might find the coverage of RNNs, embeddings, and generative models slightly less detailed in terms of implementation.  \\n\\n### Visuals  \\n\\nOne of the book\u2019s strongest points is its **illustrations**. Complex concepts are clarified with diagrams, and the use of **color visuals** made understanding significantly easier. The visual explanations are clean and intuitive.  \\n\\n## Recommended Readers  \\n\\nThis book is ideal for **beginners with some prior experience**\u2014those who\u2019ve tried basic implementations and now seek to solidify their PyTorch skills. If you\u2019ve built simple models from scratch, this book will smoothly transition you into the PyTorch framework.  \\n\\nIt\u2019s also great for **theory-focused learners** who struggle with practical implementation. The book\u2019s hands-on approach will bridge that gap effectively."},{"id":"/the-programmers-brain","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/the-programmers-brain","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-04-05-the-programmers-brain/the-programmers-brain.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-04-05-the-programmers-brain/the-programmers-brain.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Programmer\'s Brain","description":"Everything a Great Programmer Should Know About Cognitive Science","date":"2022-04-05T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-04-05","description":"Everything a Great Programmer Should Know About Cognitive Science","draft":false,"keywords":["Cognitive Science","Programmer","Coding"],"slug":"/the-programmers-brain","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Programmer\'s Brain"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Deep Learning PyTorch Textbook","permalink":"/en/blog/deep-learning-pytorch-textbook"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Machine Learning Using Python Libraries","permalink":"/en/blog/introduction-to-ml-with-python"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written after receiving the book as part of the Jpub \\\\<Trusted IT Book Reviewer\\\\> activity.  \\n:::\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/the-programmers-brain.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791191600650&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- **Title**: *The Programmer\u2019s Brain*  \\n- **Author**: Felienne Hermans  \\n- **Translator**: Gunhwi Cha  \\n- **Publisher**: Jpub  \\n- **Release Date**: January 12, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nThe introduction included some unfamiliar terms and cognitive science concepts, which made me hesitate at first. But I decided to read it because I thought it would be helpful. I was especially curious how the book explains the cognitive processes behind programming\u2014how our brains perceive and process code during the entire development workflow.\\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Learning  \\n\\nThis book reinforced the idea that simply reading something once or looking it up doesn\u2019t mean you truly understand it\u2014whether it\u2019s programming, a book, or any other subject. It explains how the brain processes code and how to read it more efficiently. These insights aren\u2019t just for coding; they apply to learning in general. Reflecting on my past study habits, I found this section both eye-opening and engaging.  \\n\\n### Scientific Approach  \\n\\nAs mentioned in the intro, the book bridges programming with cognitive science. Some technical terms were challenging, but the explanations were grounded in scientifically proven research, which made it fascinating. Footnotes citing studies added credibility, so I read without major reservations.  \\n\\n### Code Examples  \\n\\nI\u2019ve read other books that explain \\"good code vs. bad code\\" with examples, but this one stood out by connecting those principles to cognitive science. While it does use examples, the deeper dive into *why* certain patterns aid comprehension was particularly insightful.  \\n\\n## Recommended Readers  \\n\\nThis book explores programming through the lens of cognitive science, making it ideal for developers curious about the mental processes behind their daily work.  \\n\\nSome sections were slightly confusing for me, so I\u2019d recommend it more to those with practical coding experience\u2014though it\u2019s not a strict requirement. If you can read Java or Python and have some coding background (like a university student with moderate experience), you\u2019ll find it accessible. It\u2019s also great for anyone interested in boosting productivity, as the book offers science-backed tips for improving coding efficiency."},{"id":"/introduction-to-ml-with-python","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/introduction-to-ml-with-python","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-03-26-introduction-to-ml-with-python/introduction-to-ml-with-python.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-03-26-introduction-to-ml-with-python/introduction-to-ml-with-python.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Machine Learning Using Python Libraries","description":"A practical guide to machine learning and data science written by a core Scikit-learn developer","date":"2022-03-26T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-03-26","description":"A practical guide to machine learning and data science written by a core Scikit-learn developer","draft":false,"keywords":["Scikit-learn","Machine learning","Python"],"slug":"/introduction-to-ml-with-python","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Machine Learning Using Python Libraries"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Programmer\'s Brain","permalink":"/en/blog/the-programmers-brain"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Apache Airflow-based data pipeline","permalink":"/en/blog/data-pipelines-with-apache-airflow"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity, where I received the book for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2022](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2022.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/introduction-to-ml-with-python.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162245279&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- **Title**: Introduction to Machine Learning with Python  \\n- **Authors**: Andreas C. M\xfcller, Sarah Guido  \\n- **Translator**: Park Haesun  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: February 25, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nEven before the revised edition, this book was already one of the most famous introductory machine learning books. I had always wanted to read it someday, and now I finally had the chance!\\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Brief Introduction  \\n\\nSimply put, this is an introductory book on machine learning. However, it doesn\u2019t focus on building everything from scratch\u2014it teaches you how to use the *scikit-learn* library, which already has many implementations. This isn\u2019t a deep learning book using TensorFlow or PyTorch, but rather a foundational guide to machine learning with `sklearn`. Additionally, no special environment setup is required\u2014all code in this book can be practiced in Google Colab.\\n\\n### Translation Notes  \\n\\nThe translator for this edition is **Park Haesun**, and as expected, the translation is clean and well-structured, just like their other works. While typical footnotes might only include brief references, Park Haesun\u2019s translations often add helpful explanations to aid understanding. I strongly recommend reading the footnotes carefully\u2014they\u2019re packed with useful insights.\\n\\n### Closing Thoughts  \\n\\nChapter 8 wraps up by guiding readers on what to study next. It recommends advanced resources for those who want to dive deeper into machine learning after finishing this book. I really appreciate books that provide such directional keywords\u2014they feel thoughtful and are genuinely helpful for readers.\\n\\n### Korean Edition Appendix  \\n\\nThe Korean edition includes an appendix on natural language processing using [KoNLPy](https://konlpy.org/ko/latest/), as well as additional content the translator wanted to include. Interestingly, the original authors also did an interview specifically for Korean readers, discussing changes in scikit-learn. If you\u2019re interested in scikit-learn, this section is definitely worth reading.\\n\\n## Recommended Audience  \\n\\nThis book is ideal for undergraduate students new to machine learning. It\u2019s also a great choice for those curious about what\u2019s changed in the latest scikit-learn updates."},{"id":"/data-pipelines-with-apache-airflow","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/data-pipelines-with-apache-airflow","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-03-22-data-pipelines-with-apache-airflow/data-pipelines-with-apache-airflow.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-03-22-data-pipelines-with-apache-airflow/data-pipelines-with-apache-airflow.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Apache Airflow-based data pipeline","description":"Building and Managing Custom Components in Airflow-Centric Workflows | I\u2665Cloud Jpub\'s Cloud Series 22","date":"2022-03-22T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-03-22","description":"Building and Managing Custom Components in Airflow-Centric Workflows | I\u2665Cloud Jpub\'s Cloud Series 22","draft":false,"keywords":["Airflow","Apache","Pipeline","Data Engineering"],"slug":"/data-pipelines-with-apache-airflow","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Apache Airflow-based data pipeline"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Machine Learning Using Python Libraries","permalink":"/en/blog/introduction-to-ml-with-python"},"nextItem":{"title":"Kubeflow Operations Guide","permalink":"/en/blog/kubeflow-operations-guide"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Jpub \\\\<Trusted IT Book Reviewer\\\\> activity, with the book provided for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/data-pipelines-with-apache-airflow.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791191600681&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- **Title**: Data Pipelines with Apache Airflow  \\n- **Authors**: Bas P. Harenslak, Julian Rutger de Ruiter  \\n- **Translators**: Kim Jeongmin, Moon Sunhong  \\n- **Publisher**: Jpub  \\n- **Publication Date**: March 16, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### Structure\\n\\nThe book is divided into four main parts: *Basics*, *Intermediate*, *Practice*, and *Using Airflow in the Cloud*.  \\nThe *Basics* section covers data pipeline concepts, defining Airflow DAGs (Directed Acyclic Graphs), scheduling, and dependency management. Here, you\u2019ll work with the Taskflow API introduced in Airflow 2.x.  \\nThe *Intermediate* part teaches how to run tasks in external systems, testing, and building pipelines with containers. The use of examples to explain concepts was particularly impressive.  \\nIn *Practice*, the focus shifts to building efficient, maintainable pipelines and considerations for deploying Airflow in production. It\u2019s not just theoretical\u2014detailed explanations make this a great reference for future use.  \\n*Using Airflow in the Cloud* walks through designing architectures for deploying Airflow on AWS, Azure, and GCP. It\u2019s not just about *how*\u2014the inclusion of examples makes this section stand out.\\n\\n### Docker Environment\\n\\nAlmost every chapter includes a *docker-compose.yml* file, allowing you to run the code easily in a Docker environment. This is the book\u2019s strongest feature. I tried setting up the environment locally and also with Docker, and Docker was undeniably more convenient. If you\u2019re reading this book, definitely take advantage of the Docker setup.\\n\\n### Appendices\\n\\nThe appendices are also packed with useful information. For example, *Appendix A: Example Code Execution* briefly explains the code structure and provides commands to run examples using Docker. Even if you\u2019ve never used Docker before, this appendix makes it easy to set up the environment. *Appendix B: Airflow 2 Package Structure* compares the package differences between Airflow 1 and 2. These thoughtful additions were a nice touch.\\n\\n## Intended Audience\\n\\nAs stated in the introduction, this book is aimed at DevOps engineers, data engineers, and machine learning engineers with intermediate or advanced Python skills. If you\u2019re just starting in data engineering or lack foundational CS knowledge, it might be challenging. However, this is currently the only Korean IT book dedicated to Airflow, making it a worthwhile read if you\u2019re interested in pipelines or Airflow. While it\u2019s a bit difficult, the abundance of situational examples makes it highly recommended for anyone planning to use Airflow."},{"id":"/kubeflow-operations-guide","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/kubeflow-operations-guide","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-02-22-kubeflow-operations-guide/kubeflow-operations-guide.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-02-22-kubeflow-operations-guide/kubeflow-operations-guide.md","title":"Kubeflow Operations Guide","description":"On-premises deployment and cloud operations","date":"2022-02-22T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-02-22","description":"On-premises deployment and cloud operations","draft":false,"keywords":["Pipeline","Kubeflow","Cloud"],"slug":"/kubeflow-operations-guide","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"Kubeflow Operations Guide"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Apache Airflow-based data pipeline","permalink":"/en/blog/data-pipelines-with-apache-airflow"},"nextItem":{"title":"I worked at Amazon in the future.","permalink":"/en/blog/I-went-to-the-future-on-Amazon"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post is a book review written as part of the Hanbit Media \\\\<I am a Reviewer\\\\> activity, where the book was provided for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2022](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2022.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the **Kyobobook** site!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/kubeflow-operations-guide.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162245118&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- **Title:** Kubeflow Operations Guide  \\n- **Authors:** Josh Patterson, Michael Katzenellenbogen, Austin Harris  \\n- **Translator:** SoHyung Kim  \\n- **Publisher:** Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date:** January 31, 2022  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### Introduction\\n\\nAs MLOps has gained traction in recent years, Kubernetes has become one of the most popular technologies. Kubeflow aims to simplify and scale ML workflows on Kubernetes. After experimenting with Airflow, I became interested in Kubeflow, and this book provided a great opportunity to dive deeper.\\n\\n### Brief Overview of the Structure\\n\\nThe first three chapters cover the conceptual aspects of Kubeflow\u2014why it emerged, its architecture, and suitable environments for its use. Personally, these sections, along with Chapter 8 (on KFServing) and the appendices, were the most challenging to read.  \\n\\nChapters 4 through 7 focus on building a Kubeflow environment, including on-premises and three cloud-based setups.  \\n\\nChapter 8 introduces KFServing, a core model management component of Kubeflow. It explains the concept, benefits, and how to deploy models using KFServing.\\n\\n### Building Kubeflow in the Cloud\\n\\nThe book briefly describes GCP, AWS, and Azure services and how to set up Kubeflow in each. While helpful for those struggling with deployment, the lack of practical usage examples was disappointing. If you want to try Kubeflow after setup, I recommend following the [MNIST image classification](https://www.kubeflow.org/docs/started/kubeflow-examples/) example from the Kubeflow documentation. Note that this requires prior knowledge of cloud SDKs like AWS\u2019s boto3 or GCP\u2019s Cloud SDK, so general cloud familiarity is essential.\\n\\n### Additional Resources\\n\\nBeyond the book\u2019s content, there are many Kubeflow-related resources. Since a single book can\u2019t cover everything, the authors provide footnotes with further guidance\u2014something I found helpful for future study.\\n\\n## Target Audience\\n\\nThis book was quite challenging for me, and it made me realize why MLOps intern or entry-level positions are rare. It\u2019s a reminder to keep studying!  \\n\\nI recommend this book for engineers interested in MLOps who already have a solid understanding of Kubernetes and ML. It would be especially useful for DevOps engineers, ML engineers, and data engineers."},{"id":"/I-went-to-the-future-on-Amazon","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/I-went-to-the-future-on-Amazon","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2022-01-04-I-went-to-the-future-on-Amazon/I-went-to-the-future-on-Amazon.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2022-01-04-I-went-to-the-future-on-Amazon/I-went-to-the-future-on-Amazon.md","title":"I worked at Amazon in the future.","description":"\\"Lessons on Designing Work and Life: A Korean Who Worked at Amazon for 12 Years (vs. the Average Tenure of 1 Year) Realizes\\"  \\n\\n*(Note: The translation preserves the original\'s contrast between the average tenure and the individual\'s experience while ensuring natural English flow.)*","date":"2022-01-04T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2022-01-04","description":"\\"Lessons on Designing Work and Life: A Korean Who Worked at Amazon for 12 Years (vs. the Average Tenure of 1 Year) Realizes\\"  \\n\\n*(Note: The translation preserves the original\'s contrast between the average tenure and the individual\'s experience while ensuring natural English flow.)*","draft":false,"keywords":["Amazon","Growth","Retrospective"],"slug":"/I-went-to-the-future-on-Amazon","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"I worked at Amazon in the future."},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Kubeflow Operations Guide","permalink":"/en/blog/kubeflow-operations-guide"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Natural Language Processing with PyTorch","permalink":"/en/blog/NLP-with-PyTorch"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/I-went-to-the-future-on-Amazon.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791157843183&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: *I Went to the Future at Amazon*\\n- Author: Park Jeong-jun\\n- Publisher: Hanbit Biz\\n- Release Date: March 7, 2019\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\nI\u2019ve always wanted to read this book since its release because working at Amazon\u2014known for its high turnover rate\u2014for 12 years is rare. While browsing *Millie\u2019s Library* for something to read, I stumbled upon it and decided to give it a try.  \\n\\nThe author started as a developer at Amazon but changed departments and even job roles multiple times within the company, experiencing Amazon as a whole. Switching departments is one thing, but changing job roles is another challenge entirely\u2014it\u2019s impressive how they managed it.  \\n\\nThe book traces Amazon\u2019s growth from a small company during the author\u2019s early years to the global retail giant it is today. It also shows how the author adapted, thrived, and grew alongside the company.  \\n\\nStaying at one company for 12 years is remarkable, but the book also reveals the author\u2019s struggles and dilemmas. Amazon is notoriously tough to work at, and the author shares how they overcame difficulties by aligning with Amazon\u2019s core principles. It felt like watching a documentary about one person\u2019s journey.  \\n\\nThough some of Amazon\u2019s values didn\u2019t resonate with me, I found the book compelling enough to revisit.  \\n\\n### 6-Pager  \\n\\nAmazon doesn\u2019t use PowerPoint. Instead, they use the *6-pager*\u2014a method to convey information quickly and effectively. This made me rethink PowerPoint\u2019s limitations. Creating visually engaging slides is hard, and fitting all key points into them feels impossible. I often wondered, *\\"Does this help people understand? Can they grasp the message?\\"*  \\n\\nThe 6-pager format, however, is written in plain language on six A4 pages, designed for anyone\u2014even without prior knowledge\u2014to read and understand without extra explanation. During meetings, everyone gets a copy, reads it silently, and only then begins discussion. While challenging for presenters, I found this more effective than a PPT followed by Q&A\u2014it feels like a collaborative discussion rather than a one-way presentation.  \\n\\n## Career Transition  \\n\\nAmazon embodied the Silicon Valley and American culture I\u2019d imagined: fearless questioning, no beating around the bush\u2014it felt refreshingly different from Korea. The company also encourages internal job changes.  \\n\\nHowever, the idea of hiring top talent, fostering competition within Amazon, and rewarding based purely on merit sounded intensely challenging. While working with elite peers could be exciting, the pressure must be overwhelming. It\u2019s logical, yet daunting."},{"id":"/NLP-with-PyTorch","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/NLP-with-PyTorch","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-12-23-NLP-with-PyTorch/NLP-with-PyTorch.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-12-23-NLP-with-PyTorch/NLP-with-PyTorch.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Natural Language Processing with PyTorch","description":"Building Natural Language Processing Applications Using Deep Learning","date":"2021-12-23T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-12-23","description":"Building Natural Language Processing Applications Using Deep Learning","draft":false,"keywords":["NLP","PyTorch"],"slug":"/NLP-with-PyTorch","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Natural Language Processing with PyTorch"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"I worked at Amazon in the future.","permalink":"/en/blog/I-went-to-the-future-on-Amazon"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Computer Architecture and Programming in a Single Volume","permalink":"/en/blog/The-secret-life-of-programs"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media \\\\<I am a Reviewer\\\\> activity, where I was provided with the book.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2021](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2021.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/NLP-with-PyTorch.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162244333&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: Natural Language Processing with PyTorch  \\n- Authors: Delip Rao, Brian McMahan  \\n- Translator: Park Haesun  \\n- Publisher: Hanbit Media  \\n- Publication Date: June 1, 2021  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### Translation  \\n\\nThis is the second book I\u2019ve read translated by *Park Haesun*. The translation is always clean, and they even use *translator\u2019s notes* to inform readers when similar terms have been unified under one word, showing how meticulous the translation process was.  \\nI always find it easy to read books translated by *Park Haesun*. Their GitHub also includes translated comments in the Jupyter Notebook example codes, which is a great reference.\\n\\n### Exercises  \\n\\nThis is one of the book\u2019s shortcomings. Why are there exercises only in Chapter 1 and not in the other chapters? While solving the exercises in Chapter 1, I thought, \u201cThere must be exercises in the next chapters too,\u201d and felt this was a reader-friendly book. This aspect was disappointing.\\n\\n### Pororo  \\n\\nSince this is a translated book, all content is based on English. To handle Korean, personal research by the reader seems necessary. However, *Park Haesun* must have felt this was a drawback, as they introduce *Pororo* (Platform Of neuRal mOdels for natuRal language prOcessing), a natural language processing library released by Kakao Brain, in the appendix. I had only heard about it before, but this was a great opportunity to try it out directly, and it was very helpful.\\n\\n### First Study  \\n\\nI had studied NLP superficially before but never properly. This book gave me the chance to study it thoroughly, and I realized how fascinating the field of NLP is. When I start learning a new field, the most important thing for me is whether it\u2019s *fun*. This book meets that criterion. The authors seem eager to include diverse knowledge, starting from the basics and explaining them thoroughly. It feels like building from the ground up, starting with the simplest neural network, the *perceptron*, and implementing it with PyTorch. The wide range of content made my entry into NLP enjoyable.\\n\\n## Target Audience  \\n\\nAlthough I mentioned that beginners can easily start with this book, that\u2019s not entirely true. I recommend this book to those who already have some machine learning knowledge. The book briefly explains PyTorch basics, but that\u2019s not enough. While these gaps can be filled by referring to official documentation, I still suggest that readers have a basic understanding of machine learning. For example, those who have taken a machine learning course, implemented neural networks from scratch using NumPy, or studied with scikit-learn would benefit greatly. If you have such experience, this is an excellent book to start with NLP."},{"id":"/The-secret-life-of-programs","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/The-secret-life-of-programs","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-12-04-The-secret-life-of-programs/The-secret-life-of-programs.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-12-04-The-secret-life-of-programs/The-secret-life-of-programs.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Computer Architecture and Programming in a Single Volume","description":"Better Software Development Through Hardware | Data Structures, Essential Algorithms, and the Programmer\u2019s Secret Notes","date":"2021-12-04T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-12-04","description":"Better Software Development Through Hardware | Data Structures, Essential Algorithms, and the Programmer\u2019s Secret Notes","draft":false,"keywords":["Computer Architecture","Computer Engineering","Hardware"],"slug":"/The-secret-life-of-programs","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Computer Architecture and Programming in a Single Volume"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Natural Language Processing with PyTorch","permalink":"/en/blog/NLP-with-PyTorch"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Designing a Living, Breathing Machine Learning Pipeline","permalink":"/en/blog/building-machine-learning-pipelines"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/The-secret-life-of-programs.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791189909284&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: *The Secret Life of Programs: Understanding Computers from the Inside Out*\\n- Author: Jonathan E. Steinhart\\n- Translator: Hyun-Seok Oh\\n- Publisher: Book Only\\n- Publication Date: April 8, 2021\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\nAs the title suggests (*The Secret Life of Programs: Understanding Computers from the Inside Out*), the author clearly tried to pack as much knowledge as possible into a single volume. This could be seen as both a strength and a weakness.\\n\\nThe **advantage** is the sheer breadth of knowledge covered. The book spans 636 pages and feels like it bridges both computer engineering (CE) and electrical engineering (EE). Even as a current computer engineering major, I encountered many concepts I hadn\u2019t known before. In other words, it includes topics that modern computer engineering curricula often skip. Additionally, professors sometimes share historical anecdotes or fascinating insights during lectures\u2014this book includes many of those kinds of details.\\n\\nThe **disadvantage** is the book\u2019s thickness, making it impractical to carry around. It\u2019s genuinely heavy\u2014I\u2019d definitely want to split it into parts if I read it again. Also, the reading process felt quite tedious. Although the author explains concepts as simply as possible, I struggled to make progress even when reading just one or two pages daily. Despite considering myself a fast reader, this book took unexpectedly long to finish.\\n\\nBefore reading, having a basic understanding of the web would help. Chapter 9 suddenly dives into web-related topics with JavaScript code that caught me off guard since I wasn\u2019t familiar with it.\\n\\n## Intended Audience\\n\\nI wouldn\u2019t recommend this book to computer engineering freshmen or non-majors. While it\u2019s a bestseller in many bookstores, it\u2019s definitely not an easy read for beginners.\\n\\nPersonally, I see this as a great review book for engineering students. It would benefit not only computer engineering (CE) majors but also those with a background in computer science (CS) or electrical engineering (EE) who have studied foundational CS courses. It covers fun, often overlooked topics\u2014like the CORDIC algorithm, which some universities don\u2019t teach in numerical analysis. Refreshing these concepts was incredibly helpful for me."},{"id":"/building-machine-learning-pipelines","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/building-machine-learning-pipelines","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-11-20-building-machine-learning-pipelines/building-machine-learning-pipelines.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-11-20-building-machine-learning-pipelines/building-machine-learning-pipelines.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Designing a Living, Breathing Machine Learning Pipeline","description":"Automating Machine Learning Projects with TensorFlow","date":"2021-11-20T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-11-20","description":"Automating Machine Learning Projects with TensorFlow","draft":false,"keywords":["Machine learning","Pipeline","Data Engineering"],"slug":"/building-machine-learning-pipelines","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Designing a Living, Breathing Machine Learning Pipeline"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Computer Architecture and Programming in a Single Volume","permalink":"/en/blog/The-secret-life-of-programs"},"nextItem":{"title":"A Developer\'s Guide to Writing","permalink":"/en/blog/developer-writing"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post was written as part of the Hanbit Media \\\\<I am a Reviewer\\\\> activity, where I was provided with the book for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2021](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2021.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the [Kyobobook](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr) site!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/building-machine-learning-pipelines.jpg)](https://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162244814&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- **Title**: *Designing Machine Learning Pipelines That Scale*  \\n- **Authors**: Hannes Hapke, Catherine Nelson  \\n- **Translated by**: Ho-Yeon Song  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: October 11, 2021  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Book Overview\\n\\n### Prerequisites: ML & Cloud Knowledge\\n\\nBefore diving into designing machine learning pipelines, you\u2019ll need foundational ML knowledge. Consider whether you\u2019re comfortable reading TensorFlow and Keras code before starting this book. Proficiency in Python is also essential! If you\u2019re considering this book, I assume you already meet these criteria.  \\n\\nWhile not strictly required, prior experience with cloud platforms will make this book more accessible. Familiarity with **GCP (Google Cloud Platform)** or **AWS (Amazon Web Services)**\u2014even just basic usage\u2014will help, as the book discusses optimizing pipelines with cloud services.  \\n\\n### Key Content Summary\\n\\nThis book guides you through designing pipelines using **TensorFlow Extended (TFX)**, covering the full workflow:  \\n**Data Collection \u2192 Data Validation \u2192 Data Preprocessing \u2192 Model Training \u2192 Model Analysis & Validation \u2192 Model Deployment**.  \\n\\nThe entire process leverages the TensorFlow ecosystem. Since the official TFX documentation is well-translated, referring to it alongside the book will enhance your understanding!  \\n\\nThe final chapters explore orchestration tools for pipeline execution. While I found the pipeline design sections engaging, I particularly enjoyed the discussion of three orchestration tools: **Apache Beam, Apache Airflow, and Kubeflow**. Having only heard about these in the community, this book gave me a practical opportunity to explore them.  \\n\\n### Appendix Highlights\\n\\nThe appendix introduces **Docker** and **Kubernetes**\u2014essential infrastructure tools for ML\u2014and walks you through setting up a Kubernetes cluster on Google Cloud. Even if you\u2019re new to these technologies, the appendix provides a hands-on introduction.  \\n\\n## Recommended Audience\\n\\nThis book is ideal for:  \\n- **ML Engineers** familiar with frameworks like TensorFlow/Keras who want to design scalable pipelines. While the examples use TensorFlow, the core concepts apply to other frameworks.  \\n- **ML Enthusiasts** interested in the TensorFlow ecosystem.  \\n- **DevOps Engineers** exploring **MLOps** and looking to understand pipeline orchestration.  \\n\\nWhether you\u2019re building production-ready systems or curious about end-to-end ML workflows, this book offers valuable insights."},{"id":"/developer-writing","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/developer-writing","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-11-05-developer-writing/developer-writing.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-11-05-developer-writing/developer-writing.md","title":"A Developer\'s Guide to Writing","description":"From Variable Naming to Release Notes, Incident Reports, and Technical Blogs! | End Your Programming Writing Woes!","date":"2021-11-05T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-11-05","description":"From Variable Naming to Release Notes, Incident Reports, and Technical Blogs! | End Your Programming Writing Woes!","draft":false,"keywords":["Developer","Writing","Technical Document  \\n\\n(Note: Since the input was only \\"\uae30\uc220 \ubb38\uc11c\\" which directly translates to \\"Technical Document,\\" the output is a simple translation. If you need a more detailed or context-specific translation, please provide additional text or clarify the request.)  \\n\\n*Returning only the translation as requested*","Blog"],"slug":"/developer-writing","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"A Developer\'s Guide to Writing"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Designing a Living, Breathing Machine Learning Pipeline","permalink":"/en/blog/building-machine-learning-pipelines"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Kubernetes/Docker for building a container infrastructure environment","permalink":"/en/blog/k8s-and-docker-for-container-infrastructure"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook website!\\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/developer-writing.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791158391744&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: Developer\u2019s Writing\\n- Author: Kim Cheol-su\\n- Publisher: WikiBooks\\n- Published: 2019-10-04\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\nThe book explains various scenarios with detailed code examples, making it easy to understand. Most sections include examples or case studies, which made reading this book quite smooth from a reader\u2019s perspective.\\n\\nThe title *Developer\u2019s Writing* made me curious about what kind of \\"writing\\" the book would cover\u2014and after reading it, I found out. Here, \\"writing\\" doesn\u2019t refer to general business writing but specifically to writing *for developers*. It explains how to write the kinds of texts and sentences needed during development. The book helps you approach challenging aspects like variable naming, comments, and error messages more comfortably\u2014topics developers often struggle with.\\n\\n### Writing from the Reader\u2019s Perspective\\n\\nThe book emphasizes that a developer\u2019s perspective and a reader\u2019s perspective are different. Therefore, the writing style should vary depending on who the audience is, and you should consider what the reader cares about. While this seems obvious, it made me reflect: *Have I really considered my audience when writing?* It\u2019s a question worth pondering.\\n\\n## Helpful Content\\n\\n### Korean Grammar\\n\\nThese days, many people on social media or blogs don\u2019t pay attention to spelling or grammar rules unless it\u2019s a formal setting. Even in informal contexts, strict adherence can make writing seem stiff, so I don\u2019t always follow them perfectly\u2014except when blogging. Still, I sometimes get confused about correct usage. The book clarifies common grammar pitfalls, such as when to use double or single quotation marks and how to transcribe foreign words.\\n\\n> \\"Double quotation marks are used for direct dialogue or quotations in writing. Single quotation marks are used for quotes within quotes or for internal monologue.\\"\\n\\n### English Words with Multiple Meanings\\n\\nWhen writing commit messages, I often use *change* and *modify*. I\u2019ve sometimes wondered how to use *revise* correctly, and this book helped clarify that too.\\n\\n> \\"Use *change* for simple modifications, *modify* for correcting errors, and *revise* when adding new information or ideas that clearly alter the original content.\\"\\n\\n### Code Naming Conventions\\n\\n> \\"Code naming conventions exist to make code readable and to facilitate communication among developers. A good way to create abbreviations is to prioritize universality\u2014place important words first.\\"\\n\\n### Technical Blogging\\n\\n> \\"Don\u2019t just start writing blindly. First, think thoroughly, define your topic, establish a clear purpose, then gather materials and ideas needed for writing.\\"\\n\\n### Miscellaneous\\n\\nThere were many other helpful sections, but I omitted those not immediately relevant to me.\\n\\n## Target Audience\\n\\nI read this book because I run a technical blog and wanted to improve my writing from a developer\u2019s perspective. While many parts were helpful, others weren\u2019t\u2014especially since the book isn\u2019t focused on technical blogging. If you\u2019re interested in writing technical blogs, I recommend reading only the sections that apply to you. The book also includes content related to work, so it may not be suitable for students or those not yet in the industry.\\n\\nI would recommend this book to anyone who needs to write development-related documents in their current job\u2014such as incident reports, release notes, or proposals. \\n\\nAs someone without industry experience, I\u2019m not sure how much documentation developers actually write. However, from reading some new developers\u2019 reflections, it seems documentation tasks can sometimes outweigh actual coding. If your company has a strong documentation culture, you might not need this book\u2014those guidelines would suffice. But if not, this book could be a valuable reference."},{"id":"/k8s-and-docker-for-container-infrastructure","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/k8s-and-docker-for-container-infrastructure","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-10-30-k8s-and-docker-for-container-infrastructure/k8s-and-docker-for-container-infrastructure.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-10-30-k8s-and-docker-for-container-infrastructure/k8s-and-docker-for-container-infrastructure.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Kubernetes/Docker for building a container infrastructure environment","description":"Let\'s understand and build a container infrastructure environment!","date":"2021-10-30T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-10-30","description":"Let\'s understand and build a container infrastructure environment!","draft":false,"keywords":["Docker","Kubernetes","k8s"],"slug":"/k8s-and-docker-for-container-infrastructure","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Kubernetes/Docker for building a container infrastructure environment"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"A Developer\'s Guide to Writing","permalink":"/en/blog/developer-writing"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Learning Mathematical Optimization Properly","permalink":"/en/blog/mathematical-optimization"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written after receiving the book as part of the *Gilbut 16th Developer Reviewer* program.  \\n:::\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/k8s-and-docker-for-container-infrastructure.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791165215743&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: Kubernetes/Docker for Container Infrastructure Setup  \\n- Authors: Jo Hoon, Shim Geun-woo, Moon Sung-joo  \\n- Publisher: Gilbut  \\n- Publication Date: June 7, 2021  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### Detailed Explanations with Images  \\n\\nWhile not fully in color, the book provides thorough explanations with images. Most technical books assume readers are developers and skip installation steps, but this one includes detailed visual guides for those processes. It also explains troubleshooting scenarios with text and images, making it very reader-friendly.  \\n\\n*Gilbut*\u2019s books often include a page with author/translator introductions and the phrase, *\\"Experience the dedication that saves you 1 second!\\"* Honestly, that slogan didn\u2019t resonate much, but the follow-up line\u2014*\\"No matter how fast the world moves, books can\u2019t be rushed.\\"*\u2014did. As the authors note, IT evolves rapidly, but that doesn\u2019t mean books should be hastily produced.  \\n\\n### Tools for Hands-On Practice  \\n\\nBeyond Kubernetes and Docker, the book introduces tools like *Oracle VM VirtualBox* for virtual machines and *Vagrant* for provisioning. It also covers *Jenkins* for CI/CD, *Prometheus* for monitoring, and *Grafana* for visualization. Since I\u2019ve been interested in DevOps, this book gave me a practical overview of the entire workflow.  \\n\\n### Version Considerations  \\n\\nI recommend sticking to the versions specified in the book. I wasted time trying the latest versions, but realized that unless you\u2019re immediately joining a cutting-edge project (which is rare), following the book\u2019s setup is more efficient. If you\u2019re confident in customizing OS configurations, you can deviate, but otherwise, the book\u2019s examples are safer.  \\n\\n### Areas for Improvement  \\n\\nThe virtual machine images required a lot of RAM, which was challenging on my 8GB laptop. Including minimum system requirements would have been helpful.  \\n\\nThe authors pre-configured OS images available on *Vagrant Cloud*, which was convenient, but I wish the book explained how to customize those images. While Vagrant Cloud notes changes made to each version, I thought, *\\"Wouldn\u2019t it be better if this was in the book?\\"* Since the focus is on Kubernetes and Docker, Linux setup details were likely omitted.  \\n\\n### Recommended Readers  \\n\\nThis isn\u2019t a beginner-friendly book. It assumes familiarity with UNIX commands, operating systems, and shell scripting. Basic knowledge of Kubernetes and Docker is also recommended. However, if you\u2019re interested in container infrastructure and want to build hands-on experience, this is a great resource."},{"id":"/mathematical-optimization","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/mathematical-optimization","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-10-21-mathematical-optimization/mathematical-optimization.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-10-21-mathematical-optimization/mathematical-optimization.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Learning Mathematical Optimization Properly","description":"From optimization modeling to algorithms","date":"2021-10-21T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-10-21","description":"From optimization modeling to algorithms","draft":false,"keywords":["optimization"],"slug":"/mathematical-optimization","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Learning Mathematical Optimization Properly"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Kubernetes/Docker for building a container infrastructure environment","permalink":"/en/blog/k8s-and-docker-for-container-infrastructure"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Park Mijeong\'s Introduction to Git & GitHub","permalink":"/en/blog/Git-GitHub-introduction"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post is a book review written as part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity, where I was provided with the book.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2021](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2021.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/mathematical-optimization.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162244661&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- **Title**: Mathematical Optimization: A Comprehensive Approach  \\n- **Author**: Shunji Umetani (Umetani Shunji)  \\n- **Translator**: Moses Kim  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: September 30, 2021  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### A Book Requiring Mathematical Knowledge\\n\\nAs the title suggests, studying optimization theory requires prerequisite knowledge. An optimization problem, simply put, involves finding a solution that optimizes (maximizes or minimizes) the result of an objective function. While it might seem like just a math problem, it\'s widely used in machine learning and deep learning\u2014for example, gradient descent and convex optimization. Since it involves various mathematical concepts and algorithms, prerequisites like linear algebra, fundamental algorithms, data structures, and calculus are essential.  \\n\\nI thought I was prepared to read this book, but I was wrong. Even with prior knowledge, I struggled. At first glance, I thought it resembled numerical analysis and assumed it wouldn\u2019t be too difficult. That was a big mistake.  \\n\\n### Practical Examples for Optimization\\n\\nRather than just explaining mathematical concepts, this book teaches the mindset of mathematical optimization by providing examples of how to approach optimization problems. I think this is the book\u2019s greatest strength. Knowing countless theories is useless if you can\u2019t understand or apply them. The concrete examples make the content easier to grasp.  \\n\\n### Exercises and References\\n\\nI believe math books should include exercises to help retain concepts. This book does that well, and unlike many others, it provides detailed solutions in the appendix. You can solve the problems first and then compare your answers with the explanations.  \\n\\nEach chapter also includes recommended references for further study. The sheer number of references suggests the book\u2019s broad scope. However, most are Japanese books, which might feel overwhelming. Fortunately, some English references are included, and I plan to explore those if I need deeper insights later.  \\n\\n## Intended Audience\\n\\nFirst, I recommend this book to **those interested in optimization theory**. If you\u2019re not genuinely curious, I wouldn\u2019t suggest picking it up just because it relates to machine learning or deep learning. For computer science undergraduates, I\u2019d advise waiting until you\u2019ve taken machine learning courses in your senior year and studied optimization with other introductory materials first.  \\n\\nThis book is ideal for **readers seeking a foundational understanding of optimization**. It serves as an introductory guide. For more advanced study, I recommend combining it with the reference books listed in the text."},{"id":"/Git-GitHub-introduction","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Git-GitHub-introduction","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-10-08-Git-GitHub-introduction/Git-GitHub-introduction.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-10-08-Git-GitHub-introduction/Git-GitHub-introduction.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Park Mijeong\'s Introduction to Git & GitHub","description":"Must Have | Git & GitHub Drills: Mastering Collaboration Scenarios Through Repetitive Practice","date":"2021-10-08T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-10-08","description":"Must Have | Git & GitHub Drills: Mastering Collaboration Scenarios Through Repetitive Practice","draft":false,"keywords":["Git","GitHub","Collaboration","Must Have"],"slug":"/Git-GitHub-introduction","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Park Mijeong\'s Introduction to Git & GitHub"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Learning Mathematical Optimization Properly","permalink":"/en/blog/mathematical-optimization"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Python machine learning pandas data analysis","permalink":"/en/blog/pandas-data-analysis"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post was written after receiving the book from Golden Rabbit Publishing.  \\n:::\\n\\n## \u2139\ufe0fBook Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook website!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/Git-GitHub-introduction.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791191905014&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: **Park Mijung\u2019s Introduction to Git & GitHub**  \\n- Author: **\ubc15\ubbf8\uc815 (Park Mijung)**  \\n- Publisher: **Golden Rabbit**  \\n- Release Date: **September 13, 2021**  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## \ud83c\udfacIntro  \\n\\nThe author of this book is one of the admins of the Facebook group **[Early \ub610\ub77c\uc774 (Early Ddorai)](https://www.facebook.com/groups/earlyddorai/about)** and is currently working at Musinsa after previously being at Baemin Vietnam. I consider her one of the developers from whom I\u2019ve learned a lot. If you get the chance, I recommend watching her **[Monthly Code Review ver_0.1: Career Growth CODE](https://taling.me/vod/view/39222)** on Taling, where she presents on the topic of **\\"The Art of Sharing for Growing Developers.\\"**  \\n\\nWhen the book was recruiting beta readers before publication, I applied out of personal fandom but didn\u2019t make the cut. However, after its release, Golden Rabbit Publishing recruited **\\"Book Spoilers\\"**\u2014people who honestly review books to help readers choose wisely\u2014and I got selected. This time, my motivation wasn\u2019t just fandom; I genuinely wanted to become someone who can collaborate effectively using Git. Although I had taken an open-source class in college and could handle basic Git functions like `commit` and `push`, I wanted to become proficient in collaboration workflows like `branch` switching, `merge`, and `pull request`.  \\n\\nGolden Rabbit\u2019s **\\"Book Spoiler\\"** program is a great way to share honest reviews and help others pick good books. They usually recruit through their Facebook page or email, so if a topic interests you, I recommend applying.  \\n\\n## \ud83d\udcd6Book Review  \\n\\n### Scenario-Based Learning  \\n\\nThis book has a fun and unique feature: **scenarios**. These are like scripts that let you experience real-world project workflows based on what you\u2019ve learned. There are two scenarios, and they\u2019re not just simple exercises\u2014they mimic actual situations you\u2019d encounter in the field. The use of **Node.js** and **Express** stood out to me. Unlike other books that might just have you edit Markdown files, this one felt more authentic.  \\n\\n> While editing `.md` files can demonstrate GitHub issues and project boards, there\u2019s a limit to how much real-world code integration they can show.  \\n\\n### Deployment & Automation  \\n\\nAs mentioned earlier, while other books or courses might use simple file edits for Git/GitHub exercises, this one uses a **Node.js** setup. I suspect this was also to introduce **GitHub Actions**. Most books don\u2019t cover GitHub Actions in depth, so this was a refreshing touch.  \\n\\nThe book briefly explains how to use GitHub Actions and set up **automated deployments to AWS ECS** and **Azure Web App Service**. It doesn\u2019t go into deep technical details\u2014just gives you a sense of what\u2019s possible. Since the book\u2019s focus isn\u2019t on cloud platforms, the coverage is appropriately light.  \\n\\n### Using VSCode Features  \\n\\nI used to find typing Git commands in the CLI (Command-Line Interface) tedious. When I first started, I thought, *\\"Do I really need to memorize all these commands?\\"* So I used GUI tools like **Sourcetree**, **GitHub Desktop**, or **TortoiseGit**. (Though I ended up memorizing the common ones anyway... \ud83e\udd26\u200d\u2642\ufe0f)  \\n\\nNow, I\u2019m a big fan of **VSCode**. While this book focuses on learning Git through direct command-line practice, the appendix includes a guide to using Git features like `commit` and `push` within VSCode. I wish I\u2019d known about this shortcut earlier\u2014it\u2019s one of the perks of learning from a well-structured book. That said, CLI familiarity is still valuable for any developer, so I hope this book gives you a chance to practice both.  \\n\\n### Easy-to-Understand Explanations  \\n\\nI first learned Git through **[Opentutorials (\uc0dd\ud65c\ucf54\ub529)](https://opentutorials.org/course/3838)** and **[Pro Git](https://git-scm.com/book/ko/v2)**, and studied GitHub by piecing together online resources. I tried learning Git from books twice before and gave up because concepts like **tracked vs. staged** were confusing. This book avoids that problem with clear, easy explanations.  \\n\\nThe author and editor also clearly care about the reader\u2014you can see this in details like **[Thoughts Become Books: Park Mijung\u2019s Git & GitHub](https://brunch.co.kr/@hwchoi/32)**. If you want a clean, reader-friendly Git/GitHub guide, this is it.  \\n\\n## \ud83e\uddd1\u200d\ud83c\udfebTarget Audience  \\n\\nGit and GitHub have become essential skills for any developer. While technology evolves, GitHub remains a key platform for sharing code and knowledge\u2014like a social media for developers. The earlier you learn it, the better.  \\n\\nThe biggest strength of this book is that it\u2019s both an **introductory guide** and a **collaboration simulator**. It skips advanced topics like **[submodules](https://git-scm.com/book/ko/v2/Git-%EB%8F%84%EA%B5%AC-%EC%84%9C%EB%B8%8C%EB%AA%A8%EB%93%88)** and focuses on practical, frequently used workflows. If you\u2019re new to Git and GitHub, this is a great starting point."},{"id":"/pandas-data-analysis","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/pandas-data-analysis","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-09-27-pandas-data-analysis/pandas-data-analysis.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-09-27-pandas-data-analysis/pandas-data-analysis.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Python machine learning pandas data analysis","description":"The provided Korean text appears to be empty or incomplete (only a period is present). Could you please provide the actual text you\'d like translated? I\'d be happy to help once you share the content.  \\n\\n(Note: Since the input was only a period, no translation is possible. Returning only the translation as requested would mean returning an empty response.)  \\n\\nIf this was intentional, the \\"translation\\" would be:  \\n\\".\\"","date":"2021-09-27T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-09-27","description":"The provided Korean text appears to be empty or incomplete (only a period is present). Could you please provide the actual text you\'d like translated? I\'d be happy to help once you share the content.  \\n\\n(Note: Since the input was only a period, no translation is possible. Returning only the translation as requested would mean returning an empty response.)  \\n\\nIf this was intentional, the \\"translation\\" would be:  \\n\\".\\"","draft":false,"keywords":["pandas","Machine Learning","Data Analysis"],"slug":"/pandas-data-analysis","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Python machine learning pandas data analysis"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Park Mijeong\'s Introduction to Git & GitHub","permalink":"/en/blog/Git-GitHub-introduction"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Deep learning blossoms where fastai meets PyTorch","permalink":"/en/blog/fastai-and-pytorch"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/pandas-data-analysis.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9788956748337&orderClick=LAG&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: Python Machine Learning Pandas Data Analysis\\n- Author: Seung-Hwan Oh\\n- Publisher: Jeongbo Publishing\\n- Publication Date: June 15, 2019\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### Why High Sales?\\n\\nI usually check sales rankings when choosing books. While Kyobobook listed other books higher in sales, on YES24 it ranked first for \\"pandas\\" searches with a sales index of 10,524. Jeongbo Publishing is only my second book from them, but the high sales made me curious. \\n\\nI\u2019ve always studied pandas by checking official docs or YouTube lectures when needed. Since my learning was fragmented, I wanted a structured book study. This one covered pandas, matplotlib, seaborn, and more\u2014so I picked it. Other great books like *Data Science School* and *Python for Data Analysis* are also on my reading list.\\n\\n### Plenty of Examples\\n\\nThe book has many examples, making it beginner-friendly. My only regret was that the code wasn\u2019t formatted for Jupyter Notebook\u2014it used standard Python files. While it works, step-by-step Jupyter-style examples might have been more intuitive.\\n\\n### Visualization Libraries\\n\\nI enjoyed revisiting matplotlib and seaborn, and the Folium map visualizations were a fun bonus. The book shows how to apply these tools during analysis and model building.\\n\\n### Machine Learning Preview\\n\\nThe ML model-building section effectively demonstrated pandas and visualization libraries in action. However, advanced algorithms like KNN/SVM lacked detailed explanations. Simplifying the ML part with easier algorithms would have made it more accessible for beginners.\\n\\n## Recommended Audience\\n\\nIdeal for those who know Python but feel overwhelmed about starting data analysis. At 392 pages, it\u2019s less daunting than other data analysis books. While not exclusively about pandas, it\u2019s great for hands-on learners. For focused pandas study, try the [10-Minute Pandas Tutorial](https://dataitgirls2.github.io/10minutes2pandas/)."},{"id":"/fastai-and-pytorch","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/fastai-and-pytorch","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-09-19-fastai-and-pytorch/fastai-and-pytorch.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-09-19-fastai-and-pytorch/fastai-and-pytorch.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Deep learning blossoms where fastai meets PyTorch","description":"How to Implement AI Stylishly Without a PhD","date":"2021-09-19T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-09-19","description":"How to Implement AI Stylishly Without a PhD","draft":false,"keywords":["PyTorch","fastai","Deep learning"],"slug":"/fastai-and-pytorch","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Deep learning blossoms where fastai meets PyTorch"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Python machine learning pandas data analysis","permalink":"/en/blog/pandas-data-analysis"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Clean Python, Robust Backend","permalink":"/en/blog/python-backend-flask"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post is a book review written as part of the Hanbit Media \\"I am a Reviewer\\" activity, where I received the book for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2021](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2021.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store page!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/fastai-and-pytorch.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162244630&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: *Deep Learning for Coders with Fastai and PyTorch*  \\n- Authors: Jeremy Howard, Sylvain Gugger  \\n- Translators: Chansung Park, Jieun Kim  \\n- Publisher: Hanbit Media  \\n- Release Date: August 10, 2021  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### Full-Color Printing\\n\\nAs you\u2019ll see in other reviews, this book is in full color. It might seem minor, but encountering translated technical books in full color always feels refreshing. Additionally, the publisher deserves credit for printing such a thick 720-page book in full color. It made the visual experience much more comfortable.\\n\\n### TIP Sections\\n\\nAlongside the two main authors, Alexis Gallagher provides **TIP** sections aimed at readers with limited math/engineering backgrounds or minimal coding experience. These feel like mentorship moments from experts in each field\u2014very helpful!\\n\\n### Top-Down Approach\\n\\nUnlike typical ML/DL books that build from the ground up, this one takes a **top-down (\ud558\ud5a5\uc2dd)** approach. If you\u2019re familiar with DL, this style will feel intuitive. However, the initial chapters focus on *using* models rather than *understanding* them deeply. The goal here is to spark interest first; technical details follow later.\\n\\n### Development Environment\\n\\nThe book uses **Jupyter Notebooks**, but doesn\u2019t cover setup details. You\u2019ll need to configure your environment independently. Since my GPU isn\u2019t powerful, I used Google\u2019s [Colab](https://colab.research.google.com/). Even with Colab Pro, though, I\u2019m unsure why my runtime was slower than the authors\u2019 examples.  \\n\\nFor those with limited hardware, the [fast.ai course](https://course.fast.ai/start_colab) explains how to use Colab effectively\u2014definitely worth checking out.\\n\\n### Questionnaires\\n\\nEach chapter ends with a **questionnaire**, which I found uniquely helpful. You can:  \\n- Read them *before* a chapter to focus your study.  \\n- Use them *after* to test your understanding.  \\n\\nMost answers are solvable if you\u2019ve read carefully, but if stuck, solutions are available on the [fast.ai forum](https://forums.fast.ai/t/fastbook-questionnaire-solutions-megathread/76955). I plan to share my own answers on my blog someday!\\n\\n## Recommended Audience\\n\\nThe book targets readers with:  \\n- At least 1 year of coding experience  \\n- High school-level math  \\n\\nHowever, I recommend having **Python, PyTorch, and basic DL knowledge** beforehand for smoother reading.  \\n\\nIn my experience, DL is challenging due to its *overload of concepts and prerequisites*. Even with detailed explanations, encountering too many new ideas at once can be overwhelming. If your foundational knowledge is shaky, progress slowly and revisit confusing sections. This isn\u2019t a race\u2014take your time!"},{"id":"/python-backend-flask","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/python-backend-flask","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-08-23-python-backend-flask/python-backend-flask.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-08-23-python-backend-flask/python-backend-flask.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Clean Python, Robust Backend","description":"\\"Python for Backend Developers: Like You\'ve Never Seen It Before\\"  \\n\\n*(Note: The translation captures the essence of the original Korean phrase, which emphasizes a novel or unprecedented approach to Python for backend development. The wording is adjusted for natural English flow while preserving the promotional tone.)*  \\n\\nIf a more literal translation is preferred:  \\n**\\"Python for Backend Developers That Has Never Existed Before\\"**  \\n\\n*(Choose based on whether emphasis should be on creativity or directness.)*","date":"2021-08-23T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-08-23","description":"\\"Python for Backend Developers: Like You\'ve Never Seen It Before\\"  \\n\\n*(Note: The translation captures the essence of the original Korean phrase, which emphasizes a novel or unprecedented approach to Python for backend development. The wording is adjusted for natural English flow while preserving the promotional tone.)*  \\n\\nIf a more literal translation is preferred:  \\n**\\"Python for Backend Developers That Has Never Existed Before\\"**  \\n\\n*(Choose based on whether emphasis should be on creativity or directness.)*","draft":false,"keywords":["Backend","Flask","Python","API"],"slug":"/python-backend-flask","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Clean Python, Robust Backend"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Deep learning blossoms where fastai meets PyTorch","permalink":"/en/blog/fastai-and-pytorch"},"nextItem":{"title":"Python for Coding Tests","permalink":"/en/blog/coding-test-with-python"}},"content":"## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/python-backend.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791186697757&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: Clean Python, Solid Backend\\n- Author: Eunwoo Song\\n- Publisher: BJ Public\\n- Release Date: 2019-01-25\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## \ud83c\udfac Intro\\n\\nThis book guides you through building APIs with Flask. Recently, a great book called [Do it! Jump to Flask](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791163031970&orderClick=LEa&Kc=) was released. Still, I chose this one because I wanted to study API development\u2014not just Flask. Especially using the REST architectural pattern, which is almost essential for backend development.\\n\\nThis is one of the most recently published books that combines Flask and REST API. Other options were older or lacked reviews, so I didn\u2019t hesitate to buy it. In Korea, Java Spring seems more popular for backend development than Python, so there aren\u2019t many Python backend books. As someone who loves Python, I hope more Python backend books will be published.\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### API Development\\n\\nThe book walks you through building a mini Twitter by implementing some of its core features. While creating this API, you\u2019ll experience backend development concepts like HTTP, databases, unit tests, and AWS deployment. It\u2019s helpful for overall backend learning but not for deepening Flask-specific knowledge.\\n\\nI enjoyed revisiting HTTP concepts and handling authentication. There were also sections on architecture that surprised me with how practical they were\u2014like, \u201cWhoa, they even cover this?\u201d\\n\\n### Keyword Suggestions\\n\\nI prefer books that suggest topics for further study, even in appendices. Simple keywords let me research online or find related resources. This book did that well, which I appreciated.\\n\\n### Legacy Code\\n\\nPublished in early 2019, some outdated code was expected by mid-2021. I thought, \u201cSurely not *too* many issues,\u201d and fortunately, aside from a [decode error](https://teddygood.github.io/python/AttributeError-str-decode/), I didn\u2019t struggle to run the code.\\n\\n### Omitted Code\\n\\nThe book covers many topics, so some implementation details are skipped. While this was a bit disappointing, I understand\u2014if every step were detailed, the book might have been 500\u2013600 pages instead of 400. The author\u2019s choice makes sense.\\n\\n## Target Audience\\n\\nI recommend this to anyone who wants to explore backend development with Python. Before, I\u2019d struggle to learn about roles I hadn\u2019t experienced firsthand, but this book made it accessible. Personally, I\u2019d love more project-based books that cover the entire backend stack."},{"id":"/coding-test-with-python","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/coding-test-with-python","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-08-21-coding-test-with-python/coding-test-with-python.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-08-21-coding-test-with-python/coding-test-with-python.md","title":"Python for Coding Tests","description":"The Ultimate Guide to Algorithm Interviews for Securing Jobs and Career Transitions","date":"2021-08-21T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-08-21","description":"The Ultimate Guide to Algorithm Interviews for Securing Jobs and Career Transitions","draft":false,"keywords":["Coding test","Algorithm Interview","Employment"],"slug":"/coding-test-with-python","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"Python for Coding Tests"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Clean Python, Robust Backend","permalink":"/en/blog/python-backend-flask"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Why Do the Best Teams Stick to the Basics?","permalink":"/en/blog/the-ideal-team-player"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post was written as part of the Hanbit Media \\"I am a Reviewer\\" activity, where I was provided with the book.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2021](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2021.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/coding-test-with-python.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162243077&orderClick=LAG&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: *This Is the Coding Test for Getting a Job with Python*  \\n- Author: Na Dongbin  \\n- Publisher: Hanbit Media  \\n- Release Date: August 5, 2020  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nNowadays, coding tests have become a must-pass hurdle for job seekers trying to enter companies. While some companies don\u2019t require them, most use coding tests as a screening step before interviews. Back in the day, people might have struggled alone with books like *Algorithm Problem-Solving Strategies*, but now there are many resources like this book to help prepare for job-oriented coding tests\u2014something I\u2019m grateful for.  \\n\\nI was especially pleased to see that the author is Na Dongbin, whom many might recognize from his YouTube videos on coding. Since I prepared for coding tests using C++, I thought, *\u201cI won\u2019t get a chance to read this book,\u201d* but this program gave me the opportunity. I\u2019ve referenced his [YouTube lectures](https://www.youtube.com/c/dongbinna/videos) and [his blog, \\"Glasses Developer\\"](https://ndb796.tistory.com/), which are highly recommended for anyone studying or wanting to get into coding.  \\n\\nThis book is also part of Hanbit Media\u2019s **\\"This Is\\"** series. I remember studying Ubuntu Linux from an older edition of this series, and it\u2019s great to see the series rebranded with a fresh, modern look.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Analysis of Recent Coding Tests  \\n\\nThis isn\u2019t just a generic algorithm problem-solving book\u2014it\u2019s tailored for job seekers preparing for coding tests. Just as high school students analyze past exam papers, it\u2019s essential to understand the trends in coding test questions.  \\n\\nThe book analyzes problem types from major companies\u2019 coding tests between 2016\u20132020, guiding readers on how to prepare and highlighting the latest trends. The appendix even includes past problems from Kakao and Samsung Electronics, which will be especially helpful for those targeting specific companies.  \\n\\n### Career Guidance  \\n\\nWhile the book focuses on coding tests, it also offers broader career advice. It doesn\u2019t dive deep into interview prep for specific roles, but it does cover general hiring processes, common technical interview formats, and how to prepare for them. For example, it explains typical recruitment stages at major companies and what to study for technical interviews.  \\n\\n### A Very Friendly Book  \\n\\nAs the title suggests, this book uses Python. However, the [GitHub repository](https://github.com/ndb796/python-for-coding-test) also provides source code in C++ and Java\u2014a thoughtful gesture for those who prefer other languages. The author\u2019s effort in supporting multiple languages is impressive.  \\n\\nThe book\u2019s friendliness doesn\u2019t stop there. The author also offers free YouTube lectures that cover not just Python but also C++ and Java implementations. I remember binge-watching his videos the day before a coding test\u2014it was a lifesaver!  \\n\\n## Appendix & Helpful Content  \\n\\nThe author includes everything a job seeker might need: study plans, how to use this book effectively, and even a crash course on Python basics for those unfamiliar with the language.  \\n\\nModern coding tests often go beyond standard algorithm problems. Some companies include development-based tasks or unexpected challenges during video interviews. The appendix addresses this by covering REST API calls and JSON parsing\u2014skills tested in Kakao\u2019s coding exams. It explains the concepts and shows how to implement them in Python, making it a practical guide.  \\n\\n## Target Audience  \\n\\nI can\u2019t promise that *this single book will guarantee a perfect coding test score and a smooth transition to interviews*\u2014test outcomes depend on many factors, including the questions and your condition on the day. However, I believe this book covers about half of what you need to know for coding test prep.  \\n\\nI recommend it to **aspiring developers just starting their job search**. The book is packed with insights that make you think, *\u201cI wish I\u2019d known this earlier.\u201d* Reading books is a way to fast-track others\u2019 experiences and useful information. Even if you\u2019re not a job seeker, I\u2019d suggest **computer science students read this early**\u2014it could have made my own job search much smoother."},{"id":"/the-ideal-team-player","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/the-ideal-team-player","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-08-20-the-ideal-team-player/the-ideal-team-player.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-08-20-the-ideal-team-player/the-ideal-team-player.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Why Do the Best Teams Stick to the Basics?","description":"The 3 Secrets of Team Players Who Help Organizations Grow","date":"2021-08-20T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-08-20","description":"The 3 Secrets of Team Players Who Help Organizations Grow","draft":false,"keywords":["Corporate culture","Organizational culture","Growth"],"slug":"/the-ideal-team-player","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Why Do the Best Teams Stick to the Basics?"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Python for Coding Tests","permalink":"/en/blog/coding-test-with-python"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Web Optimization Using Machine Learning","permalink":"/en/blog/ml-with-web-optimization"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![\ucc45](../assets/review/the-ideal-team-player.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9788965962762&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: *The Ideal Team Player: How to Recognize and Cultivate the Three Essential Virtues*\\n- Author: Patrick M. Lencioni (\ud328\ud2b8\ub9ad \ub80c\uc2dc\uc624\ub2c8)\\n- Translator: \uc720\uc815\uc2dd\\n- Publisher: \ud750\ub984\ucd9c\ud310\\n- Release Date: August 24, 2018\\n\\n## Why I Read This Book\\n\\nRecently, I saw a job posting from a company that linked to their Notion page. The page had a dedicated section for recommended reading. I\u2019d been focusing on tech books lately and wanted to branch out into other topics. The list included books on startups, human relationships, and more\u2014all relevant to someone working at a startup. With 10 options, I had to narrow it down.\\n\\nMy first criterion was **whether the book was available at the library**\u2014buying would mean waiting for delivery and spending money. Second, **would it help me now?** While reviewing startup job postings, I realized I needed to understand different company cultures better. While technical skills are crucial, many startups also prioritize cultural fit. I had other reasons too, but I\u2019ll skip those to keep this concise.\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### The Model\\n\\nThe book introduces a model centered on three traits: **humility, hunger, and smarts**, visualized as a Venn diagram. These aren\u2019t as simple as they sound\u2014each has nuanced layers explored in Part 2. Whether you\u2019re a team member or leader, reflecting on these traits could be valuable.\\n\\nAre these **non-negotiable core values?** Not necessarily. Every company and team has different priorities. But if you\u2019re aiming for strong teamwork, growth, or even success, these qualities are worth considering. \\n\\nPart 2 dives deeper, explaining how people with (or without) these traits behave. It also offers practical advice: interview questions for hiring, evaluation criteria for current employees, and strategies for developing missing traits. If you\u2019re thinking of adopting this model, this section is gold.\\n\\n### Storytelling\\n\\nThis book stands out for its narrative approach. Instead of dry theory, it weaves a story about **Jeff**, a reluctant successor who takes over his uncle\u2019s construction business. As he tackles company challenges and hires new talent, the model comes to life. The characters and their dynamics make the concepts easier to grasp\u2014and the storytelling keeps it engaging.\\n\\n## Who Should Read This\\n\\nTo sum up: Don\u2019t feel pressured to adopt these traits as rigid values. Discuss and align with your team first. That said, this book is ideal for:  \\n- Anyone curious about **how companies build culture** and what they look for in hires.  \\n- Those who want to **infer unspoken hiring criteria** (since most companies don\u2019t spell it out).  \\n- Readers interested in **organizational culture**\u2014it\u2019s a worthwhile read without regrets.  \\n\\nIf you\u2019re exploring team dynamics or culture, give it a shot!"},{"id":"/ml-with-web-optimization","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/ml-with-web-optimization","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-07-22-ml-with-web-optimization/ml-with-web-optimization.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-07-22-ml-with-web-optimization/ml-with-web-optimization.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Web Optimization Using Machine Learning","description":"A/B testing, metaheuristics, multi-armed bandit algorithms, and Bayesian optimization","date":"2021-07-22T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-07-22","description":"A/B testing, metaheuristics, multi-armed bandit algorithms, and Bayesian optimization","draft":false,"keywords":["Probability","Statistics","A/B testing"],"slug":"/ml-with-web-optimization","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Web Optimization Using Machine Learning"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Why Do the Best Teams Stick to the Basics?","permalink":"/en/blog/the-ideal-team-player"},"nextItem":{"title":"Deep Learning from Scratch","permalink":"/en/blog/deep-learning-from-scratch"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity, where the book was provided for review purposes.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2021](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2021.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/ml-with-web-optimization.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162244357&orderClick=LAG&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: *Machine Learning for Web Optimization*  \\n- Author: Shuhei Iitsuka (Iitsuka Shuhei)  \\n- Translator: Yeonsu Kim  \\n- Publisher: Hanbit Media  \\n- Release Date: June 7, 2021  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nI believe *probability and statistics* are essential mathematical foundations for machine learning. That\u2019s why I took a university course on the subject and studied independently with books to deepen my understanding. I felt confident I could tackle this book.  \\n\\nThe subtitle also mentions *A/B testing*\u2014a topic I\u2019ve been eager to explore in detail as I study web backend development and data analysis. Additionally, the idea of applying machine learning concepts I\u2019ve learned to web optimization intrigued me, making this book a compelling choice.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\n### Web Optimization  \\n\\nThrough my machine learning studies, I\u2019ve built a foundation in probability, statistics, and optimization theory. This book shows how to apply those concepts practically, focusing on *how machine learning can be used for web optimization*. It uses examples like A/B testing and demonstrates how Bayesian inference can determine whether option A or B performs better. While the focus is on application, it doesn\u2019t skip essential theory\u2014key algorithms and statistical concepts are well explained. Chapter 7 on *Bayesian optimization* was particularly challenging yet fascinating.  \\n\\n### Appendix  \\n\\nThe book includes an appendix covering computational methods needed to understand the calculations discussed. If you find certain sections difficult, the appendix is a helpful reference. For potential buyers, I recommend checking the appendix first to ensure the mathematical level is manageable before purchasing.  \\n\\n### Code  \\n\\nThe code is provided as Jupyter Notebooks and assumes execution on Google Colab\u2014a convenient setup for learners. However, the sample code is bundled into a single file, which made it cumbersome to navigate. Organizing it by chapter would have improved usability, especially for readers who want to run all examples.  \\n\\n### Recommended Audience  \\n\\n- Web engineers interested in statistics or machine learning  \\n- Web marketing professionals or marketers  \\n- Those fascinated by machine learning applications, especially human-computer interaction  \\n\\nWhile the book specifies its target audience, I\u2019d emphasize that it\u2019s not an introductory text. Topics like multi-armed bandits, Bayesian inference, and regression require prior knowledge in statistics or machine learning. The title itself\u2014*Machine Learning for Web Optimization*\u2014implies it\u2019s about *applying* machine learning, not learning it from scratch. I strongly recommend this book for readers with foundational ML experience."},{"id":"/deep-learning-from-scratch","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/deep-learning-from-scratch","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-07-19-deep-learning-from-scratch/deep-learning-from-scratch.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-07-19-deep-learning-from-scratch/deep-learning-from-scratch.md","title":"Deep Learning from Scratch","description":"Deep Learning Theory and Implementation with Python","date":"2021-07-19T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-07-19","description":"Deep Learning Theory and Implementation with Python","draft":false,"keywords":["Deep learning","Neural network","CNN"],"slug":"/deep-learning-from-scratch","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"Deep Learning from Scratch"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Web Optimization Using Machine Learning","permalink":"/en/blog/ml-with-web-optimization"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Kim Sang-hyeong\'s Renowned Lecture: Mastering SQL","permalink":"/en/blog/conquest-sql"}},"content":"## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book cover to visit the Kyobobook store!\\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/deep-learning-from-scratch.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9788968484636&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: \ubc11\ubc14\ub2e5\ubd80\ud130 \uc2dc\uc791\ud558\ub294 \ub525\ub7ec\ub2dd (Deep Learning from Scratch)\\n- Author: Koki Saitoh (\uc0ac\uc774\ud1a0 \uace0\ud0a4)\\n- Translator: \uac1c\uc55e\ub9f5\uc2dc\\n- Publisher: Hanbit Media\\n- Release Date: 2017-01-03\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\nIt\u2019s been 4 years since this book was first published. I discovered it when I started learning Python as a freshman in college. Deep learning was booming at the time, and I wanted to study AI because I thought I could create something like AlphaGo. But I was too busy with schoolwork and club activities, and since I\u2019d never studied linear algebra, I gave up on reading it. After finishing my third year (the \\"death year\\"), I finally had the time to pick it up.\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### A Great Book for Deep Learning Beginners\\n\\nThis book consistently ranks high on bestseller lists for computer science books across online stores. The fact that a 4-year-old book still holds its ground speaks to its clear explanations and recognition as a quality resource. Many deep learning books have been published since the field exploded, but I still believe none are better for beginners than this one.\\n\\nWhat sets it apart from typical deep learning books is its approach: it uses NumPy to implement concepts from scratch in Python, without relying on libraries like TensorFlow or PyTorch\u2014just as the title suggests. This hands-on method helps ideas stick in your memory better than jumping straight into high-level frameworks.\\n\\nAnother standout feature is its use of Python scripts instead of Jupyter Notebooks. While the code would work in notebooks too, structuring implementations in Python files with an object-oriented approach was a valuable experience I really appreciated.\\n\\n### References\\n\\nThe references are neatly organized like academic papers. I found this a huge advantage, though it might frustrate readers who prefer spoon-fed explanations. Many want books to meticulously detail every concept, but this one expects you to dive into the references for deeper dives. If you\u2019re unfamiliar with research papers, it might slow your progress. For me, though, it felt like a roadmap for further study.\\n\\n### Future Studies\\n\\nChapter 8 doesn\u2019t include implementations\u2014it provides a broad overview of deep learning and suggests keywords for future exploration. Without this guidance, readers might struggle to decide which areas to focus on next. It\u2019s incredibly helpful, covering most keywords you\u2019d encounter in deep learning. I highly recommend googling these terms after reading.\\n\\n## Recommended Readers\\n\\nI\u2019d recommend this book to anyone curious about deep learning. It offers hands-on implementations from the ground up and lays a solid foundation for computer vision. It\u2019s excellent for beginners\u2014though don\u2019t stick to easy reads forever; challenge yourself! While older books are often skipped, this one remains a gem despite its age."},{"id":"/conquest-sql","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/conquest-sql","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-06-20-conquest-sql/conquest-sql.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-06-20-conquest-sql/conquest-sql.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Kim Sang-hyeong\'s Renowned Lecture: Mastering SQL","description":"From core machine learning and deep learning algorithms to GANs and reinforcement learning!","date":"2021-06-20T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-06-20","description":"From core machine learning and deep learning algorithms to GANs and reinforcement learning!","draft":false,"keywords":["SQL","Oracle","MSSQL","MariaDB","Famous Lectures  \\n*(or)*  \\nRenowned Lectures"],"slug":"/conquest-sql","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Kim Sang-hyeong\'s Renowned Lecture: Mastering SQL"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Deep Learning from Scratch","permalink":"/en/blog/deep-learning-from-scratch"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Machine Learning Textbook with Python, Scikit-learn, and TensorFlow","permalink":"/en/blog/python-machine-learning"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media *I am a Reviewer* activity, where I was provided with the book.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2021](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2021.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/conquest-sql.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162244241&orderClick=LAG&Kc=)\\n\\n- **Title:** Conquering SQL by Kim Sang-hyeong  \\n- **Author:** Kim Sang-hyeong  \\n- **Publisher:** Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date:** May 1, 2021  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\nThis book, like the one I read in April, was chosen to deepen my SQL knowledge. While *Learning SQL* focused on MySQL, this one is based on Oracle\u2014a database frequently used in large enterprises. That made me curious, as I\u2019d only worked with MySQL and PostgreSQL before. Plus, the book compares Oracle, MSSQL, and MariaDB, which I thought was great for beginners exploring different SQL dialects.\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### About the Author\\n\\nThe author runs a site called [SoEn](http://www.soen.kr/) (though it seems inaccessible now). If you\u2019ve studied C/C++ or Windows API, you might recognize them\u2014especially from their book *Mastering Windows API*. Their teaching style felt familiar and approachable throughout this book.\\n\\n### Diverse SQL Dialects\\n\\nOracle DB is widely used in large corporations. This book doesn\u2019t just teach queries\u2014it includes hands-on exercises with GUI-based environments. I appreciated how it guided me through setting up Oracle, MSSQL, and MariaDB environments, highlighting their differences. Normally, you\u2019d need separate books for each, but this one streamlined the learning process.\\n\\n### Personal Regret\\n\\nThe only downside was the lack of coverage on PostgreSQL. Many startups now prefer it, so I wished it had been included instead of MariaDB. That said, it\u2019s still a minor quibble.\\n\\n## Recommended Audience\\n\\nThis book is ideal for anyone wanting a structured SQL foundation or curious about multiple SQL dialects. It\u2019s especially useful for those interested in Oracle DB, commonly used in large enterprises. Whether you\u2019re a beginner or looking to expand your skills, this book offers a practical and comparative approach."},{"id":"/python-machine-learning","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/python-machine-learning","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-06-10-python-machine-learning/python-machine-learning.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-06-10-python-machine-learning/python-machine-learning.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Machine Learning Textbook with Python, Scikit-learn, and TensorFlow","description":"From machine learning and deep learning core algorithms to GANs and reinforcement learning!","date":"2021-06-10T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-06-10","description":"From machine learning and deep learning core algorithms to GANs and reinforcement learning!","draft":false,"keywords":["Machine Learning","TensorFlow","Scikit-learn","Jupyter Notebook"],"slug":"/python-machine-learning","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Machine Learning Textbook with Python, Scikit-learn, and TensorFlow"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Kim Sang-hyeong\'s Renowned Lecture: Mastering SQL","permalink":"/en/blog/conquest-sql"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Do It! Django + Bootstrap: The Ultimate Guide to Python Web Development","permalink":"/en/blog/Do-it-django-bootstrap"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written after receiving the book as part of the **15th Developer Reviewer** activity by Gilbut.  \\n:::\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobook website!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/python-machine-learning.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791165215187&orderClick=LAG&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: *Machine Learning Textbook with Python, Scikit-learn, and TensorFlow*  \\n- Authors: Sebastian Raschka, Vahid Mirjalili  \\n- Translator: \ubc15\ud574\uc120 (Park Haesun)  \\n- Publisher: Gilbut  \\n- Release Date: March 31, 2021  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\nI read this book as part of the **15th Developer Reviewer** program by Gilbut. I found out about this activity by following their [Facebook page](https://www.facebook.com/gbitbook/). As a soon-to-be fourth-year student, I was under pressure to work on a machine learning project for my graduation thesis, so I wanted to study machine learning more deeply in advance.  \\n\\nIn previous courses like linear algebra, numerical analysis, and probability & statistics, my professors assigned machine learning tasks without me realizing it, and I struggled a lot. Back then, I was too focused on completing the assignments to study properly. That\u2019s why I wanted to learn through this book and applied for this program.  \\n\\nI was tempted by many other books, but machine learning was my top priority. I\u2019ll review other books when I get the chance. Honestly, I didn\u2019t expect to be selected, but I\u2019m thrilled that I was!  \\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### Translation\\n\\nThis book is a translation of *[Python Machine Learning 3rd Edition](https://www.amazon.com/Python-Machine-Learning-scikit-learn-TensorFlow/dp/1789955750)*. The translator, \ubc15\ud574\uc120 (Park Haesun), is well-known for translating and writing machine learning books. His translations are clean, and the **translator\u2019s notes** are particularly helpful. These notes show how meticulously he approaches translation, and I found them very useful.  \\n\\nI was initially worried that technical terms might be fully translated into Korean, but that wasn\u2019t the case. Key terms are bolded and accompanied by their English equivalents in parentheses\u2014this was a great touch. Since machine learning often involves English resources, having both languages side-by-side is a big help.  \\n\\nThe book also provides practical code examples in Jupyter Notebook or Colab, and even the code comments are translated into Korean. This level of detail in translation is impressive.  \\n\\n### Concepts & Practice\\n\\nThis book strikes a great balance between theory and practice. At 868 pages, it\u2019s a hefty textbook that thoroughly explains concepts and provides detailed code examples. I especially appreciated the sections where algorithms were implemented from scratch using only NumPy.  \\n\\nEach chapter begins with an overview of what\u2019s to come, which shows the author\u2019s thoughtful approach. The book also explains the historical context and real-world applications of algorithms, making it easier to follow. It\u2019s not just a dry, technical manual.  \\n\\nFor deeper dives, the book references research papers and supplementary materials. I also liked that it covers modern topics like GANs and transformers.  \\n\\nIf you need extra help or want to reinforce your understanding, check out the translator\u2019s [YouTube lectures](https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLJN246lAkhQiEc-QvvGzUneCWuRnCNKgU). He\u2019s already uploaded up to Chapter 5, and they\u2019re very helpful.  \\n\\n## Target Audience\\n\\nHonestly, this book might be challenging for complete beginners. If you enjoy diving into complex concepts from the start, it\u2019s a great choice\u2014just be prepared to take your time.  \\n\\nYou don\u2019t need to know machine learning inside-out, but some familiarity with Python libraries like NumPy, Matplotlib, and Pandas is recommended. I was only somewhat familiar with those, and TensorFlow, Scikit-learn, and SciPy were new to me, but I managed by looking up references.  \\n\\nIf you\u2019ve taken courses in linear algebra, probability & statistics, or numerical analysis\u2014or if you\u2019re curious about machine learning algorithms\u2014this book will be both educational and engaging. As mentioned in the **practical review** section, the [official GitHub repository](https://github.com/rickiepark/python-machine-learning-book-3rd-edition) for the 3rd edition is well-maintained, so you can follow along with the code examples using Colab or Jupyter Notebook. Just know the basics of those tools beforehand!"},{"id":"/Do-it-django-bootstrap","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Do-it-django-bootstrap","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-06-09-do-it-django-bootstrap/Do-it-django-bootstrap.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-06-09-do-it-django-bootstrap/Do-it-django-bootstrap.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Do It! Django + Bootstrap: The Ultimate Guide to Python Web Development","description":"Everything You Need to Know About Server-Side JavaScript for the Modern Web","date":"2021-06-09T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-06-09","description":"Everything You Need to Know About Server-Side JavaScript for the Modern Web","draft":false,"keywords":["Django","Python","Bootstrap","Docker"],"slug":"/Do-it-django-bootstrap","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Do It! Django + Bootstrap: The Ultimate Guide to Python Web Development"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Machine Learning Textbook with Python, Scikit-learn, and TensorFlow","permalink":"/en/blog/python-machine-learning"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Complete Guide to Node & Express in One Book","permalink":"/en/blog/web-development-with-node-and-express"}},"content":"## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![\ucc45](../assets/review/Do-it-Django-Bootstrap.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791163032069&orderClick=LET&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: Do it! Django + Bootstrap: The Ultimate Guide to Python Web Development\\n- Authors: Lee Seong-yong, Kim Tae-gon\\n- Publisher: Easys Publishing\\n- Release Date: 2021-01-18\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n## Intro\\n\\nI once saw people using Django in \\"Like Lions\\" and thought it looked like an easy stack for web beginners to study. Back then, I failed to learn Django because I didn\'t know how to study programming on my own. I guess I just wanted someone to spoon-feed me the knowledge. Anyway, after that, I gave up on Django and started learning other stacks.\\n\\nRecently, I decided to study Django again and was considering what to learn from when I found out two Django books were released this year: `Do it! Jump to Django` and `Do it! Django + Bootstrap: The Ultimate Guide to Python Web Development`.\\n\\nThere were other options like the official Django documentation and *Two Scoops of Django*, but I didn\u2019t read the latter because it\u2019s in English and would take too long. There\u2019s a Korean translation, but it was published in 2016 and uses older versions, so I didn\u2019t choose it.\\n\\nIn the end, I decided to read one of the Do it! books and chose `Do it! Django + Bootstrap: The Ultimate Guide to Python Web Development` because it uses Docker. I also referenced [Jump to Django](https://wikidocs.net/book/4223) from Wikidocs while reading.\\n\\n## Book Review\\n\\n### Web Development, Deployment, and Operations\\n\\nThis book is 640 pages thick, which might make you think, \\"Why is a Django book so long?\\" But considering it includes all the code, covers Django, Bootstrap, and deployment, 640 pages isn\u2019t even enough. I think it\u2019s amazing that they managed to fit everything into one book\u2014and this is the biggest strength of this book, in my opinion.\\n\\n### Technologies Used\\n\\nThe book says it teaches you to build a blog, but you\u2019re actually creating a community platform. You\u2019ll implement login functionality, posting, and comments\u2014basically CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) operations commonly used in Django.\\n\\n#### Frontend\\n\\nThe frontend section teaches the necessary parts of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript and how to use Bootstrap to style your app. Personally, I think it would have been better if they covered React instead of Bootstrap, but that would have made the book over 1,000 pages. Also, React is harder for beginners who haven\u2019t mastered HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, so Bootstrap was a practical choice for quick implementation.  \\n\\nNote that the Bootstrap version used in the book is outdated, so you might need to refer to the official documentation if you use the latest version.\\n\\n#### Git\\n\\nEvery time you write code, you commit and push to GitHub. This was helpful because it showed me when to upload changes during a project.\\n\\n#### Docker, AWS\\n\\nThis was my first time using Docker, so it was a bit challenging. The book gives a good introduction to deploying with Docker. It also uses AWS Lightsail, which I tried for the first time and found user-friendly for AWS beginners. Plus, the first month is free, so there\u2019s no need to worry about costs (though I\u2019ve had unexpected charges from AWS before, but it\u2019s probably not a big deal).\\n\\n#### TDD\\n\\nTest-Driven Development (TDD) is something I\u2019d only heard about from Java developers. This book introduced me to TDD in Django, and it takes up a significant portion of the content. You write test code before implementing features, which was the most fun part for me.\\n\\n#### Django\\n\\nThis is the most important section. You\u2019ll create a project, implement and use the MTV pattern, FBV, CBV, one-to-many, and many-to-many relationships. The code is thoroughly explained, which impressed me. The book also introduces useful Django packages. The only downside is the lack of content on Django REST framework.\\n\\n### Concepts\\n\\nWhile not super detailed, this book covers more than the basics of Django. As the subtitle says, \\"Learn Web Development by Building,\\" it explains concepts step-by-step while building a project. So, you might find some concepts a bit lacking in depth.\\n\\nThe authors sometimes intentionally include mistakes to show common pitfalls. There are also \\"Good to Know\\" sections that explain additional concepts, which were interesting to read.\\n\\n### Struggles\\n\\nMy biggest worry while reading was, \\"Will I struggle because of version differences?\\" I had the same concern when I first learned Django. In the end, I did face some deployment issues due to updated package versions and my lack of Docker experience. Thankfully, the author\u2019s [Do It Django](https://doitdjango.com/) site had a Q&A section that helped me resolve problems.\\n\\nThis was the first time I had to refer to so many external documents while reading a book. I checked GitHub issues, official package docs, Stack Overflow, and more. That\u2019s why this book took me longer to read.\\n\\nI also tried using Bootstrap 5.0.1 instead of the book\u2019s version (4.5) and had to rely heavily on the official Bootstrap documentation.\\n\\nFortunately, Django version differences didn\u2019t cause major issues.  \\n\\nSince I bought the first edition, there were indentation and typo errors, which added to the struggles. As someone who reads books carefully, I found this a bit disappointing.\\n\\n## Recommended Readers\\n\\nIf you want to try the latest versions, I recommend studying HTML, CSS, and JavaScript from Opentutorials (\uc0dd\ud65c\ucf54\ub529) first. For Django, basic Python knowledge (functions, classes, inheritance) is a must. While web scraping experience would be helpful, it\u2019s not required.\\n\\nThis book is great for anyone who wants to experience web development with Python. You\u2019ll quickly go through development, deployment, and operations."},{"id":"/web-development-with-node-and-express","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/web-development-with-node-and-express","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-05-20-web-development-with-node-and-express/web-development-with-node-and-express.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-05-20-web-development-with-node-and-express/web-development-with-node-and-express.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Complete Guide to Node & Express in One Book","description":"Everything You Need to Know About Server-Side JavaScript for the Modern Web","date":"2021-05-20T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-05-20","description":"Everything You Need to Know About Server-Side JavaScript for the Modern Web","draft":false,"keywords":["Node.js","Express","Backend","JavaScirpt"],"slug":"/web-development-with-node-and-express","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Complete Guide to Node & Express in One Book"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Do It! Django + Bootstrap: The Ultimate Guide to Python Web Development","permalink":"/en/blog/Do-it-django-bootstrap"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Amazon Web Services (AWS) Discovery Book","permalink":"/en/blog/AWS-Discovery-Book"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis post was written as part of the Hanbit Media \\"I am a Reviewer\\" activity, where I received the book for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2021](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2021.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book cover to visit the [Kyobobook](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr) page!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/web-development-with-node-and-express.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162244227&orderClick=LAG&Kc=)\\n\\n- **Title**: Web Development with Node and Express (2nd Edition)  \\n- **Author**: Ethan Brown  \\n- **Translator**: Han Seon-yong  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: May 1, 2021  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nI read this book as part of Hanbit Media\u2019s \\"I am a Reviewer 2021\\" program. Every month, the books provided for this activity are always excellent. This time, the May review candidates were all topics I wanted to study, making the selection process really tough. I ultimately chose *Statistics for Data Science (2nd Edition)*, *High-Performance Python (2nd Edition)*, and *Web Development with Node and Express (2nd Edition)*. If I get the chance, I\u2019ll also review the other books on the list here.  \\n\\n## Book Review  \\n\\nAt first, I wondered if a single book could truly cover both Node.js and Express comprehensively. However, after reading it, I found it to be a solid resource for self-study\u2014provided you have some prior knowledge and can supplement with online research.  \\n\\nThe book goes beyond just building websites, guiding you through deployment processes. It also simulates real-world environments for testing, connects to databases, and touches on maintenance planning. Along the way, it briefly covers REST APIs, HTTP, QA, cookies, and more. Later chapters even introduce databases and React, so having some familiarity with these topics would be helpful.  \\n\\nThe book efficiently delivers core concepts without diving too deeply into every detail. While this might appeal to experienced Node.js developers, I found it challenging as a beginner with only basic JavaScript knowledge.  \\n\\nTo save pages, the book includes only essential code snippets. For the full project structure, refer to the author\u2019s [GitHub repository](https://github.com/EthanRBrown/web-development-with-node-and-express-2e).  \\n\\n## Target Audience  \\n\\nI had no prior Node.js experience and only a little JavaScript knowledge. If you\u2019re in a similar situation, this book might be tough without additional resources. The publisher\u2019s review also notes that readers should have **intermediate JavaScript** and **beginner-level Node & Express** skills.  \\n\\nOf course, you can still tackle it with extra effort\u2014Google searches, other courses, or supplementary books. This book is best suited for those who understand Node.js concepts but lack project experience, especially if you want to practice deploying a full web application."},{"id":"/AWS-Discovery-Book","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/AWS-Discovery-Book","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-05-14-AWS-Discovery-Book/AWS-Discovery-Book.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-05-14-AWS-Discovery-Book/AWS-Discovery-Book.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Amazon Web Services (AWS) Discovery Book","description":"Understanding the concept of cloud services and trying to set them up yourself  \\n\\n(Note: The translation is provided as requested, returning only the translation without additional text.)","date":"2021-05-14T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-05-14","description":"Understanding the concept of cloud services and trying to set them up yourself  \\n\\n(Note: The translation is provided as requested, returning only the translation without additional text.)","draft":false,"keywords":["AWS","Cloud","Amazon Web Service"],"slug":"/AWS-Discovery-Book","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Amazon Web Services (AWS) Discovery Book"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Complete Guide to Node & Express in One Book","permalink":"/en/blog/web-development-with-node-and-express"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Learning SQL","permalink":"/en/blog/Learning-SQL"}},"content":"## \u2139\ufe0f Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/aws-discovery-book.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000000833222)\\n\\n- Title: AWS Discovery Book\\n- Author: Kwon Young-hwan\\n- Publisher: Jeongbo Media\\n- Publication Date: 2019-02-10\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## \ud83c\udfac Intro\\n\\nLooking at recent backend developer job postings, more companies are requiring experience in cloud environments. AWS, in particular, is widely used, so companies prefer candidates with AWS experience. As someone aiming to become a backend developer, I wanted to gain hands-on AWS experience, which led me to this book.\\n\\nI thought, **\\"Why read a book when AWS official documentation is so comprehensive?\\"** But I wasn\u2019t confident I could go through all the documentation, so I wanted a book that let me quickly practice core concepts. I also considered books like *[Hands-on AWS Networking for Beginners](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000060612654)* and *[AWS Infrastructure Guide for Easier Service Operations](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000001766358)*, but since this one was available in the e-library, I borrowed it. The *[Hands-on AWS Networking for Beginners](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000060612654)* book was published in late 2020, so it was a tough choice. I plan to read the others when I get the chance.\\n\\n## \ud83d\udcd6 Book Review\\n\\n### Structure\\n\\nEach chapter follows the structure: concept \u2192 relevant AWS service \u2192 hands-on practice \u2192 epilogue. The epilogue at the end of each chapter includes helpful insights or historical context, which I found quite interesting. For example, in Chapter 8 on Auto Scaling, I wondered, **\\"Is Auto Scaling actually usable? Does anyone really use it?\\"** The epilogue mentioned how Devsisters used it for their Cookie Run service. Real-world examples like this made the technology more intriguing.\\n\\nThis book is a great introductory guide to AWS concepts. While it doesn\u2019t go extremely in-depth, it covers all the key services you\u2019d expect. There are tons of hands-on exercises, each explained in detail with images. Beginners can follow along from AWS sign-up to EC2, S3, VPC, and more. However, since the book was published in 2019, some menu names or labels might differ. You can supplement with online research for those parts.\\n\\nChapters 12 and 13 explain how to prepare for AWS certifications, including exam registration and study resources. The visual explanations are helpful, though I\u2019m not sure if the methods are still valid after two years. Those interested in AWS certifications can still find this section useful.\\n\\n### Free Tier Utilization\\n\\nWhen I first studied AWS, I wondered, **\\"Is payment required for practice?\\"** It turns out simple exercises don\u2019t need billing, and this book uses the **AWS Free Tier**, so there\u2019s no need to worry. If you follow the steps carefully, you won\u2019t incur charges. The book emphasizes terminating or stopping services after each practice to avoid unexpected costs.\\n\\n## \ud83e\uddd1\u200d\ud83c\udfeb Target Audience\\n\\nI recommend this book to beginners who want hands-on AWS experience. It guides you through practical exercises without trial and error, and the image-heavy explanations make it user-friendly. However, since this is a cloud-focused book, basic CS knowledge (terminal usage, networking) is necessary. While it briefly explains some concepts, it doesn\u2019t go into depth\u2014so be ready to Google unfamiliar terms. That\u2019s how I read it, and it motivated me to study CS more seriously."},{"id":"/Learning-SQL","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Learning-SQL","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-04-17-learning-sql/Learning-SQL.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-04-17-learning-sql/Learning-SQL.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Learning SQL","description":"Mastering Data: From Generation to Retrieval and Manipulation","date":"2021-04-17T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-04-17","description":"Mastering Data: From Generation to Retrieval and Manipulation","draft":false,"keywords":["SQL","RDBMS","MySQL"],"slug":"/Learning-SQL","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Learning SQL"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Amazon Web Services (AWS) Discovery Book","permalink":"/en/blog/AWS-Discovery-Book"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6First Steps with GANs","permalink":"/en/blog/make-your-first-gan"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media \\"I am a Reviewer\\" activity, where I received the book for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2021](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2021.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/Learning-SQL.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000001810371)\\n\\n- **Title**: Learning SQL  \\n- **Author**: Alan Beaulieu  \\n- **Translators**: Soo-Mi Ryu, Hee-Jeong Song  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: March 30, 2021  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## \ud83c\udfac Intro  \\n\\nAlthough I\u2019m a computer engineering major, I\u2019ve never properly studied databases. My department leans more toward Computer Engineering than Computer Science, and the database course is scheduled for my final semester. However, while studying web backends, I naturally felt the need to learn SQL and thought, *\\"I should study this someday.\\"* Fortunately, I got the chance to participate in Hanbit Media\u2019s \\"I am a Reviewer\\" program and was able to read this book.  \\n\\n## \ud83d\udcd6 Book Review  \\n\\n### SQL  \\n\\nAs the title suggests, this book is about learning SQL. There are many types of SQL databases, such as MySQL, Oracle Database, IBM DB2, Microsoft SQL Server, and PostgreSQL. This book focuses on MySQL, which is one of the most widely used. While there are occasional examples from other SQL dialects, the syntax is largely similar, so it\u2019s not a big issue.  \\n\\n### Hands-On Environment  \\n\\n![katacoda](mysql-environment-katacoda.jpg)  \\n\\nMost SQL books require you to create tables, insert data, or download a pre-built database for practice. This book uses the Sakila database, a sample database developed by MySQL for tutorials and examples.  \\n\\nSetting up the environment requires installing MySQL and importing the Sakila database, which can be challenging for beginners. To help, the original publisher, O\'Reilly, provides a [Katacoda](https://www.katacoda.com/) environment for hands-on practice. This was one of the most impressive features, making it very convenient for newcomers.  \\n\\n![wsl2](mysql-environment-wsl2.jpg)  \\n\\nFor those who prefer to set up their own environment, the book supports that too. I used WSL2 (Windows Subsystem for Linux 2) to set up MySQL. While the book uses terminal-based queries, I chose not to use MySQL Workbench and followed along in the terminal instead.  \\n\\n### More Than Just an Introduction  \\n\\nThis book doesn\u2019t stop at basic SQL queries. It starts with the fundamentals and progresses to advanced topics like partitioning, clustering, sharding, and big data. It even introduces Apache Drill, an open-source tool that debuted in 2015.  \\n\\n### A Study-Friendly Book  \\n\\nAt 455 pages and 18 chapters, the book is thick but well-structured for gradual learning. Reading one chapter a day means finishing it in just 18 days\u2014manageable without feeling overwhelmed.  \\n\\nEach chapter ends with **\\"Learning Check Practice Problems\\"**, which I found very helpful. Many technical books provide examples but lack review exercises. This one includes problems with answers in the appendix, making it great for self-assessment.  \\n\\nAdditionally, the book offers plenty of practical code examples, often explaining when and why to use specific queries. It\u2019s not just a reference\u2014it\u2019s a guide for applying SQL in real scenarios.  \\n\\n## \ud83d\udd16 Recommended Readers  \\n\\nOccasionally, a chapter introduces concepts from other sections before they\u2019re fully explained. For this reason, readers who have at least some prior SQL experience will benefit more.  \\n\\nIf you\u2019re completely new to SQL, I recommend supplementing this book with other beginner-friendly resources. For those with some background, working through the examples and exercises will be an excellent way to reinforce your skills."},{"id":"/make-your-first-gan","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/make-your-first-gan","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-03-20-make-your-first-gan/make-your-first-gan.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-03-20-make-your-first-gan/make-your-first-gan.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6First Steps with GANs","description":"From PyTorch Neural Network Basics to Generating Celebrity Faces","date":"2021-03-20T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-03-20","description":"From PyTorch Neural Network Basics to Generating Celebrity Faces","draft":false,"keywords":["Neural network","Deep learning","GAN","PyTorch"],"slug":"/make-your-first-gan","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6First Steps with GANs"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Learning SQL","permalink":"/en/blog/Learning-SQL"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6First Steps in Neural Networks","permalink":"/en/blog/make-your-own-neural-network"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media \\"I am a Reviewer\\" activity, where the book was provided for review.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am a Reviewer 2021](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2021.jpg)\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to visit the Kyobobook store!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/Make-your-first-gan.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162243954&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: GAN \uccab\uac78\uc74c  \\n- Author: Tariq Rashid  \\n- Translator: Ko Rak-yun  \\n- Publisher: Hanbit Media  \\n- Publication Date: March 10, 2021  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Intro  \\n\\nI read this book as part of Hanbit Media\u2019s \\"I am a Reviewer 2021\\" program. There were many great books to choose from for the March reviews, and I selected *Satoshi\u2019s Whitepaper*, *GAN \uccab\uac78\uc74c*, and *Refactoring 2nd Edition*. I\u2019ll skip explaining why I excluded the others this time.  \\n\\nWhile studying deep learning, I stumbled upon GANs and tried to learn more, but got stuck due to the math and complex concepts. That\u2019s when I came across this book and decided to give it a shot.  \\n\\n## Book Overview  \\n\\nThis book focuses on the essentials of GANs\u2014it doesn\u2019t cover every aspect but provides a solid foundation. That\u2019s why it was especially helpful for me.  \\n\\nIt doesn\u2019t just explain concepts\u2014it walks you through implementing them step-by-step using PyTorch. You can find example codes on the [author\u2019s GitHub](https://github.com/makeyourownneuralnetwork) to build your own GAN neural network.  \\n\\nFamiliarity with Colab and basic PyTorch usage will make reading this book smoother. Since the focus is on GANs, the book only covers the necessary parts of Colab and PyTorch, not every detail.  \\n\\nAlso, reading the author\u2019s previous book, *\uc2e0\uacbd\ub9dd \uccab\uac78\uc74c* (*Make Your Own Neural Network*), before this one is highly recommended. While this book briefly covers neural networks, the earlier work explains them in greater detail. When I learned this was a sequel, I borrowed *\uc2e0\uacbd\ub9dd \uccab\uac78\uc74c* from the library and read it first.  \\n\\nThe book is divided into three main parts:  \\n- **Part 1**: Basic concepts and foundations for implementing GANs.  \\n- **Part 2**: Core GAN concepts and building your own.  \\n- **Part 3**: Advanced applications like Convolutional GANs and Conditional GANs.  \\n\\nThe natural progression makes it easy for beginners to follow.  \\n\\n## Recommended Readers  \\n\\nThis book is great for those who are interested in deep learning or machine learning but find some concepts too challenging. Since I fit this category, I can confidently say it\u2019s accessible. The explanations are simple and friendly, with plenty of visuals, making it beginner-friendly.  \\n\\nThink of it as an introductory guide to AI. While it doesn\u2019t cover every GAN variant, it lays a strong foundation for deeper, more specialized study later.  \\n\\n## Summary  \\n\\n**I recommend this book to beginners who are new to deep learning, curious about GANs, or have hit a roadblock in their studies.**  \\n\\nOf course, this is just my opinion\u2014take it as a reference!"},{"id":"/make-your-own-neural-network","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/make-your-own-neural-network","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-03-10-make-your-own-neural-network/make-your-own-neural-network.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-03-10-make-your-own-neural-network/make-your-own-neural-network.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6First Steps in Neural Networks","description":"\\"Understanding Neural Networks and Deep Learning Basics\u2014Even for Math Hatters\\"  \\n\\n(Note: \\"\uc218\ud3ec\uc790\\" literally means \\"math avoiders\\" or \\"people who give up on math,\\" often translated as \\"math hatters\\" for a natural tone. The title balances technical accuracy with approachability.)","date":"2021-03-10T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-03-10","description":"\\"Understanding Neural Networks and Deep Learning Basics\u2014Even for Math Hatters\\"  \\n\\n(Note: \\"\uc218\ud3ec\uc790\\" literally means \\"math avoiders\\" or \\"people who give up on math,\\" often translated as \\"math hatters\\" for a natural tone. The title balances technical accuracy with approachability.)","draft":false,"keywords":["Neural network","Deep learning","Neural network"],"slug":"/make-your-own-neural-network","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6First Steps in Neural Networks"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6First Steps with GANs","permalink":"/en/blog/make-your-first-gan"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6A New Way to Organize Work and Daily Life: Notion","permalink":"/en/blog/clean-up-with-notion"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\n\\n\\n## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/Make-your-own-neural-network.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9788968483509&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: First Step in Neural Networks  \\n- Author: Tariq Rashid  \\n- Translator: Kyo-seok Song  \\n- Publisher: Hanbit Media  \\n- Release Date: April 3, 2017  \\n\\n## Why I Read This Book  \\n\\nAs part of the `I am a Reviewer 2021` activity, I received the book `First Step in GANs` for my March review. While reading it, the introduction mentioned that the author\u2019s previous work, `First Step in Neural Networks`, would be helpful to read before diving into GANs. Curious, I wondered if I should visit another library or buy the book\u2014but fortunately, my university\u2019s e-library had it, so I borrowed it.  \\n\\n## Book Overview  \\n\\nThis book gently and clearly explains neural networks, a topic familiar to anyone interested in deep learning. Its subtitle is *Understanding How Neural Networks Work and Deep Learning Basics\u2014Even for Math Hatters*. You might ask, *How can someone who hates math understand deep learning?* But this book genuinely avoids complex formulas, relying only on basic arithmetic.  \\n\\nA downside is that the lack of mathematical depth might leave you wondering, *Why is this used?* While the explanations are friendly, some mathematical concepts are glossed over without deeper exploration, which was slightly disappointing. However, since these gaps can be filled with additional research, I still recommend it as an excellent introductory deep learning book.  \\n\\nYou can finish it in a day or two\u2014it\u2019s that easy to follow, with plenty of visual aids that speed up understanding.  \\n\\nI was amazed that such an accessible book was published back in 2017. If only I\u2019d known about it earlier, my deep learning journey might have been smoother.  \\n\\nThe book starts with foundational concepts and gradually introduces examples in a `Jupyter Notebook` environment (though it refers to IPython\u2014Jupyter works fine too). Setup details aren\u2019t thoroughly covered, but since we can Google solutions, it\u2019s manageable. Check out the [author\u2019s GitHub](https://github.com/makeyourownneuralnetwork) for code examples.  \\n\\n## Intended Audience  \\n\\nWhether you\u2019re a major or not, this is a great first read for anyone new to deep learning. It\u2019s a helpful primer before taking courses like Andrew Ng\u2019s *Machine Learning* on Coursera or Professor Sung Kim\u2019s *Deep Learning for Everyone*.  \\n\\n## Summary  \\n\\n*I believe this book will be very helpful for anyone\u2014whether a major or not\u2014who is just starting with deep learning.*  \\n\\nOf course, this is just my opinion\u2014take it as a reference!"},{"id":"/clean-up-with-notion","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/clean-up-with-notion","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-02-25-clean-up-with-notion/clean-up-with-notion.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-02-25-clean-up-with-notion/clean-up-with-notion.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6A New Way to Organize Work and Daily Life: Notion","description":"\\"From organizing thoughts to boosting work productivity and managing collaboration\u2014all in one with Notion!\\"","date":"2021-02-25T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-02-25","description":"\\"From organizing thoughts to boosting work productivity and managing collaboration\u2014all in one with Notion!\\"","draft":false,"keywords":["Notion","Collaboration","Cleanup  \\n(Note: The Korean word \\"\uc815\ub9ac\\" can also mean \\"organization,\\" \\"tidy up,\\" or \\"summary\\" depending on context. If you provide more details, I can give a more precise translation.)  \\n\\nSince the instruction specifies to return **ONLY the translation** and no additional explanation, here is the direct translation:  \\n\\n**Cleanup**","Record  \\n(Note: The Korean word \\"\uae30\ub85d\\" translates to \\"record\\" in English. If you provide additional context or a full sentence, I can offer a more precise translation.)  \\n\\nSince the instruction specifies to return **only the translation**, here is the minimal response:  \\n\\nRecord"],"slug":"/clean-up-with-notion","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6A New Way to Organize Work and Daily Life: Notion"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6First Steps in Neural Networks","permalink":"/en/blog/make-your-own-neural-network"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Delicious Design Photoshop & Illustrator CC 2021","permalink":"/en/blog/delicious-design-Ps-Ai"}},"content":"## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/How-to-clean-up-with-notion.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791190665476&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: \uc5c5\ubb34\uc640 \uc77c\uc0c1\uc744 \uc815\ub9ac\ud558\ub294 \uc0c8\ub85c\uc6b4 \ubc29\ubc95 \ub178\uc158 Notion (*A New Way to Organize Work and Life with Notion*)\\n- Authors: \uc804\uc2dc\uc9c4, \uc774\ud574\ubd04 (Seonjin Jeon, Haebom Lee)\\n- Publisher: \uc81c\uc774\ud38d (Jpub)\\n- Release Date: 2020-10-16\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Why I Read It\\n\\nI was already using Notion with interest and had gotten somewhat used to it, but I wasn\u2019t satisfied with myself because I was only using templates others had made. I was thinking about creating my own templates when I found this book at the library and decided to read it.\\n\\nAlso, since I run a blog, I thought I was familiar with Markdown syntax and using Notion well\u2014but I wasn\u2019t utilizing Notion\u2019s unique features like shortcuts or databases. I wanted to study those aspects, which is why I picked up this book.\\n\\n## Notion\\n\\nIt\u2019s an app so productive that even Evernote users switch to it. Most companies use Notion for documentation, and you\u2019ll often see job postings formatted as Notion documents.\\n\\nSomehow, it\u2019s become a *de facto* essential tool for those in IT. And one of the biggest reasons people use it is because it\u2019s visually appealing\u2014the clean design plays a big role.\\n\\nIt also offers various features, supports widgets, allows easy sharing, and makes documentation straightforward. Recently, a Korean version was launched, and plenty of templates are available for those who find the features challenging.\\n\\nWhile there\u2019s a Pro plan, all basic features are free. That\u2019s a huge draw. College students can also switch to an Education account for Pro Plan access. With these advantages, there\u2019s no reason not to use it.\\n\\nOf course, Notion can be confusing at first\u2014you might not know where to start. But if you have a clear purpose, it becomes a powerful tool.\\n\\n## Drawbacks\\n\\nLoading times get slower as data grows, which can be frustrating. However, the book offers solutions for this.\\n\\nFor those unfamiliar with tools like PowerPoint or Excel, there might be a learning curve. I think such users should first learn how to use the features and see how others apply them.\\n\\n## The Book\\n\\nI recommend this book to anyone unsure how to use Notion effectively. It provides various use cases and explains Notion\u2019s features in detail\u2014almost like a manual for those struggling with the tool. It\u2019s beginner-friendly.\\n\\nI found **Chapter 03** and **Chapter 04** especially helpful, which covered databases. This part can be challenging for beginners, but once you grasp it, using Notion becomes much easier.\\n\\n## How I Use It\\n\\nI use Notion for diaries, book logs, and organizing study notes. On YouTube or other platforms, I see people using it more creatively and aesthetically\u2014there are lots of fun templates to inspire you.\\n\\nYou can also check out how others use Notion in the [Notion.so Korean User Group](https://www.facebook.com/groups/notion.so). The group shares community pages and template sites, so it\u2019s worth exploring.\\n\\n## Final Thoughts\\n\\n`If you want to live a productive life, Notion can be a fun tool to try.`\\n\\nThis is just my opinion\u2014take it as a reference!"},{"id":"/delicious-design-Ps-Ai","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/delicious-design-Ps-Ai","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-02-18-delicious-design-Ps-Ai/delicious-design-Ps-Ai.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-02-18-delicious-design-Ps-Ai/delicious-design-Ps-Ai.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Delicious Design Photoshop & Illustrator CC 2021","description":"A graphic design primer that anyone can easily learn and effectively apply","date":"2021-02-18T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-02-18","description":"A graphic design primer that anyone can easily learn and effectively apply","draft":false,"keywords":["Photoshop","Illustrator","Designer","Delicious Design"],"slug":"/delicious-design-Ps-Ai","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Delicious Design Photoshop & Illustrator CC 2021"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6A New Way to Organize Work and Daily Life: Notion","permalink":"/en/blog/clean-up-with-notion"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6I am a LINE developer.","permalink":"/en/blog/LINE-developer"}},"content":":::info  \\nThis review was written as part of the Hanbit Media \\\\<I am a Reviewer\\\\> activity, for which the book was provided.  \\n:::\\n\\n![I am Reviewer 2021](../assets/I-am-reviewer-2021.jpg)  \\n\\n## Book Info  \\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/delicious-design-Ps-Ai.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162243848&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)  \\n\\n- **Title**: Delicious Design Photoshop & Illustrator CC 2021  \\n- **Authors**: Red Whale, Yoon Isara  \\n- **Publisher**: Hanbit Media  \\n- **Release Date**: 2021-01-18  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}  \\n\\n## I am Reviewer 2021  \\n\\nThis book was provided through my participation in Hanbit Media\u2019s book review program, **\\\\<I am Reviewer 2021\\\\>**. I think this program is really helpful for anyone interested in IT. Last year, I missed the application period and felt disappointed, so I was thrilled to join this year.  \\n\\nHonestly, I never expected to be selected. My GitHub Jekyll blog isn\u2019t like Naver Blog, Tistory, or Brunch\u2014platforms with high traffic. Plus, I tend to write factual reviews rather than just praising books. Most such programs seem to favor influencers or high-traffic sites, so I applied with a \\"why not try?\\" mindset.  \\n\\nBeing selected showed me that **\\\\<I am Reviewer\\\\>** isn\u2019t just for established influencers. I\u2019m grateful to **Hanbit Media** for giving me this self-development opportunity.  \\n\\nIn this program, you select three preferred books from a list, and one is randomly assigned. I chose *Learning Azure*, *Serious Python*, and *Delicious Design Photoshop & Illustrator*.  \\n\\n## Why Did I Choose This Book?  \\n\\nWhile I aim to be a developer, I\u2019ve always been interested in popular computer programs and studied Photoshop CS4 before.  \\n\\nOf course, programming is a developer\u2019s core skill, but I\u2019ve always wanted to be a developer with knowledge in other fields too. This book let me revisit Photoshop and learn Illustrator.  \\n\\nThe other two books aren\u2019t relevant here, so I\u2019ll skip explaining them.  \\n\\n## Free Trial Experience  \\n\\nI used Adobe\u2019s 7-day free trial to finish the book quickly. While student discounts make Adobe affordable, I feared I\u2019d lose motivation if I took too long. So I thought, **\\"Let\u2019s study hard for 7 days, finish the book, and write a proper review.\\"**  \\n\\nIt was exhausting to focus only on this book while pausing other studies, but I didn\u2019t want to quit halfway. I treated it like a challenge\u2014no half-hearted reading. I reviewed every step carefully to avoid missing anything.  \\n\\n## Is This Book Suitable for Beginners?  \\n\\nYes. Compared to other Photoshop books (often over 600 pages), this one is 532 pages\u2014shorter but still comprehensive. The pages are filled with images, making it visually engaging.  \\n\\nThe explanations are concise, paired with step-by-step images, which makes learning easier. Hanbit Media also runs a **\\\\<Delicious Design Study Group\\\\>** where you can join a community or ask questions on the Q&A board if you get stuck.  \\n\\n## What I Liked  \\n\\n1. **Updated Features**  \\n   Adobe switched from standalone software (like CS6) to the subscription-based CC model, with annual updates. This book highlights new features in CC 2021 compared to CC 2020.  \\n\\n   While Adobe\u2019s official docs are the fastest way to check updates, this book summarizes them for those who find the official guides overwhelming.  \\n\\n2. **Example Files Provided**  \\n   Beginners often lack practice images, but this book offers downloadable example files and completed project files for comparison.  \\n\\n3. **Photoshop + Illustrator in One Book**  \\n   Some might prefer separate books for deeper dives, but I appreciated the concise, one-book approach. It\u2019s great for beginners who want an overview before specializing.  \\n\\n   The previous *Delicious Design CC 2020* editions were split, but this 2021 version combines both\u2014ideal for casual learners.  \\n\\n4. **Practical Applications, Not Just Features**  \\n   - **Photoshop**: The portrait retouching techniques were especially useful for social media posts.  \\n   - **Illustrator**: Designing logos, ads, and SNS pages gave me hands-on skills for real-world projects.  \\n\\n## What Could Be Improved  \\n\\n1. **English UI vs. Korean Users**  \\n   The book uses the English version of the software, which might confuse Korean users unfamiliar with the English interface.  \\n\\n   While the **\\"Feature Deep Dive\\"** sections explain everything in detail, some readers might still struggle with the language barrier. For casual users or hobbyists, a Korean UI version could be more accessible.  \\n\\n2. **Lack of Video Lectures**  \\n   While not essential, video tutorials would have made hands-on learning easier.  \\n\\n   My results sometimes differed slightly from the book\u2019s examples\u2014probably due to differences in tool adjustments or drag distances. Design is subjective, so having video guidance could help beginners grasp the nuances.  \\n\\n## Personal Reflections While Studying  \\n\\nThe most surprising feature was the **AI-powered Neural Filter**. With just a few clicks, it can change a person\u2019s age, expression, gaze, or even colorize black-and-white photos\u2014tasks that once required manual editing.  \\n\\nThis reminded me of my image processing projects where I implemented filters from scratch. It also made me realize how fast technology evolves. I want to become someone who can create such tools, not just use them. That\u2019s why I\u2019m drawn to programming\u2014it\u2019s about innovation beyond existing tools.  \\n\\n## Final Rating  \\n\\n**Recommended for**:  \\n- Those who studied Photoshop before but need a refresher.  \\n- Beginners new to Photoshop or Illustrator.  \\n\\n**Not Recommended for**:  \\n- Those aiming to master the software solely through this book. It\u2019s an **introductory guide**, not a comprehensive expert-level manual.  \\n\\nThese are my personal thoughts\u2014take them as a reference!"},{"id":"/LINE-developer","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/LINE-developer","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-02-07-LINE-developer/LINE-developer.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-02-07-LINE-developer/LINE-developer.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6I am a LINE developer.","description":"The Challenges, Opportunities, and Growth Journey of Line\'s 12 Development Experts  \\n(Note: \\"\uac1c\ubc1c\uace0\uc218\\" is translated as \\"Development Experts\\" to convey expertise, though a more literal translation would be \\"Development Masters\\" or \\"Development Gurus.\\" The title is adjusted for natural English flow while preserving meaning.)  \\n\\n**Final Answer**  \\n*The Challenges, Opportunities, and Growth Journey of Line\'s 12 Development Experts*  \\n\\n(If a more literal tone is preferred: *The Challenges and Opportunities, and Growth-Oriented Development Life of Line\'s 12 Development Masters*)  \\n\\nSince the user requested **ONLY the translation**, the first version is provided as the primary answer.","date":"2021-02-07T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-02-07","description":"The Challenges, Opportunities, and Growth Journey of Line\'s 12 Development Experts  \\n(Note: \\"\uac1c\ubc1c\uace0\uc218\\" is translated as \\"Development Experts\\" to convey expertise, though a more literal translation would be \\"Development Masters\\" or \\"Development Gurus.\\" The title is adjusted for natural English flow while preserving meaning.)  \\n\\n**Final Answer**  \\n*The Challenges, Opportunities, and Growth Journey of Line\'s 12 Development Experts*  \\n\\n(If a more literal tone is preferred: *The Challenges and Opportunities, and Growth-Oriented Development Life of Line\'s 12 Development Masters*)  \\n\\nSince the user requested **ONLY the translation**, the first version is provided as the primary answer.","draft":false,"keywords":["LINE","Developer","Growth","Study"],"slug":"/LINE-developer","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6I am a LINE developer."},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Delicious Design Photoshop & Illustrator CC 2021","permalink":"/en/blog/delicious-design-Ps-Ai"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Birth of Unix","permalink":"/en/blog/UNIX-history-memoir"}},"content":"## Book Info\\n\\n:::tip  \\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!  \\n:::\\n\\n[![\ucc45](../assets/review/LINE-developer.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162242162&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: I Am a LINE Developer  \\n- Authors: Kang Yunshin, Kim Younghwan, Kim Jaeseok, Kim Jungyeop, Kim Taekju, No Seunghyeon, Park Minwoo, Bae Kwanhwan, Lee Seoyeon, Lee Seungjin, Lee Hongkyu, Ha Taeho  \\n- Publisher: Hanbit Media  \\n- Release Date: 2019-08-23  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}  \\n\\n## Why Did I Read It?  \\n\\nBy now, anyone who reads my book reviews on this blog probably knows: I\u2019ll keep writing why I read each book, even if there\u2019s no particularly interesting reason.  \\n\\nThis book caught my attention when it first came out, but I never got the chance to read it. One day, I visited a different library than usual and found it there. I was curious about developer culture, lifestyles, and things to learn from, so I picked it up.  \\n\\nHonestly, if you\u2019re aiming to become a programmer, wouldn\u2019t you be curious about what a LINE developer\u2019s life is like? People working at other companies might hear about it from colleagues or communities like Blind, but as a regular college student, I was super curious.  \\n\\nIf you\u2019ve read similar books, you know they usually have an introduction. The intro of this book had some really appealing words for aspiring developers, so I had to share:  \\n\\n> \\"If this book can give even a little courage to young people hesitating about their future as developers, telling them \'If you dream, you can do it,\' that would be the greatest joy.\\"  \\n\\n## LINE  \\n\\nWhat comes to mind when you hear \\"LINE\\"?  \\n\\nHonestly, my impression was: *\\"A messenger app more popular in Japan than Korea\\"*\u2014like \\"Japan\u2019s KakaoTalk.\\" I assumed LINE made most of its revenue in Japan, similar to Kakao in Korea.  \\n\\nBut reading this book, I learned LINE operates globally, not just in Japan.  \\n\\nI looked into what else LINE does beyond messaging. They\u2019re involved in healthcare, financial services with cryptocurrency, and Line Friends\u2014so they\u2019re not just famous in Korea but have diverse projects worldwide.  \\n\\n## Attractive Culture  \\n\\nReading this book, I felt LINE is a great place for developers and was envious of those working there.  \\n\\nWhat stood out was their culture of not blaming failures. Everyone makes mistakes, and even a small coding error can disrupt services.  \\n\\nImagine a teammate saying, *\\"It\u2019s my fault for missing that in the code review, even though it was a simple coding error.\\"* How comforting would that be? Not just comforting\u2014it\u2019s deeply grateful. A culture where people don\u2019t waste time blaming but solve problems together. Is that common in most companies?  \\n\\nAlso, after resolving an incident, they immediately write a postmortem report and review it. I thought postmortems were standard, but documenting them as reports? That\u2019s impressive.  \\n\\nMost companies might skip documentation due to busy schedules, but LINE avoids misunderstandings and makes information searchable for future tasks.  \\n\\nOther perks: $2,000 Herman Miller chairs, a dedicated Developer Relations team to attract top talent, and an environment focused on development.  \\n\\nI wondered, *\\"Isn\u2019t LINE the perfect place for developers who want to grow while coding comfortably?\\"*  \\n\\nIf you\u2019re into hacking, you might know Grayhash (now Graylab at LINE) and experts like Lee Seungjin. For junior developers, having mentors like them is a huge advantage.  \\n\\nThere are more great aspects, but I\u2019ll stop here. The takeaway: LINE seems like a place where developers can thrive.  \\n\\n## The Book  \\n\\nThis book showcases the lives of 12 LINE developers and introduces the company\u2019s culture.  \\n\\nIt features stories from non-CS majors, evangelists, open-source managers, etc. I enjoyed reading about evangelists and open-source roles\u2014fields I hadn\u2019t considered before.  \\n\\n## Final Thoughts  \\n\\n`LINE is truly a company where developers can work comfortably.`  \\n\\n`Job seekers or aspiring developers will find this book intriguing.`  \\n\\nThese are just my thoughts\u2014take them with a grain of salt!"},{"id":"/UNIX-history-memoir","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/UNIX-history-memoir","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-01-28-UNIX-history-memoir/UNIX-history-momoir.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-01-28-UNIX-history-memoir/UNIX-history-momoir.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Birth of Unix","description":"The untold stories of the geniuses who created the operating systems that changed the world","date":"2021-01-28T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-01-28","description":"The untold stories of the geniuses who created the operating systems that changed the world","draft":false,"keywords":["UNIX","Brian Kernighan","Bell Laboratories"],"slug":"/UNIX-history-memoir","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Birth of Unix"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6I am a LINE developer.","permalink":"/en/blog/LINE-developer"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Effective Programming Study Methods","permalink":"/en/blog/successful-programming"}},"content":"## \u2139\ufe0f Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![\ucc45](../assets/review/UNIX-history-and-memoir.jpg)](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewKor.laf?ejkGb=KOR&mallGb=KOR&barcode=9791162243282&orderClick=LEa&Kc=)\\n\\n- Title: The Birth of UNIX\\n- Author: Brian W. Kernighan\\n- Translator: Ha Sung-chang\\n- Publisher: Hanbit Media\\n- Release Date: August 3, 2020\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## \ud83c\udfac Intro\\n\\nI borrowed this book from a local library near my home. I first saw it on Hanbit Media\u2019s Facebook page. At the time, I was taking an operating systems course at university, so I thought I\u2019d like to read it\u2014but I was too busy during the semester to do so. I hadn\u2019t given it much thought until I stumbled upon it at the library. I wondered, \u201cWhy is this in a public library?\u201d but ended up borrowing it anyway.\\n\\n## \ud83d\udcd6 Book Review\\n\\n### What Kind of Book Is This?\\n\\nThis is a memoir by the author, Brian Kernighan. He\u2019s one of the co-authors of [The C Programming Language](http://www.kyobobook.co.kr/product/detailViewEng.laf?mallGb=ENG&ejkGb=ENG&barcode=9780131103627), a book familiar to anyone who\u2019s studied C from its original text. He wrote it with Dennis Ritchie, the creator of the C language.\\n\\nThe book shares interesting anecdotes about the author\u2019s experiences at Bell Labs and his fellow developers. It mentions legendary programmers like Dennis Ritchie, who co-created Unix with Ken Thompson (now co-developer of Go at Google), and highlights how brilliant and impactful Bell Labs was at the time. It also traces the history of Unix\u2014how it was created and evolved.\\n\\nThis book truly deserves the word \u201cawe-inspiring.\u201d At times, the Unix development process reads like a novel. The book also includes emails and interviews with colleagues, which I found an engaging way to present history. I was amazed at how much detail the author remembered\u2014even if he kept records, I wondered, \u201cHow did he document all this?\u201d\\n\\n### Serious About Writing\\n\\nThe developers at Bell Labs had a serious attitude toward writing, and they supported each other\u2019s critiques, even with management\u2019s backing. That\u2019s probably why they could publish books that influenced developers worldwide. As a student who studied languages developed by these great programmers and read their books, I was deeply impressed by this aspect.\\n\\nI\u2019m a college student aiming to become a developer, but I also love writing. That\u2019s why I run a blog where I review books and organize what I\u2019ve learned, hoping to help others. Moving forward, I want to keep practicing writing and become a developer who leaves knowledge for the world through my blog.\\n\\n### Fun Anecdotes\\n\\nThe book is full of entertaining stories. For example, the name \u201cUnix\u201d was a pun on [Multics (Multiplexed Information and Computing Service)](https://ko.wikipedia.org/wiki/%EB%A9%80%ED%8B%B1%EC%8A%A4). The original name was UNICS, but AT&T lawyers didn\u2019t like it because it sounded like \u201ceunuchs\u201d (\ub0b4\uc2dc). \\n\\nThere\u2019s also a story about Douglas McIlroy, who created the `malloc` library often used in C programming. If you\u2019ve studied C, you\u2019ll find this particularly interesting. Another fun fact: the system call for creating files in UNIX, `creat`, was actually a typo by Ken Thompson.\\n\\nI also learned that the BSD License, commonly used today (like on GitHub alongside the MIT License), originated from Unix. The book is packed with useful and fun tidbits like these. This is just what I remember now\u2014there are many more interesting stories. If you\u2019re aspiring to be a developer, this is a fun book to read when you\u2019re bored.\\n\\n## \ud83d\udd16 Recommended Readers\\n\\nI don\u2019t recommend this book for those just starting to learn programming. It\u2019s best for those who have studied operating systems or systems programming. I took an OS course but skimmed through it, and even then, this book was quite challenging. It might be even harder for those without that background.\\n\\nMy university had a systems programming course, so I could somewhat understand the code snippets and terms in the book. I\u2019m not sure how others would fare\u2014if you come across unfamiliar code, Google it diligently. Take your time, enjoy the read, and dive in!"},{"id":"/successful-programming","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/successful-programming","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-01-07-successful-programming/successful-programming.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-01-07-successful-programming/successful-programming.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Effective Programming Study Methods","description":"**Person and Programmer #7: Reflecting on the Path of a Programmer**  \\n\\n*(Note: The original text appears to be a title or heading. If additional context or content is provided, the translation can be refined accordingly.)*","date":"2021-01-07T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-01-07T00:00:00.000Z","description":"**Person and Programmer #7: Reflecting on the Path of a Programmer**  \\n\\n*(Note: The original text appears to be a title or heading. If additional context or content is provided, the translation can be refined accordingly.)*","draft":false,"keywords":["Study methods","Programming","Growth"],"slug":"/successful-programming","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Effective Programming Study Methods"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6The Birth of Unix","permalink":"/en/blog/UNIX-history-memoir"},"nextItem":{"title":"Markdown Summary","permalink":"/en/blog/markdown"}},"content":"## \u2139\ufe0f Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/How-to-sutdy-programming.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000001624697)\\n\\n- Title: How to Succeed in Programming Study\\n- Authors: Park Jae-sung, Ko Jong-beom, Nam Jae-chang, Park Ji-hyun\\n- Publisher: Roadbook\\n- Publication Date: 2018-09-10\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## \ud83c\udfac Intro\\n\\nI happened to find this book while visiting the library and was immediately drawn to the table of contents. Looking back, I realized it was written by Park Jae-sung, who leads Woowahan TechCourse (part of Woowa Brothers, the company behind Baemin), and I wanted to read it.  \\n\\nWhile I enjoyed creating new things and learning languages, there was a period when I lost interest in programming due to an overwhelming flood of knowledge. Now, I\u2019ve moved past that phase and study consistently because I find it fun. However, I still struggle with questions like **\\"How should I study programming?\\"** and **\\"How should I approach computer science?\\"** I hoped this book might offer some answers.  \\n\\n## \ud83d\udcd6 Book Review\\n\\n### Insights from Professional Programmers\\n\\nThis book contains diverse experiences from working programmers. It\u2019s helpful for anyone wondering how to study programming. I really appreciated being able to indirectly experience their journeys.  \\n\\nAlthough the book lists four authors, it actually includes interviews with 11 individuals. Each shares how they studied programming, the importance of algorithms and math, their motivations, and moments of confusion. These stories were incredibly insightful.  \\n\\n### Thought-Provoking Content\\n\\nThe book covers general programming study methods and makes you rethink **\\"Why programming studies fail.\\"** While it\u2019s best to avoid discouragement, every field has moments of struggle. This book is a great read for those times.  \\n\\n## Diverse Stories\\n\\nThe table of contents labels chapters as **\\"Chapter n\\"**, but the back cover lists them as **\\"Story #n\\"**.  \\n\\n**Story #1** is by Park Jae-sung (JavaJigi), a renowned educator at Woowahan TechCourse and Woowahan TechCamp. This section helped me reflect on how to approach programming and even reach some conclusions. It was very helpful.  \\n\\n**Story #2** explains Agile methodologies. I\u2019d only heard the term before but didn\u2019t know much. The examples made it engaging, and it sparked my interest to learn more.  \\n\\n**Story #3** is great if you enjoy writing or reading. It compares coding to communication.  \\n\\n**Story #4** is especially useful for non-majors. Many universities now teach programming as a general requirement in the first year, focusing on **computational thinking** with Python. This chapter feels like an advanced version of that course, explaining how to synergize basic programming skills with your major. Even non-majors will find it valuable.  \\n\\n## \ud83d\udd16 Recommended Audience\\n\\nIf asked, **\\"Is this book suitable for someone new to programming?\\"**, I\u2019d say **\\"No.\\"** While reading it is a challenge, I don\u2019t recommend it for beginners. It\u2019s better suited for those who\u2019ve already grappled with their growth and doubts.  \\n\\nAs mentioned earlier, whether you\u2019re a major or non-major aiming to become a developer, this book is worth your time. Students especially should read it, as they rarely get to hear from senior developers outside of work."},{"id":"/markdown","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/markdown","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2021-01-01-markdown/markdown.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2021-01-01-markdown/markdown.md","title":"Markdown Summary","description":"Organizing Markdown for Getting Used to Documentation  \\n\\n(Note: The original Korean text is quite brief, so the translation reflects the core meaning while ensuring natural English flow. If you\'d like to expand this into a full guide or have additional content to include, I\'d be happy to refine it further!)  \\n\\n**Alternative (more literal):**  \\n*Organizing Markdown to Become Familiar with Documentation*  \\n\\nLet me know if you\'d like a more detailed version or specific sections added!","date":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Blog","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/blog"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2021-01-01","description":"Organizing Markdown for Getting Used to Documentation  \\n\\n(Note: The original Korean text is quite brief, so the translation reflects the core meaning while ensuring natural English flow. If you\'d like to expand this into a full guide or have additional content to include, I\'d be happy to refine it further!)  \\n\\n**Alternative (more literal):**  \\n*Organizing Markdown to Become Familiar with Documentation*  \\n\\nLet me know if you\'d like a more detailed version or specific sections added!","draft":false,"keywords":["Markdown","Blog"],"slug":"/markdown","tags":["Blog"],"title":"Markdown Summary"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Effective Programming Study Methods","permalink":"/en/blog/successful-programming"},"nextItem":{"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Do It! HTML5 + CSS3: The Standard Guide to Web Standards","permalink":"/en/blog/Do-it-html5-css3"}},"content":"Restarting my blog after a long time, I realized I\u2019ve gotten rusty with Markdown, so I\u2019m documenting and practicing it.\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## What is Markdown?\\n\\nMarkdown is a syntax for editing the formatting of plain text documents. It\u2019s used in GitHub README files, online documentation, or when editing documents with plain text editors. Documents written in Markdown can be easily converted into other formats like HTML. In short, it\u2019s a language that helps developers document things easily.\\n\\n## When You Want to Show the Syntax Itself\\n\\nIf you add a backslash (`\\\\`) before Markdown syntax, it will display the syntax as-is.\\n\\n```\\n\\\\### Hello\\n```\\n\\n\\\\### Hello\\n\\n## Code Blocks\\n\\n```\\n\\\\`\\\\`\\\\`language name  \\ncode  \\n\\\\`\\\\`\\\\`\\n```\\n\\n```c\\n#include <stdio.h>\\n\\nint main(void)\\n{\\n    printf(\\"Hello World!\\");\\n}\\n```\\n\\n## Text Formatting\\n\\n```\\n*Italic (slanted)*\\n_Italic (slanted)_\\n**Bold**\\n__Bold__\\n~~Strikethrough~~\\n```\\n\\n*Italic*  \\n_Italic_  \\n**Bold**  \\n__Bold__  \\n~~Strikethrough~~  \\n\\nFor underlines or text colors, use HTML and CSS.\\n\\n## Headers\\n\\nYou can indicate heading sizes from `h1` to `h6` using `#` to `######`.\\n\\n```\\n# This is a h1\\n## This is a h2\\n### This is a h3\\n#### This is a h4\\n##### This is a h5\\n###### This is a h6\\n```\\n\\n# This is a h1  \\n## This is a h2  \\n### This is a h3  \\n#### This is a h4  \\n##### This is a h5  \\n###### This is a h6  \\n\\n######## This is a h7 \u2192 Not supported.  \\n\\nYou might notice a horizontal line under `h2`\u2014this is defined in the SCSS of the minimal-mistakes theme. I\u2019m still deciding whether to keep or modify this.\\n\\n## Lists\\n\\n### Ordered Lists\\n\\n1. 1st  \\n2. 2nd  \\n3. 3rd  \\n\\n```\\n1. 1st  \\n1. 2nd  \\n1. 3rd  \\n```\\nYou can write them as usual with `1.`, but even if you repeat the same number like in the code block above, it will still display as a numbered list in descending order.\\n\\n### Unordered Lists (Bullets: `*`, `+`, `-`)\\n\\n```\\n- I  \\n  + want  \\n  * to eat  \\n    + raw fish  \\n    + chicken\\n```\\n\\n- I  \\n  + want  \\n  * to eat  \\n    + raw fish  \\n    + chicken  \\n\\nYou can use a single character for bullets, or mix them as shown in the example.\\n\\n## Line Breaks\\n\\nIn HTML, you use `<br>`, but in Markdown, press the **Space bar twice** and then **Enter** to create a line break.\\n\\n```\\nI\'m hungry  \\nI want to eat\\n```\\n\\nI\'m hungry  \\nI want to eat  \\n\\n## Horizontal Lines\\n\\nThis is equivalent to `<hr>` in HTML. It\u2019s often used to separate sections\u2014like a page break. It can be written as `---`, `***`, etc., and some irregular syntax seems to be accepted too.\\n\\n```\\n* * *  \\n***  \\n******  \\n- - -  \\n---  \\n___  \\n```\\n\\n---\\n***\\n\\n## Blockquotes\\n\\nUse `>` to denote blockquotes. For line breaks in nested quotes, use the same line break method as above.\\n\\n```\\n> Quote  \\n>> Quote inside a quote  \\nSecond quote inside  \\n>>> Quote inside a quote inside a quote\\n```\\n\\n> Quote  \\n>> Quote inside a quote  \\nSecond quote inside  \\n>>> Quote inside a quote inside a quote  \\n\\n## Links\\n\\nHere are ways to add links to documents. There may be other methods too.\\n\\n```\\nLink showing URL: <https://www.google.com/>  \\n\\nLink with URL in description: [Google](https://www.google.com/)  \\n\\nLink to header in the same file: [Blockquotes](#blockquotes)  \\n```\\n\\n[https://www.google.com/](https://www.google.com/)  \\n[Google](https://www.google.com/)  \\n[Blockquotes](#blockquotes)  \\n\\n### How to Create a Link to a Header\\n\\n1. Copy the heading text (excluding the `#` symbols).  \\n2. Remove special characters.  \\n3. Replace spaces with `-`.  \\n4. Convert uppercase letters to lowercase.  \\n5. Add a `#` at the beginning of the string.  \\n\\ne.g., \\"## When You Forget or Want to Apply Markdown\\" \u2192 \\"#when-you-forget-or-want-to-apply-markdown\\"\\n\\n## Images\\n\\n```\\n![Profile](profile.jpg)\\n\\n<img src=\\"profile.jpg\\" width=\\"300\\" height=\\"200\\">\\n\\n[![Profile](profile.jpg)](https://teddygood.github.io/)\\n```\\n\\n![Pencil](profile.jpg)\\n\\n[![Pencil](profile.jpg)](https://teddygood.github.io/)\\n\\nThis image is a photo of the moon I took at my university.\\n\\n## Tables\\n\\nYou can create tables using a combination of `|` and `-`.\\n\\n- Alignment:\\n  * Left-aligned |:\u2014|  \\n  * Right-aligned |\u2014:|  \\n  * Center-aligned |:\u2014:|  \\n\\n| Food | Price | Review |  \\n|:---:|---:|---|  \\n| Chicken + Cheese Balls | 25000 | Delicious |  \\n| Rice Noodles | 7000 | Not tasty |\\n\\n## When You Forget or Want to Apply Markdown\\n\\nIn such cases, you can mix Markdown with HTML/CSS. For example, if line breaks aren\u2019t working, you can use the `<br>` tag. If you want to change text color or add underlines, use HTML and CSS.\\n\\n## References\\n\\n- [Markdown](https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/)  \\n- [Wikipedia Markdown](https://ko.wikipedia.org/wiki/%EB%A7%88%ED%81%AC%EB%8B%A4%EC%9A%B4)  \\n- [Complete Markdown Syntax Guide](https://ansohxxn.github.io/blog/markdown/#%EA%B8%80%EC%94%A8-%EC%83%89)  \\n- [How to Use Markdown with Examples](https://theorydb.github.io/envops/2019/05/22/envops-blog-how-to-use-md/#markdown%EC%9D%B4%EB%9E%80)  \\n- [Markdown Writing Guide](https://gist.github.com/ihoneymon/652be052a0727ad59601)"},{"id":"/Do-it-html5-css3","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/blog/Do-it-html5-css3","editUrl":"https://github.com/teddygood/teddygood.github.io/tree/main/blog/2020-12-30-do-it-html5-css3/Do-it-html5-css3.md","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2020-12-30-do-it-html5-css3/Do-it-html5-css3.md","title":"\ud83d\udcd6Do It! HTML5 + CSS3: The Standard Guide to Web Standards","description":"Mastering Data: From Generation to Retrieval and Manipulation","date":"2020-12-30T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Book Review","permalink":"/en/blog/tags/book-review"}],"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Chanho Lee","title":"\ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ubd84\uc57c\ub97c \uacf5\ubd80\ud558\uace0 \uc788\ub294 \ud559\uc0dd","url":"https://github.com/teddygood","imageURL":"https://github.com/teddygood.png","key":"teddygood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"authors":"teddygood","date":"2020-12-30","description":"Mastering Data: From Generation to Retrieval and Manipulation","draft":false,"keywords":["HTML","CSS","web"],"slug":"/Do-it-html5-css3","tags":["Book Review"],"title":"\ud83d\udcd6Do It! HTML5 + CSS3: The Standard Guide to Web Standards"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Markdown Summary","permalink":"/en/blog/markdown"}},"content":"## \u2139\ufe0f Book Info\\n\\n:::tip\\nClick the book image to go to the Kyobobook site!\\n:::\\n\\n[![Book](../assets/review/Do-it-HTML5-CSS3.jpg)](https://product.kyobobook.co.kr/detail/S000001817955)\\n\\n- Title: Do it! HTML5+CSS3 \uc6f9 \ud45c\uc900\uc758 \uc815\uc11d  \\n- Author: Go Kyung-hee  \\n- Publisher: Easys Publishing  \\n- Release Date: 2019-12-27  \\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## \ud83c\udfac Intro\\n\\nI had studied basic HTML and CSS through Opentutorials (\uc0dd\ud65c\ucf54\ub529). Since I first learned C and was new to web programming, I secretly wondered, *\\"Is it really this simple?\\"* Eventually, I decided to buy this book to study more thoroughly. There were other candidates, but this one was ranked highest when I purchased it.\\n\\n## \ud83d\udcd6 Book Review\\n\\n### Is it Suitable for Web Programming Beginners?\\n\\nHonestly, if you\'re completely new to programming, this book might seem too thick to finish. I even paused reading it because it felt overwhelming. I attempted to reread it twice, which shows how challenging it was. Although the explanations are incredibly detailed, I kept thinking, *\\"Do I really need to know all this?\\"*\\n\\nUnless you aim to become an exceptional frontend developer, I don\u2019t think you need to read and practice everything. Of course, if you have plenty of time, studying it thoroughly is great. However, since there are many online lectures, I recommend using this book as a reference\u2014watching lectures first and then consulting the book for specific concepts you want to explore.\\n\\nInitially, I bought this book thinking I\u2019d master HTML and CSS perfectly, but I soon realized that approach wasn\u2019t efficient. Instead, I revisited Opentutorials lectures and skimmed this book for key points.\\n\\n### Recommended Resources Besides This Book\\n\\nIf you\u2019re comfortable reading English, I highly recommend [MDN](https://developer.mozilla.org/ko/) and [w3schools](https://www.w3schools.com/) for HTML and CSS. For simpler learning, check out [Opentutorials](https://opentutorials.org/course/1), [Dream Coding on YouTube](https://www.youtube.com/@dream-coding/featured), and other lectures. Additionally, [Boostcourse](https://www.boostcourse.org/web344) offers helpful courses.\\n\\n## \ud83d\udd16 Target Audience\\n\\nI recommend this book for aspiring web publishers and frontend developers."}]}}')}}]);